{"title_page": "Obi Toppin", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Obi Toppin\n| image = Obi_Toppin.jpg\n| image_size = 260px\n| caption = Toppin in 2020\n| number =\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 9\n| weight_lbs = 220\n| team =\n| league =\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1998|3|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| high_school = \n*[[Heritage High School (Palm Bay, Florida)|Heritage]]<br>([[Palm Bay, Florida]])\n*[[Melbourne Central Catholic High School|Melbourne Central Catholic]]<br>([[Melbourne, Florida]])\n*[[Ossining High School|Ossining]]<br>([[Ossining (village), New York|Ossining, New York]])\n*Mt. Zion Prep<br>([[Baltimore, Maryland]])\n| college = [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton]] (2018\u20132020) \n| highlights = \n*[[List of U.S. men's college basketball national player of the year awards|National College Player of the Year]] (2020)\n*Consensus first-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] ([[2020 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|2020]])\n*[[Karl Malone Award]] winner (2020)\n*[[Atlantic 10 Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|Atlantic 10 Player of the Year]] ([[2019\u201320 Atlantic 10 Conference men's basketball season|2020]])\n*2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Atlantic 10 Conference|Atlantic 10]] ([[2018\u201319 Atlantic 10 Conference men's basketball season|2019]], 2020)\n*Atlantic 10 Rookie of the Year (2019)\n}}\n'''Obadiah Richard \"Obi\" Toppin''' (born March 4, 1998) is an American [[basketball]] player who last played for the [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton Flyers]] of the [[Atlantic 10 Conference]]. Listed at {{convert|6|ft|9|in|m|2}} and {{convert|220|lbs|kg|0}}, he plays the [[power forward (basketball)|power forward]] position.\n\nA native of [[Brooklyn]], Toppin finished high school at [[Ossining High School]] in New York. After receiving no [[NCAA Division I]] offers, he played a postgraduate season at Mt. Zion Preparatory School in [[Maryland]]. As a freshman with the Dayton Flyers, Toppin was named Atlantic 10 Rookie of the Year after leading his team in scoring. He had breakout success in his sophomore season, earning [[Atlantic 10 Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|Atlantic 10 Player of the Year]] and several [[List of U.S. men's college basketball national player of the year awards|national player of the year]] honors.\n\n==Early life and high school==\nToppin was born in [[Brooklyn]] in New York City and originally grew up in the neighborhood of [[Bushwick, Brooklyn|Bushwick]] before moving to [[Melbourne, Florida]]. He attended [[Heritage High School (Palm Bay, Florida)|Heritage High School]] in [[Palm Bay, Florida|Palm Bay]] as a freshman before transferring to [[Melbourne Central Catholic High School]] the next year. Toppin, his mother and younger brother relocated to [[Ossining (village), New York|Ossining, New York]] and enrolled at [[Ossining High School]] going into his junior year.<ref name=\"Eager\">{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/archdeacon-redshirt-freshman-toppin-eager-make-dayton-debut/aSQAiZyosYQdG2m9wSvd2K/|title=Redshirt freshman Toppin eager to make Dayton debut|first=Tom|last=Archdeacon|work=[[Dayton Daily News]]|date=June 10, 2018|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> \n\nHe averaged 20.6 [[Point (basketball)|points]], 8.1 [[Rebound (basketball)|rebounds]], 3 [[Assist (basketball)|assists]] and 3 [[Steal (basketball)|steals]] as a senior during his only year playing [[varsity team|varsity]] at Ossining and led the team to its first conference title in 10 years. Having received no [[NCAA Division I]] offers, Toppin opted to enroll at Mt. Zion Preparatory School in [[Baltimore, Maryland]] for a postgraduate year. He averaged 17 points, eight rebounds and four assists and also grew four inches to {{convert|6|ft|9|in|m|2}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dayton247now.com/sports/dayton-flyers/ud-freshman-toppin-academically-ineligible-for-2017-18-season|title=UD freshman Toppin academically ineligible for 2017\u201318 season|first=James|last=Rider|website=dayton247now.com|date=September 19, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> He committed to play college basketball at the [[University of Dayton]] over offers from [[Rhode Island Rams men's basketball|Rhode Island]], [[Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball|Georgetown]], [[Georgia Bulldogs basketball|Georgia]], [[Texas A&M Aggies men's basketball|Texas A&M]], [[Minnesota Golden Gophers men's basketball|Minnesota]] and [[Texas Tech Red Raiders basketball|Texas Tech]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/sports/columnists/josh-thomson/2017/05/19/thomson-obi-toppins-patience-leads-him-dayton/330563001/|title=Thomson: Patience lands Toppin at Dayton|first=Josh|last=Thompson|work=The Journal News|date=May 19, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/insider/story/_/id/28685100/how-obi-toppin-ended-dayton-other-origin-stories-wooden-award-favorites|title=How Obi Toppin ended up at Dayton and other origin stories around Wooden Award favorites|first=Jeff|last=Borzello|website=[[ESPN.com]]|date=February 13, 2020|access-date=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nToppin [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] his true freshman season after being ruled academically ineligible to play.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2017/09/19/dayton-freshman-toppin-ineligible-for-2017-18-season/|title=Dayton freshman Toppin ineligible for 2017\u201318 season|first=Raphielle|last=Johnson|website=[[NBCSports.com]]|date=September 19, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> As a redshirt freshman, Toppin led the Flyers with 14.4 points per game while averaging 5.6 rebounds per game and was named the [[Atlantic 10 Conference]] Rookie of the Week seven times.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/four-dayton-flyers-honored-atlantic-awards/oE9itI5FYWiShpmroaH0KL/|title=Atlantic 10 awards: Obi Toppin makes Dayton Flyers history|first=David|last=Jablonski|work=Dayton Daily News|date=March 12, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> At the end of the season, Toppin was named the Atlantic 10 Rookie of the Year and to the first team All-Atlantic 10, the first freshman to do so since [[Lamar Odom]] in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailyvoice.com/new-york/mountpleasant/sports/northern-westchesters-obi-toppin-named-atlantic-10-rookie-of-year/749463/|title=Northern Westchester's Obi Toppin Named Atlantic 10 Rookie Of Year|first=Zak|last=Failla|website=Daily Voice|date=March 14, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theathletic.com/1187555/2019/09/06/state-of-the-hoops-program-with-obi-toppin-leading-the-way-dayton-ready-for-breakout-season/|title=State of the Hoops Program: With Obi Toppin leading the way, Dayton ready for breakout season|first=Brian|last=Bennett|website=[[The Athletic]]|date=September 6, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> Following the end of the season he declared for the [[2019 NBA draft]], but did not hire an [[sports agent|agent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/sports/college/2019/04/17/dayton-obi-toppin-ossining-graduate-declares-2019-nba-draft/3501625002/|title=Obi Toppin, Ossining graduate, declares for 2019 NBA Draft|first=Adrian|last=Szkolar|work=The Journal News|date=April 17, 2019|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> After working out for several NBA teams, Toppin opted to withdraw from the draft and return to Dayton.<ref>{{cite web|first=Dave|last=Jablonski|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/dayton-forward-obi-toppin-flyer-nation-back/swdGYPUHyYBrpHbWlNlxtI/|title=Dayton Flyers forward Obi Toppin withdraws from NBA Draft|work=Dayton Daily News|date=May 28, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://celticswire.usatoday.com/2019/05/13/2019-nba-draft-celtics-workout-obi-toppin-a-10-rookie-of-the-year/|title=2019 NBA Draft: Celtics workout Obi Toppin, A-10 Rookie of the Year|first=Quenton S.|last=Albertie|website=Celtics Wire|publisher=USA Today|date=May 13, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> \n\nEntering his redshirt sophomore season, Toppin was named to the preseason first team All-Atlantic 10 and to the [[Karl Malone Award|Karl Malone]], [[Lute Olson Award|Lute Olson]], and [[Naismith Award]] watchlists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/toppin-named-watch-list-for-karl-malone-award/bOk1Q1YHSkU5jmVwzZZwwK/|title=Dayton's Obi Toppin named to watch list for Karl Malone Award|work=Dayton Daily News|date=October 17, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whio.com/sports/toppin-named-watch-list-for-college-basketball-most-prestigious-award/OMv4QVwWAblYpfAYM8ImnO/|title=Toppin named to watch list for college basketball\u2019s most prestigious award|first=David|last=Jablonski|website=WHIO.com|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Obi Toppin Named To Lute Olson Award Watch List |url=https://daytonflyers.com/news/2019/11/6/mens-basketball-obi-toppin-named-to-lute-olson-award-watch-list.aspx |publisher=University of Dayton Athletics |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |date=November 6, 2019}}</ref> Toppin was also named the 44th-best collegiate basketball player going into the [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2019\u201320 season]] by [[CBS Sports]] and the 24th-best prospect for the [[2020 NBA draft]] by [[ESPN]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/ranking-the-top-100-and-1-best-players-in-college-basketball-entering-the-2019-20-season/|title=Ranking the Top 100 And 1 best players in college basketball entering the 2019\u201320 season|first1=Kyle|last1=Boone|first2=Matt|last2=Norlander|first3=Gary|last3=Parrish|website=CBSSports.com|date=October 24, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/insider/story/_/id/27998169/nba-mock-draft-viewer-guide-our-top-prospects|title=NBA mock draft: Viewer's guide for our top prospects|first=Jonathan|last=Givony|website=[[ESPN.com]]|date=November 4, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> He was named the Atlantic 10 Player of the Week for the first week of the season after scoring a career-high 29 points with 12 rebounds in the Flyers' season opening 86\u201381 win over [[Indiana State Sycamores men's basketball|Indiana State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/toppin-wins-atlantic-player-the-week-award/IXwhWzUSd05XMhQL4HNJ8L/|title=Toppin wins Atlantic 10 Player of the Week award|first=David|last=Jablonski|work=Dayton Daily News|date=November 11, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> In late November 2019, Toppin led Dayton to second place at the [[2019 Maui Invitational Tournament]], averaging 22.3 points, 7.0 rebounds, 2.3 assists and 1.3 [[Block (basketball)|blocks]] over three games. He subsequently repeated as Atlantic 10 Player of the Week and was recognized as National Player of the Week by [[NBC Sports]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wdtn.com/sports/flyers-soar-into-ap-top-20-toppin-player-of-the-week/|title=Flyers soar into AP Top 20, Toppin player of the week|first=Jack|last=Pohl|website=[[WDTN|WDTN.com]]|date=December 2, 2019|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2019/12/02/mondays-overreactions-michigans-awesome-udoka-azubuikes-breakout-obi-toppin-alert/|title=Monday\u2019s Overreactions: Michigan\u2019s awesome, Udoka Azubuike\u2019s breakout, Obi Toppin alert|first=Rob|last=Dauster|website=[[NBCSports.com]]|date=December 2, 2019|access-date=December 27, 2019}}</ref> On December 30, Toppin scored a career-high 31 points in a 77\u201359 win over [[North Florida Ospreys men's basketball|North Florida]], including a school-record 10 [[slam dunk|dunks]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jablonski |first1=David |title=Obi Toppin breaks school record with 10 dunks in victory over North Florida |url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/dayton-flyers-build-double-digit-lead-against-north-florida/MBpGBHvFxJFMNkRR4AlVHN/ |accessdate=January 1, 2020 |work=[[Dayton Daily News]] |date=December 30, 2019}}</ref> He was named to the midseason watchlist for the [[Wooden Award]] and was named the Midseason Player of the Year by ''[[The Athletic]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gonzaga's Filip Petrusev among new faces on Wooden Award midseason list |url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28448986/gonzaga-filip-petrusev-new-faces-wooden-award-midseason-list |accessdate=January 10, 2020 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=January 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/obi-toppin-named-midseason-national-player-the-year-the-athletic/oDRj6Ek0xLlMQe1JJPSBJO/|title=Obi Toppin named midseason national player of the year by The Athletic|first=David|last=Jablonski|work=Dayton Daily News|date=January 7, 2020|access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref> \n\nToppin sprained his left ankle during a win against [[UMass Minutemen basketball|UMass]] on January 11, 2020 but did not miss a game, scoring 24 points in Dayton's next game against [[2019\u201320 VCU Rams men's basketball team|VCU]] in spite of his injury.<ref>{{cite news |title=Obi Toppin injures ankle during Dayton's big win over UMass |url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28464455/obi-toppin-injures-ankle-dayton-big-win-umass |accessdate=January 11, 2020 |website=[[ESPN]] |publisher = [[Associated Press]] |date=January 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/washington/ncaa/vcu-falls-no-13-dayton-unable-contain-hobbled-obi-toppin|title=VCU falls to No. 13 Dayton, unable to contain a hobbled Obi Toppin|website=[[NBC Sports Washington]]|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 14, 2020|access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref> Toppin scored his 1,000th career point on February 22, 2020 during a 28-point performance in an 80\u201370 win over [[2019\u201320 Duquesne Dukes men's basketball team|Duquesne]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Mitch |last=Stacy |url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401170308|title=Toppin scores 28 as No. 5 Dayton cruises past Duquesne 80\u201370|website=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|date=February 22, 2020|access-date=February 22, 2020}}</ref> At the end of the regular season Toppin was named to the first team All-Atlantic 10 and the [[Atlantic 10 Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year]] after averaging 20 points, 7.5 rebounds and 1.2 blocks per game with a .633 [[field goal percentage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/obi-toppin-makes-more-dayton-flyers-history-atlantic-awards/eOcITCJfq5dixdLyb3NpcP/|title=Obi Toppin makes more Dayton Flyers history in Atlantic 10 awards|first=David|last=Jablonski|work=Dayton Daily News|date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/09/once-an-afterthought-obi-toppin-turned-dayton-into-ncaa-title-threat/|title=Once an afterthought, Obi Toppin turned Dayton into NCAA title threat|first=Zach|last=Braziller|work=[[New York Post]]|date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Toppin was a consensus first team All-American selection, won the [[Karl Malone Award]] as the nation's top power forward,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whio.com/sports/university-of-dayton-flyers/obi-toppin-named-national-power-forward-year-moves-closer-sweep-prestigious-awards/53TWFZLC6FADPA3BGJGRBQC6NI/|title=Obi Toppin named national power forward of the year; moves closer to sweep of prestigious awards|first=Michael|last=Purves|website=WHIO.com|date=April 7, 2020|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> and was the consensus National Player of the Year after being named the [[Associated Press College Basketball Player of the Year]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/2020/03/24/uds-obi-toppin-areas-first-national-player-year-since-2003/5022288002/|title=Dayton's Toppin first in our area to win college basketball player of the year since 2003|first=Shelby|last=Dermer|work=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[NABC Player of the Year]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/obi-toppin-anthony-grant-add-trophy-case-with-more-national-awards/da3OWjjOxdiOJEWMlFVKwK/|title=Obi Toppin, Anthony Grant add to trophy case with more national awards|work=[[Dayton Daily News]]|first=David|last=Jablonski|date=March 30, 2020|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[Naismith College Player of the Year]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/daytons-obi-toppin-earns-2020-citizen-naismith-trophy-for-being-named-the-mens-player-of-the-year/|title=Dayton's Obi Toppin earns 2020 Citizen Naismith Trophy for being named the men's player of the year|first=Matt|last=Norlander|website=[[CBSSports.com]]|date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> and awarded the [[Oscar Robertson Trophy]] and the [[John R. Wooden Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.springfieldnewssun.com/sports/obi-toppin-anthony-grant-sweep-top-awards-from-usbwa/JcTjlsv2QlL2Pwf9b09cTM/|title=Obi Toppin, Anthony Grant sweep top awards from USBWA|work=[[Springfield News-Sun]]|first=David|last=Jablonski|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/page/wooden040720/dayton-obi-toppin-wins-wooden-award-complete-sweep|title=Dayton's Obi Toppin wins Wooden Award to complete sweep|first=Myron|last=Medcalf|website=[[ESPN.com]]|date=April 7, 2020|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> He also garnered national player of the year honors from [[CBS Sports]], ''The Athletic'', [[NBC Sports]] and ''[[USA Today]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whio.com/sports/dayton-obi-toppin-named-first-team-all-american-first-program-history/GqiHiyI0gFujSRb6DUd3wK/|title=Dayton\u2019s Obi Toppin named First Team All-American, first in program history|first=Michael|last=Purves|website=WHIO.com|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> After the season Toppin announced that he would be forgoing his final two seasons of eligibility to enter the [[2020 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/Article/Obi-Toppin-declares-for-NBA-Draft-2020-Dayton-Flyers-college-basketball-145383378/|title=Obi Toppin declares for NBA Draft|first=Sam|last=Hellman|website=247Sports.com|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Toppin finished his college career with 1,096 points scored and a school-record 190 dunks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whio.com/sports/dayton-obi-toppin-hire-agent-enter-nba-draft/xeS3zXTXdizVAPvSLl5fNM/|title=\u2018Thank you Flyer Nation;\u2019 Dayton\u2019s Obi Toppin to enter NBA Draft|first=Michael|last=Purves|website=WHIO.com|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"collegestats\">{{cite web |title=Obi Toppin College Stats |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/obadiah-toppin-1.html |publisher=[[Sports Reference]] |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|Dayton]]\n| '''33''' || 15 || 26.5 || '''.666''' || '''.524''' || '''.713''' || 5.6 || 1.8 || .6 || .8 || 14.4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=collegestats/>\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2019\u201320 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|Dayton]]\n| 31 || '''31''' || '''31.6''' || .633 || .390 || .702 || '''7.5''' || '''2.2''' || '''1.0''' || '''1.2''' || '''20.0'''\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 64 || 46 || 29.0 || .647 || .417 || .706 || 6.6 || 2.0 || .8 || 1.0 || 17.1\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nToppin's father, also named Obadiah, was a well-known [[streetball]] player in Brooklyn. He played basketball collegiately at [[Globe Institute of Technology]] and professionally for the [[Brooklyn Kings (basketball)|Brooklyn Kings]] of the [[United States Basketball League]], the Harlem Strong Dogs of the [[American Basketball Association (2000\u2013present)|American Basketball Association]] and in the Dominican Republic.<ref name=\"Eager\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theathletic.com/1580753/2020/02/04/obi-toppin-college-basketball-dayton-flyers-dunks-player-of-year-draft/|title=The flight of Obi Toppin|first=Brian|last=Bennett|website=[[The Athletic]]|date=February 4, 2020|access-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref> His father was also known as \u201cDunkers Delight\u201d while playing for a streetball team called the Court Kingz. His brother, Jacob, plays college basketball for [[Rhode Island Rams men's basketball|Rhode Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewesterlysun.com/sports/latest-sports/college-basketball-uri-good-enough-in-opener/article_4e0b64a6-003c-11ea-be0b-4b888158a658.html|title=College basketball: URI good enough in opener|first=William|last=Geoghegan|work=[[The Westerly Sun]]|date=November 5, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nToppin is a Christian and has a cross tattoo on his right shoulder as a sign of his faith.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mercer |first1=Kevin |title=Player of the Year frontrunner Obi Toppin of Dayton looks to God amid coronavirus cancellations |url=https://sportsspectrum.com/sport/basketball/2020/03/13/dayton-forward-obi-toppin-looks-to-god-coronavirus-cancellations/ |website=Sports Spectrum |date= March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Toppin |first1=Obi |last2=Hager |first2=Tom |title=Trust the Process |url=https://www.athletesforgod.com/obi-toppin/page-1 |website=Athletes For God |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://daytonflyers.com/sports/mens-basketball/roster/obi-toppin/10161 Dayton Flyers bio]\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/obadiah-toppin-1.html College Statistics at Sports-Reference.com]\n\n{{navboxes|list=\n{{Wooden Player of the Year men}}\n{{Naismith Player of the Year men}}\n{{Oscar Robertson Trophy}}\n{{NABC Player of the Year}}\n{{Associated Press College Basketball Player of the Year}}\n{{2020 NCAA Men's Basketball Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Karl Malone Award}}\n{{Atlantic 10 Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Toppin, Obi}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-American college men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Dayton Flyers men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:People from Bushwick, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Brooklyn]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Obi Toppin\n| image = Obi_Toppin.jpg\n| image_size = 260px\n| caption = Toppin in 2020\n| number =\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 9\n| weight_lbs = 220\n| team =\n| league =\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1998|3|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Brooklyn, New York]]\n| high_school = \n*[[Heritage High School (Palm Bay, Florida)|Heritage]]<br>([[Palm Bay, Florida]])\n*[[Melbourne Central Catholic High School|Melbourne Central Catholic]]<br>([[Melbourne, Florida]])\n*[[Ossining High School|Ossining]]<br>([[Ossining (village), New York|Ossining, New York]])\n*Mt. Zion Prep<br>([[Baltimore, Maryland]])\n| college = [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton]] (2018\u20132020) \n| highlights = \n*[[List of U.S. men's college basketball national player of the year awards|National College Player of the Year]] (2020)\n*Consensus first-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] ([[2020 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|2020]])\n*[[Karl Malone Award]] winner (2020)\n*[[Atlantic 10 Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|Atlantic 10 Player of the Year]] ([[2019\u201320 Atlantic 10 Conference men's basketball season|2020]])\n*2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Atlantic 10 Conference|Atlantic 10]] ([[2018\u201319 Atlantic 10 Conference men's basketball season|2019]], 2020)\n*Atlantic 10 Rookie of the Year (2019)\n}}\n'''Obadiah Richard \"Obi\" Toppin''' (born March 4, 1998) is an American [[basketball]] player who last played for the [[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton Flyers]] of the [[Atlantic 10 Conference]]. Listed at {{convert|6|ft|9|in|m|2}} and {{convert|220|lbs|kg|0}}, he plays the [[power forward (basketball)|power forward]] position.\n\nA native of [[Brooklyn]], Toppin finished high school at [[Ossining High School]] in New York. After receiving no [[NCAA Division I]] offers, he played a postgraduate season at Mt. Zion Preparatory School in [[Maryland]]. As a freshman with the Dayton Flyers, Toppin was named Atlantic 10 Rookie of the Year after leading his team in scoring. He had breakout success in his sophomore season, earning [[Atlantic 10 Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|Atlantic 10 Player of the Year]] and several [[List of U.S. men's college basketball national player of the year awards|national player of the year]] honors.\n\n==Early life and high school==\nToppin was born in [[Brooklyn]] in New York City and originally grew up in the neighborhood of [[Bushwick, Brooklyn|Bushwick]] before moving to [[Melbourne, Florida]]. He attended [[Heritage High School (Palm Bay, Florida)|Heritage High School]] in [[Palm Bay, Florida|Palm Bay]] as a freshman before transferring to [[Melbourne Central Catholic High School]] the next year. Toppin, his mother and younger brother relocated to [[Ossining (village), New York|Ossining, New York]] and enrolled at [[Ossining High School]] going into his junior year.<ref name=\"Eager\">{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/archdeacon-redshirt-freshman-toppin-eager-make-dayton-debut/aSQAiZyosYQdG2m9wSvd2K/|title=Redshirt freshman Toppin eager to make Dayton debut|first=Tom|last=Archdeacon|work=[[Dayton Daily News]]|date=June 10, 2018|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> \n\nHe averaged 20.6 [[Point (basketball)|points]], 8.1 [[Rebound (basketball)|rebounds]], 3 [[Assist (basketball)|assists]] and 3 [[Steal (basketball)|steals]] as a senior during his only year playing [[varsity team|varsity]] at Ossining and led the team to its first conference title in 10 years. Having received no [[NCAA Division I]] offers, Toppin opted to enroll at Mt. Zion Preparatory School in [[Baltimore, Maryland]] for a postgraduate year. He averaged 17 points, eight rebounds and four assists and also grew four inches to {{convert|6|ft|9|in|m|2}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dayton247now.com/sports/dayton-flyers/ud-freshman-toppin-academically-ineligible-for-2017-18-season|title=UD freshman Toppin academically ineligible for 2017\u201318 season|first=James|last=Rider|website=dayton247now.com|date=September 19, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> He committed to play college basketball at the [[University of Dayton]] over offers from [[Rhode Island Rams men's basketball|Rhode Island]], [[Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball|Georgetown]], [[Georgia Bulldogs basketball|Georgia]], [[Texas A&M Aggies men's basketball|Texas A&M]], [[Minnesota Golden Gophers men's basketball|Minnesota]] and [[Texas Tech Red Raiders basketball|Texas Tech]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/sports/columnists/josh-thomson/2017/05/19/thomson-obi-toppins-patience-leads-him-dayton/330563001/|title=Thomson: Patience lands Toppin at Dayton|first=Josh|last=Thompson|work=The Journal News|date=May 19, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/insider/story/_/id/28685100/how-obi-toppin-ended-dayton-other-origin-stories-wooden-award-favorites|title=How Obi Toppin ended up at Dayton and other origin stories around Wooden Award favorites|first=Jeff|last=Borzello|website=[[ESPN.com]]|date=February 13, 2020|access-date=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nToppin [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] his true freshman season after being ruled academically ineligible to play.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2017/09/19/dayton-freshman-toppin-ineligible-for-2017-18-season/|title=Dayton freshman Toppin ineligible for 2017\u201318 season|first=Raphielle|last=Johnson|website=[[NBCSports.com]]|date=September 19, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> As a redshirt freshman, Toppin led the Flyers with 14.4 points per game while averaging 5.6 rebounds per game and was named the [[Atlantic 10 Conference]] Rookie of the Week seven times.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/four-dayton-flyers-honored-atlantic-awards/oE9itI5FYWiShpmroaH0KL/|title=Atlantic 10 awards: Obi Toppin makes Dayton Flyers history|first=David|last=Jablonski|work=Dayton Daily News|date=March 12, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> At the end of the season, Toppin was named the Atlantic 10 Rookie of the Year and to the first team All-Atlantic 10, the first freshman to do so since [[Lamar Odom]] in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailyvoice.com/new-york/mountpleasant/sports/northern-westchesters-obi-toppin-named-atlantic-10-rookie-of-year/749463/|title=Northern Westchester's Obi Toppin Named Atlantic 10 Rookie Of Year|first=Zak|last=Failla|website=Daily Voice|date=March 14, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theathletic.com/1187555/2019/09/06/state-of-the-hoops-program-with-obi-toppin-leading-the-way-dayton-ready-for-breakout-season/|title=State of the Hoops Program: With Obi Toppin leading the way, Dayton ready for breakout season|first=Brian|last=Bennett|website=[[The Athletic]]|date=September 6, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> Following the end of the season he declared for the [[2019 NBA draft]], but did not hire an [[sports agent|agent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lohud.com/story/sports/college/2019/04/17/dayton-obi-toppin-ossining-graduate-declares-2019-nba-draft/3501625002/|title=Obi Toppin, Ossining graduate, declares for 2019 NBA Draft|first=Adrian|last=Szkolar|work=The Journal News|date=April 17, 2019|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> After working out for several NBA teams, Toppin opted to withdraw from the draft and return to Dayton.<ref>{{cite web|first=Dave|last=Jablonski|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/dayton-forward-obi-toppin-flyer-nation-back/swdGYPUHyYBrpHbWlNlxtI/|title=Dayton Flyers forward Obi Toppin withdraws from NBA Draft|work=Dayton Daily News|date=May 28, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://celticswire.usatoday.com/2019/05/13/2019-nba-draft-celtics-workout-obi-toppin-a-10-rookie-of-the-year/|title=2019 NBA Draft: Celtics workout Obi Toppin, A-10 Rookie of the Year|first=Quenton S.|last=Albertie|website=Celtics Wire|publisher=USA Today|date=May 13, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> \n\nEntering his redshirt sophomore season, Toppin was named to the preseason first team All-Atlantic 10 and to the [[Karl Malone Award|Karl Malone]], [[Lute Olson Award|Lute Olson]], and [[Naismith Award]] watchlists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/toppin-named-watch-list-for-karl-malone-award/bOk1Q1YHSkU5jmVwzZZwwK/|title=Dayton's Obi Toppin named to watch list for Karl Malone Award|work=Dayton Daily News|date=October 17, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whio.com/sports/toppin-named-watch-list-for-college-basketball-most-prestigious-award/OMv4QVwWAblYpfAYM8ImnO/|title=Toppin named to watch list for college basketball\u2019s most prestigious award|first=David|last=Jablonski|website=WHIO.com|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Obi Toppin Named To Lute Olson Award Watch List |url=https://daytonflyers.com/news/2019/11/6/mens-basketball-obi-toppin-named-to-lute-olson-award-watch-list.aspx |publisher=University of Dayton Athletics |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |date=November 6, 2019}}</ref> Toppin was also named the 44th-best collegiate basketball player going into the [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2019\u201320 season]] by [[CBS Sports]] and the 24th-best prospect for the [[2020 NBA draft]] by [[ESPN]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/ranking-the-top-100-and-1-best-players-in-college-basketball-entering-the-2019-20-season/|title=Ranking the Top 100 And 1 best players in college basketball entering the 2019\u201320 season|first1=Kyle|last1=Boone|first2=Matt|last2=Norlander|first3=Gary|last3=Parrish|website=CBSSports.com|date=October 24, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/insider/story/_/id/27998169/nba-mock-draft-viewer-guide-our-top-prospects|title=NBA mock draft: Viewer's guide for our top prospects|first=Jonathan|last=Givony|website=[[ESPN.com]]|date=November 4, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> He was named the Atlantic 10 Player of the Week for the first week of the season after scoring a career-high 29 points with 12 rebounds in the Flyers' season opening 86\u201381 win over [[Indiana State Sycamores men's basketball|Indiana State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/toppin-wins-atlantic-player-the-week-award/IXwhWzUSd05XMhQL4HNJ8L/|title=Toppin wins Atlantic 10 Player of the Week award|first=David|last=Jablonski|work=Dayton Daily News|date=November 11, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> In late November 2019, Toppin led Dayton to second place at the [[2019 Maui Invitational Tournament]], averaging 22.3 points, 7.0 rebounds, 2.3 assists and 1.3 [[Block (basketball)|blocks]] over three games. He was subsequently repeated as Atlantic 10 Player of the Week and was recognized as National Player of the Week by [[NBC Sports]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wdtn.com/sports/flyers-soar-into-ap-top-20-toppin-player-of-the-week/|title=Flyers soar into AP Top 20, Toppin player of the week|first=Jack|last=Pohl|website=[[WDTN|WDTN.com]]|date=December 2, 2019|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2019/12/02/mondays-overreactions-michigans-awesome-udoka-azubuikes-breakout-obi-toppin-alert/|title=Monday\u2019s Overreactions: Michigan\u2019s awesome, Udoka Azubuike\u2019s breakout, Obi Toppin alert|first=Rob|last=Dauster|website=[[NBCSports.com]]|date=December 2, 2019|access-date=December 27, 2019}}</ref> On December 30, Toppin scored a career-high 31 points in a 77\u201359 win over [[North Florida Ospreys men's basketball|North Florida]], including a school-record 10 [[slam dunk|dunks]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jablonski |first1=David |title=Obi Toppin breaks school record with 10 dunks in victory over North Florida |url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/dayton-flyers-build-double-digit-lead-against-north-florida/MBpGBHvFxJFMNkRR4AlVHN/ |accessdate=January 1, 2020 |work=[[Dayton Daily News]] |date=December 30, 2019}}</ref> He was named to the midseason watchlist for the [[Wooden Award]] and was named the Midseason Player of the Year by ''[[The Athletic]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gonzaga's Filip Petrusev among new faces on Wooden Award midseason list |url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28448986/gonzaga-filip-petrusev-new-faces-wooden-award-midseason-list |accessdate=January 10, 2020 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=January 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/obi-toppin-named-midseason-national-player-the-year-the-athletic/oDRj6Ek0xLlMQe1JJPSBJO/|title=Obi Toppin named midseason national player of the year by The Athletic|first=David|last=Jablonski|work=Dayton Daily News|date=January 7, 2020|access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref> \n\nToppin sprained his left ankle during a win against [[UMass Minutemen basketball|UMass]] on January 11, 2020 but did not miss a game, scoring 24 points in Dayton's next game against [[2019\u201320 VCU Rams men's basketball team|VCU]] in spite of his injury.<ref>{{cite news |title=Obi Toppin injures ankle during Dayton's big win over UMass |url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28464455/obi-toppin-injures-ankle-dayton-big-win-umass |accessdate=January 11, 2020 |website=[[ESPN]] |publisher = [[Associated Press]] |date=January 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/washington/ncaa/vcu-falls-no-13-dayton-unable-contain-hobbled-obi-toppin|title=VCU falls to No. 13 Dayton, unable to contain a hobbled Obi Toppin|website=[[NBC Sports Washington]]|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 14, 2020|access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref> Toppin scored his 1,000th career point on February 22, 2020 during a 28-point performance in an 80\u201370 win over [[2019\u201320 Duquesne Dukes men's basketball team|Duquesne]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Mitch |last=Stacy |url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401170308|title=Toppin scores 28 as No. 5 Dayton cruises past Duquesne 80\u201370|website=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|date=February 22, 2020|access-date=February 22, 2020}}</ref> At the end of the regular season Toppin was named to the first team All-Atlantic 10 and the [[Atlantic 10 Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year]] after averaging 20 points, 7.5 rebounds and 1.2 blocks per game with a .633 [[field goal percentage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/obi-toppin-makes-more-dayton-flyers-history-atlantic-awards/eOcITCJfq5dixdLyb3NpcP/|title=Obi Toppin makes more Dayton Flyers history in Atlantic 10 awards|first=David|last=Jablonski|work=Dayton Daily News|date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/09/once-an-afterthought-obi-toppin-turned-dayton-into-ncaa-title-threat/|title=Once an afterthought, Obi Toppin turned Dayton into NCAA title threat|first=Zach|last=Braziller|work=[[New York Post]]|date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Toppin was a consensus first team All-American selection, won the [[Karl Malone Award]] as the nation's top power forward,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whio.com/sports/university-of-dayton-flyers/obi-toppin-named-national-power-forward-year-moves-closer-sweep-prestigious-awards/53TWFZLC6FADPA3BGJGRBQC6NI/|title=Obi Toppin named national power forward of the year; moves closer to sweep of prestigious awards|first=Michael|last=Purves|website=WHIO.com|date=April 7, 2020|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> and was the consensus National Player of the Year after being named the [[Associated Press College Basketball Player of the Year]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/2020/03/24/uds-obi-toppin-areas-first-national-player-year-since-2003/5022288002/|title=Dayton's Toppin first in our area to win college basketball player of the year since 2003|first=Shelby|last=Dermer|work=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[NABC Player of the Year]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/obi-toppin-anthony-grant-add-trophy-case-with-more-national-awards/da3OWjjOxdiOJEWMlFVKwK/|title=Obi Toppin, Anthony Grant add to trophy case with more national awards|work=[[Dayton Daily News]]|first=David|last=Jablonski|date=March 30, 2020|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[Naismith College Player of the Year]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/daytons-obi-toppin-earns-2020-citizen-naismith-trophy-for-being-named-the-mens-player-of-the-year/|title=Dayton's Obi Toppin earns 2020 Citizen Naismith Trophy for being named the men's player of the year|first=Matt|last=Norlander|website=[[CBSSports.com]]|date=April 3, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> and awarded the [[Oscar Robertson Trophy]] and the [[John R. Wooden Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.springfieldnewssun.com/sports/obi-toppin-anthony-grant-sweep-top-awards-from-usbwa/JcTjlsv2QlL2Pwf9b09cTM/|title=Obi Toppin, Anthony Grant sweep top awards from USBWA|work=[[Springfield News-Sun]]|first=David|last=Jablonski|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/page/wooden040720/dayton-obi-toppin-wins-wooden-award-complete-sweep|title=Dayton's Obi Toppin wins Wooden Award to complete sweep|first=Myron|last=Medcalf|website=[[ESPN.com]]|date=April 7, 2020|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> He also garnered national player of the year honors from [[CBS Sports]], ''The Athletic'', [[NBC Sports]] and ''[[USA Today]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whio.com/sports/dayton-obi-toppin-named-first-team-all-american-first-program-history/GqiHiyI0gFujSRb6DUd3wK/|title=Dayton\u2019s Obi Toppin named First Team All-American, first in program history|first=Michael|last=Purves|website=WHIO.com|date=March 20, 2020|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> After the season Toppin announced that he would be forgoing his final two seasons of eligibility to enter the [[2020 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/Article/Obi-Toppin-declares-for-NBA-Draft-2020-Dayton-Flyers-college-basketball-145383378/|title=Obi Toppin declares for NBA Draft|first=Sam|last=Hellman|website=247Sports.com|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Toppin finished his college career with 1,096 points scored and a school-record 190 dunks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whio.com/sports/dayton-obi-toppin-hire-agent-enter-nba-draft/xeS3zXTXdizVAPvSLl5fNM/|title=\u2018Thank you Flyer Nation;\u2019 Dayton\u2019s Obi Toppin to enter NBA Draft|first=Michael|last=Purves|website=WHIO.com|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"collegestats\">{{cite web |title=Obi Toppin College Stats |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/obadiah-toppin-1.html |publisher=[[Sports Reference]] |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|Dayton]]\n| '''33''' || 15 || 26.5 || '''.666''' || '''.524''' || '''.713''' || 5.6 || 1.8 || .6 || .8 || 14.4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=collegestats/>\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2019\u201320 Dayton Flyers men's basketball team|Dayton]]\n| 31 || '''31''' || '''31.6''' || .633 || .390 || .702 || '''7.5''' || '''2.2''' || '''1.0''' || '''1.2''' || '''20.0'''\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 64 || 46 || 29.0 || .647 || .417 || .706 || 6.6 || 2.0 || .8 || 1.0 || 17.1\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nToppin's father, also named Obadiah, was a well-known [[streetball]] player in Brooklyn. He played basketball collegiately at [[Globe Institute of Technology]] and professionally for the [[Brooklyn Kings (basketball)|Brooklyn Kings]] of the [[United States Basketball League]], the Harlem Strong Dogs of the [[American Basketball Association (2000\u2013present)|American Basketball Association]] and in the Dominican Republic.<ref name=\"Eager\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theathletic.com/1580753/2020/02/04/obi-toppin-college-basketball-dayton-flyers-dunks-player-of-year-draft/|title=The flight of Obi Toppin|first=Brian|last=Bennett|website=[[The Athletic]]|date=February 4, 2020|access-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref> His father was also known as \u201cDunkers Delight\u201d while playing for a streetball team called the Court Kingz. His brother, Jacob, plays college basketball for [[Rhode Island Rams men's basketball|Rhode Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewesterlysun.com/sports/latest-sports/college-basketball-uri-good-enough-in-opener/article_4e0b64a6-003c-11ea-be0b-4b888158a658.html|title=College basketball: URI good enough in opener|first=William|last=Geoghegan|work=[[The Westerly Sun]]|date=November 5, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nToppin is a Christian and has a cross tattoo on his right shoulder as a sign of his faith.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mercer |first1=Kevin |title=Player of the Year frontrunner Obi Toppin of Dayton looks to God amid coronavirus cancellations |url=https://sportsspectrum.com/sport/basketball/2020/03/13/dayton-forward-obi-toppin-looks-to-god-coronavirus-cancellations/ |website=Sports Spectrum |date= March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Toppin |first1=Obi |last2=Hager |first2=Tom |title=Trust the Process |url=https://www.athletesforgod.com/obi-toppin/page-1 |website=Athletes For God |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://daytonflyers.com/sports/mens-basketball/roster/obi-toppin/10161 Dayton Flyers bio]\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/obadiah-toppin-1.html College Statistics at Sports-Reference.com]\n\n{{navboxes|list=\n{{Wooden Player of the Year men}}\n{{Naismith Player of the Year men}}\n{{Oscar Robertson Trophy}}\n{{NABC Player of the Year}}\n{{Associated Press College Basketball Player of the Year}}\n{{2020 NCAA Men's Basketball Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Karl Malone Award}}\n{{Atlantic 10 Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Toppin, Obi}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-American college men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Dayton Flyers men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:People from Bushwick, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Power forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Brooklyn]]\n", "name_user": "Sportzeditz", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obi_Toppin"}
{"title_page": "Business Plot", "text_new": "{{short description|Political conspiracy in 1933 in the United States}}\nThe '''Business Plot ''' was a [[Conspiracy (political)|political conspiracy]] in 1933 in the United States.  Retired [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]] [[Major General (United States)|Major General]] [[Smedley Butler]] revealed that wealthy businessmen were plotting to create a [[Fascism|fascist]] veterans' organization with Butler as its leader and use it in a [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] to overthrow President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]. In 1934, Butler testified before the [[United States House of Representatives]] [[House Un-American Activities Committee#Special Committee on Un-American Activities (1934-1937)|Special Committee on Un-American Activities]] (the \"[[John William McCormack|McCormack]]\u2013[[Samuel Dickstein (congressman)|Dickstein]] Committee\") on these revelations.<ref name=\"Schlesinger, p. 85\">Schlesinger, p. 85</ref> No one was prosecuted.\n\nAt the time of the incidents, news media dismissed the plot, with a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' editorial characterizing it as a \"gigantic hoax\".<ref name=\"nyt112234\"/>  While historians have not accepted the notion of a plot, they agree that Butler described one.<ref name=burk/><ref name=schmidt226/><ref name=Fox>{{cite book|last1=Fox|title=The Clarks of Cooperstown|publisher=Knopf|year=2007|isbn=978-0-307-26347-6|url=https://archive.org/details/clarksofcooperst00webe}}</ref><ref name=\"schlesinger83\"/>\n\n==Background==\n\n===Butler and the veterans===\n[[Image:evictbonusarmy.jpg|thumb|260px|Shacks, erected by the [[Bonus Army]] on the [[Anacostia]] flats, burning after being set on fire by the US military (1932)]]\n{{Main|Bonus Army}}\n\nOn July 17, 1932, thousands of [[World War I]] veterans converged on [[Washington, D.C.]], set up tent camps, and demanded immediate payment of bonuses due to them according to the [[World War Adjusted Compensation Act]] of 1924 (the original act made the bonuses initially due no earlier than 1925 and no later than 1945). [[Walter W. Waters]], a former Army [[sergeant]], led this \"[[Bonus Army]]\". The Bonus Army was encouraged by an appearance from retired Marine Corps Maj. Gen. [[Smedley Butler]]; as a popular military figure of the time. A few days after Butler's arrival, President [[Herbert Hoover]] ordered the marchers removed and [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] [[cavalry]] troops under the command of Gen. [[Douglas MacArthur]] destroyed their camps.\n\nButler, although a self-described [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], responded by supporting [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] in the [[1932 United States presidential election|1932 US presidential election]].<ref name=\"support\">Schmidt, p. 219 <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\"Declaring himself a \"Hoover-for-Ex-President [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]],\" Smedley used the bonus issue and the army's use of gas in routing the \"Bonus Expeditionary Force\"--recalling infamous gas warfare during the Great War--to disparage Hoover during the [[1932 United States presidential election|1932 general elections]]. He came out for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] \"despite the fact that my family for generations has been Republican,\" and shared the platform when Republican [[United States Senate|Sen.]] [[George W. Norris]] opened a coast-to-coast stump for FDR in Philadelphia....Butler was pleased with the election results that saw Hoover defeated; although he admitted that he had exerted himself in the campaign more \"to get rid of Hoover than to put in Roosevelt,\" and to \"square a debt.\" FDR, his old [[Haiti]] ally, was a \"nice fellow\" and might make a good president, but Smedley did not expect much influence in the new administration.\"</span>\n</ref> By 1933 Butler started denouncing [[capitalism]] and bankers, going on to explain that for 33 years he had been a \"high-class muscle man\" for Wall Street, the bankers and big business, labeling himself as a \"racketeer for Capitalism.\"<ref>Smedley D. Butler, ''[[War is a Racket]]'' (Los Angeles: Feral House, 1935, 2003), 26</ref>\n\n===Reaction to Roosevelt===\nRoosevelt's election was upsetting for many conservative businessmen of the time, as his \"campaign promise that the government would provide jobs for all the unemployed had the perverse effect of creating a new wave of unemployment by businessmen frightened by fears of socialism and reckless government spending.\"<ref name=\"power\">{{cite book|title=The Power of Gold: the history of an obsession|url=https://archive.org/details/powerofgoldhisto00bern|url-access=registration|author=Peter L. Bernstein|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=NY, NY|year=2000|author-link=Peter L. Bernstein}}</ref> Some writers have said concerns over the [[gold standard]] were also involved; Jules Archer, in ''The Plot to Seize the White House'', wrote that with the end of the gold standard, \"conservative financiers were horrified. They viewed a currency not solidly backed by gold as [[inflation]]ary, undermining both private and business fortunes and leading to national bankruptcy. Roosevelt was damned as a socialist or Communist out to destroy private enterprise by sapping the gold backing of wealth in order to subsidize the poor.\"<ref name=\"Jules\"/>\n\n==McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee==\nThe Committee began examining evidence on November 20, 1934. On November 24 the committee released a statement detailing the testimony it had heard about the plot and its preliminary findings. On February 15, 1935, the committee submitted its final report to the House of Representatives.<ref name=\"plotx\" />\n\nDuring the McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee hearings Butler testified that [[Business Plot#1933|Gerald C. MacGuire]] attempted to recruit him to lead a coup, promising him an army of 500,000 men for a march on [[Washington, DC]], and financial backing. Butler testified that the pretext for the coup would be that the president's health was failing.<ref name=\"archerquote\">Archer, p. 155.</ref> Despite Butler's support for Roosevelt in the election<ref name=\"support\" /> and his reputation as a strong critic of capitalism,<ref>Schmidt, p. 231</ref> Butler said the plotters felt his good reputation and popularity were vital in attracting support amongst the general public and saw him as easier to manipulate than others. Given a successful coup, Butler said that the plan was for him to have held near-absolute power in the newly created position of \"Secretary of General Affairs\", while Roosevelt would have assumed a [[figurehead]] role. \n\nThose implicated in the plot by Butler all denied any involvement. MacGuire was the only figure identified by Butler who testified before the committee. Others Butler accused were not called to appear to testify because the \"committee has had no evidence before it that would in the slightest degree warrant calling before it such men ... The committee will not take cognizance of names brought into testimony which constitute mere hearsay.\"<ref name=page1>Public Statement on Preliminary findings of HUAC, November 24, 1934, page 1</ref>\n\nOn the final day of the committee,<ref>Archer, p. 189</ref> January 29, 1935, [[John L. Spivak]] published the first of two articles in the [[Communist Party USA|communist]] magazine ''[[New Masses]]'', revealing portions of the Congressional committee testimony that had been redacted as hearsay. Spivak argued that the plot was part of a plan by [[J.P. Morgan, Jr.|J.P. Morgan]] and other financiers who were coordinating with fascist groups to overthrow President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]].\n\nHans Schmidt concludes that while Spivak made a cogent argument for taking the suppressed testimony seriously, he embellished his article with his \"overblown\" claims regarding Jewish financiers, which Schmidt dismisses as [[guilt by association]] not supported by the evidence of the Butler-MacGuire conversations themselves.<ref name=\"plotx\">Archer, p. x ''(Foreword)''</ref><ref name=Schmidt229>Schmidt, p. 229</ref>\n\nOn March 25, 1935, MacGuire died in a hospital in [[New Haven, Connecticut]], at the age of 37. His attending doctor at the hospital attributed the death to [[pneumonia]] and its complications, but also said that the accusations against MacGuire had led to his weakened condition and collapse which in turn led to the pneumonia.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1935/03/26/archives/gc-mguire-dies-accused-of-plot-was-named-as-leading-wall-st-move-to.html G.C. M'Guire Dies; Accused of 'Plot'], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (March 26, 1935) (subscription).  An image of the article is also accessible down the page [http://imgur.com/gallery/ryG41 here].  Retrieved July 27, 2017.</ref>\n\n===Butler's testimony in detail===\n[[File:Universal Newsreel - Gen. Butler bares \"plot\" by fascists.ogv|thumb|Smedley Butler describes the alleged plot in 1933.]]\n{{synthesis|section|date=March 2009}}\n\n====1933====\nOn July 1, 1933, Butler met with MacGuire and Doyle for the first time. Gerald C. MacGuire was a $100-a-week bond salesman for [[Grayson Murphy|Grayson Murphy & Company]]<ref>Schmidt, p. 224</ref><ref name=\"record\">[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Testimony of Gerald C. Macguire]]</ref> and a member of the Connecticut [[American Legion]].<ref>Archer, p. 6.</ref><ref name=\"contradicts\">This contradicts MacGuire's testimony: \"You are a past department commander in the American Legion?\" \"No, sir; never held an office in the American Legion, I have just been a Legionnaire--oh, I beg your pardon. I did hold one office. I was on the distinguished guest committee of the Legion in 1933, I believe.\" [[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Testimony of Gerald C. Macguire|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, testimony of Gerald C. MacGuire]]</ref> Bill Doyle was commander of the Massachusetts American Legion.<ref>Archer, p. 6</ref> Butler stated that he was asked to run for National Commander of the [[American Legion]].<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 1|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, p. 1]]</ref>\n\nOn July 3 or 4, Butler held a second meeting with MacGuire and Doyle. He stated that they offered to get hundreds of supporters at the American Legion convention to ask for a speech.<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Doyle and MacGuire's second visit|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report]]</ref> MacGuire left a typewritten speech with Butler that they proposed he read at the convention. \"It urged the American Legion convention to adopt a resolution calling for the United States to return to the gold standard, so that when veterans were paid the bonus promised to them, the money they received would not be worthless paper.\"<ref name=\"Jules\">{{cite book |author=Jules Archer|year=1973|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing |title=The Plot to Seize the White House: The Shocking True Story of the Conspiracy to Overthrow FDR}}</ref> The inclusion of this demand further increased Butler's suspicion.\n\nAround August 1, MacGuire visited Butler alone. Butler stated that MacGuire told him Grayson Murphy underwrote the formation of the American Legion in New York and Butler told MacGuire that the American Legion was \"nothing but a [[strikebreaking]] outfit.\"<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Third visit with MacGuire|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report]]</ref> Butler never saw Doyle again.\n\nOn September 24,<ref>Archer, p. 178</ref><ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 20|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, p. 20]]</ref> MacGuire visited Butler's hotel room in [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]].<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Meeting in hotel|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report]]</ref> In late September Butler met with [[Robert Sterling Clark]].<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Meeting with Clark|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report]]</ref> Clark was an art collector and an heir to the [[Singer Corporation]] fortune.<ref>Schmidt, p. 239, 241</ref><ref name=\"Archer, p. 14\">Archer, p. 14</ref> MacGuire had known Robert S. Clark when he was a second lieutenant in [[China]] during the [[Boxer Rebellion]].  Clark had been nicknamed \"the millionaire lieutenant\".<ref name=\"Archer, p. 14\"/>\n\n====1934====\nDuring the first half of 1934, MacGuire traveled to Europe and mailed postcards to Butler.<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 3|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, p. 3]]</ref> On March 6, MacGuire wrote Clark and Clark's attorney a letter describing the [[Croix-de-Feu]].<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 10|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, p. 10]]</ref>\n\nOn August 22, Butler met MacGuire at a hotel, the last time Butler met him.<ref>Archer, p. 153</ref><ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 3|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, p. 3]] and [[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 20|p. 20]]</ref> According to Butler's account, it was on this occasion that MacGuire asked Butler to run a new veterans' organization and lead a coup attempt against the President.\n\nOn September 13, [[Paul Comly French]], a [[investigative journalism|reporter]] who had once been Butler's personal secretary,<ref>Mennonite Church Historical Archives [http://www.mcusa-archives.org/Archives/scannedphotos/Mennonite%20Central%20Committee,%201920-%20(IX)/Civilian%20Public%20Service%20(CPS)%20Photos,%201941-47%20(IX-13-2-2)/General,%20Paul%20C%20French%20(1-2a)/French,%20Paul%20Comly%20-%200D2%20-%201944.pdf Paul French Biographical Information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604000410/http://www.mcusa-archives.org/Archives/scannedphotos/Mennonite%20Central%20Committee%2C%201920-%20%28IX%29/Civilian%20Public%20Service%20%28CPS%29%20Photos%2C%201941-47%20%28IX-13-2-2%29/General%2C%20Paul%20C%20French%20%281-2a%29/French%2C%20Paul%20Comly%20-%200D2%20-%201944.pdf |date=2011-06-04 }}</ref> met MacGuire in his office.<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 5|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, pg. 5]]</ref> In late September, Butler told Van Zandt that co-conspirators would be meeting him at an upcoming [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] convention.\n\nOn November 20 the Committee began examining evidence. Journalist [[Paul Comly French]] broke the story in the ''[[Philadelphia Record]]'' and ''[[New York Post]]'' on November 21.<ref>Archer, p. 139</ref>  On November 22, ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote its first article on the story and described it as a \"gigantic hoax\".<ref name=\"nyt112234\"/><ref name=\"schmidt224\"/>\n\n===Committee reports===\nThe Congressional committee preliminary report said:\n\n<blockquote>This committee has had no evidence before it that would in the slightest degree warrant calling before it such men as [[John W. Davis]], Gen. [[Hugh S. Johnson|Hugh Johnson]], General [[James Harbord|Harbord]], [[Thomas W. Lamont]], Admiral [[William Sims|Sims]], or [[Hanford MacNider]].\n<br>The committee will not take cognizance of names brought into the testimony which constitute mere hearsay.\n<br>This committee is not concerned with premature newspaper accounts especially when given and published prior to the taking of the testimony.\n<br>As the result of information which has been in possession of this committee for some time, it was decided to hear the story of Maj. Gen. Smedley D. Butler and such others as might have knowledge germane to the issue. ...</blockquote>\n\nThe Congressional committee final report said:\n\n<blockquote>In the last few weeks of the committee's official life it received evidence showing that certain persons had made an attempt to establish a fascist organization in this country. No evidence was presented and this committee had none to show a connection between this effort and any fascist activity of any European country. There is no question that these attempts were discussed, were planned, and might have been placed in execution when and if the financial backers deemed it expedient.\n<br>This committee received evidence from Maj. Gen Smedley D. Butler (retired), twice decorated by the Congress of the United States. He testified before the committee as to conversations with one Gerald C. MacGuire in which the latter is alleged to have suggested the formation of a fascist army under the leadership of General Butler.\n<br>MacGuire denied these allegations under oath, but your committee was able to verify all the pertinent statements made by General Butler, with the exception of the direct statement suggesting the creation of the organization. This, however, was corroborated in the correspondence of MacGuire with his principal, Robert Sterling Clark, of New York City, while MacGuire was abroad studying the various forms of veterans organizations of Fascist character.<ref>74th Congress House of Representatives Report, pursuant to House Resolution No. 198, 73d Congress, February 15, 1935. Quoted in: George Seldes, ''1000 Americans'' (1947), pp.&nbsp;290\u2013292. See also Schmidt, p. 245</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Contemporary reaction==\nA ''The New York Times'' editorial dismissed Butler's story as \"a gigantic hoax\" and a \"bald and unconvincing narrative.\"<ref name=\"nyt112234\">{{cite news|title=Credulity Unlimited|date=November 22, 1934|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1934/11/22/archives/credulity-unlimited.html|work=[[The New York Times]]<!--|accessdate=2009-03-03-->}}</ref><ref name=\"schmidt224\">{{cite book|last=Schmidt|authorlink=|title= Maverick Marine|publisher=[[University Press of Kentucky]]|year=1998|edition=reprint, illustrated|pages=224|isbn=0-8131-0957-4|first=Hans}}</ref> Thomas W. Lamont of [[J.P. Morgan & Co.|J.P. Morgan]] called it \"perfect moonshine\".<ref name=\"schmidt224\"/> Gen. Douglas MacArthur, alleged to be the back-up leader of the [[putsch]] if Butler declined, referred to it as \"the best laugh story of the year.\"<ref name=\"schmidt224\"/> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine and other publications also scoffed at the allegations.\n\nWhen the committee released its report, editorials remained skeptical. ''Time'' wrote: \"Also last week the House Committee on Un-American Activities purported to report that a two-month investigation had convinced it that General Butler's story of a Fascist march on Washington was alarmingly true.\" ''The New York Times'' reported that the committee \"alleged that definite proof had been found that the much publicized Fascist march on Washington, which was to have been led by Maj. Gen. Smedley D. Butler, retired, according to testimony at a hearing, was actually contemplated.\"<ref name=time>{{cite magazine|title=Plot Without Plotters|magazine=Time magazine|date=1934-12-03|volume=|issue=|pages=|url= http://www.livejournal.com/users/bailey83221/47109.html}}<br> {{cite journal|title= Gen. Butler Bares 'Fascist Plot' To Seize Government by Force; Says Bond Salesman, as Representative of Wall St. Group, Asked Him to Lead Army of 500,000 in March on Capital \u2013 Those Named Make Angry Denials \u2013 Dickstein Gets Charge.|journal=The New York Times|date=1934-11-21|pages=1|url=}}; <br> Philadelphia Record, November 21 and 22, 1934;''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine, February 25, 1935: <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\"Also last week the House Committee on Un-American Activities purported to report that a two-month investigation had convinced it that General Butler's story of a Fascist march on Washington was alarmingly true.\"</span><br> ''[[The New York Times]]'' February 16, 1935. p. 1, <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\"Asks Laws To Curb Foreign Agitators; Committee In Report To House Attacks Nazis As The Chief Propagandists In Nation. State Department Acts Checks Activities Of An Italian Consul \u2013 Plan For March On Capital Is Held Proved. Asks Laws To Curb Foreign Agitators, \"Plan for \u201cMarch\u201d Recalled. It also alleged that definite proof had been found that the much publicized Fascist march on Washington, which was to have been led by Major. Gen. Smedley D. Butler, retired, according to testimony at a hearing, was actually contemplated. The committee recalled testimony by General Butler, saying he had testified that Gerald C. MacGuire had tried to persuade him to accept the leadership of a Fascist army.\"</span></ref><ref>Archer, p. 173<br>Philadelphia Post, November 22, 1934</ref>\n \nSeparately, Veterans of Foreign Wars commander [[James E. Van Zandt]] stated to the press, \"Less than two months\" after Gen. Butler warned him, \"he had been approached by 'agents of Wall Street' to lead a Fascist dictatorship in the United States under the guise of a 'Veterans Organization'.\"<ref>Schlesinger, p 85; Wolfe, Part IV: <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\"But James E. Van Zandt, national commander of the Veterans of Foreign Wars and subsequently a Republican congressman, corroborated Butler's story and said that he, too, had been approached by \"agents of Wall Street\". \"Zandt had been called immediately after the August 22 meeting with MacGuire by Butler and warned that...he was going to be approached by the coup plotters for his support at an upcoming VFW convention. He said that, just as Butler had warned, he had been approached \"by agents of Wall Street\" who tried to enlist him in their plot.\"</span>{{cite journal|date=1934-11-23 |title=Says Butler Described. Offer. |journal=The New York Times |pages=3 |url=http://bailey83221.livejournal.com/68822.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061020014333/http://bailey83221.livejournal.com/68822.html |archivedate=2006-10-20 }} ''Quoted material from the NYT''<br>Schmidt, p. 224 <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">But James E. Van Zandt, national commander of the Veterans of Foreign Wars and subsequently a Republican congressman, corroborated Butler's story and said that he, too, had been approached by \"agents of Wall Street.\" </span> <br>Archer, p.3, 5, 29, 32, 129, 176.</ref>\n\n==Later reactions==\n\n[[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning historian [[Arthur M. Schlesinger, Jr.]] said in 1958, \"Most people agreed with Mayor [[Fiorello La Guardia|La Guardia]] of New York in dismissing it as a 'cocktail putsch'\" ([[Argument from authority|argumentum ab auctoritate]] via a very likely fabricated [[Argumentum ad populum|argumentum ad populum]]). <ref>Wolfe, Part IV: \"New York's Mayor Fiorello LaGuardia,..&nbsp; a (supporter) of the fascist program of Mussolini, coined the term ''cocktail putsch'' to describe the Butler story: It's a joke of some kind, he told the wire services, \"someone at a party had suggested the idea to the ex-marine as a joke.\"</ref> In Schlesinger's summation of the affair in 1958, \"No doubt, MacGuire did have some wild scheme in mind, though the gap between contemplation and execution was considerable, and it can hardly be supposed that the Republic was in much danger.\"<ref name=schlesinger83>Schlesinger, p. 83</ref>\n\nRobert F. Burk wrote, \"At their core, the accusations probably consisted of a mixture of actual attempts at influence peddling by a small core of financiers with ties to veterans organizations and the self-serving accusations of Butler against the enemies of his pacifist and populist causes.\"<ref name=burk>{{cite book|last=Burk|first=Robert F.|title=The Corporate State and the Broker State: The Du Ponts and American National Politics, 1925\u20131940|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1990|isbn=0-674-17272-8|url=https://archive.org/details/corporatestatet00burk}}</ref>\n\nHans Schmidt wrote, \"Even if Butler was telling the truth, as there seems little reason to doubt, there remains the unfathomable problem of MacGuire's motives and veracity. He may have been working both ends against the middle, as Butler at one point suspected. In any case, MacGuire emerged from the HUAC hearings as an inconsequential trickster whose base dealings could not possibly be taken alone as verifying such a momentous undertaking. If he was acting as an intermediary in a genuine probe, or as agent provocateur sent to fool Butler, his employers were at least clever enough to keep their distance and see to it that he self-destructed on the witness stand.\"<ref name=schmidt226>Schmidt p. 226, 228, 229, 230</ref>\n\n===Prescott Bush===\n<!-- NOTE: THIS SECTION QUICKLY EXPLAINS THE 2007 HARPERS MAGAZINE ARTICLE AND STATES THAT BUSH WAS NOT INVOLVED. SEE TALK PAGE OF PRESCOTT BUSH-->In July 2007, [[Scott Horton (attorney)|Scott Horton]] wrote an article in ''Harper's Magazine'' claiming that [[Prescott Bush]], father of US President [[George H. W. Bush]] and grandfather of US president [[George W. Bush]], was involved in the 1934 Business Plot.<ref>[https://harpers.org/blog/2007/07/1934-the-plot-against-america/ 1934: The Plot Against America], Scott Horton, Harper's Magazine, July 28, 2007</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Roosevelt dictatorship]]\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|title=The McCormack Dickstein Committee | url = https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/McCormack\u2013Dickstein_Committee }}\n* {{cite book|last=Archer|first=Jules|title=The Plot to Seize the White House|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing|origyear=1973|year=2007|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-1-60239-036-2|url=http://www.clubhousewreckards.com/plot/plottoseizethewhitehouse.htm|quote=Book Information and Chapter|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060211190309/http://clubhousewreckards.com/plot/plottoseizethewhitehouse.htm|archivedate=2006-02-11}} [https://www.jstor.org/stable/491493 online review]\n* {{cite book|last=Denton|first=Sally|title=The Plots Against the President: FDR, A Nation in Crisis, and the Rise of the American Right|publisher=Bloomsbury Press|year=2012|isbn=978-1-60819-089-8|url=https://archive.org/details/plotsagainstpres0000dent}}  Interview of the author and an excerpt are available at NPR's \"When The Bankers Plotted To Overthrow FDR\" [https://www.npr.org/2012/02/12/145472726/when-the-bankers-plotted-to-overthrow-fdr.html here] \n* {{cite journal|last=Feran |first=Tim |title=History Channel Looks At Plot to Oust FDR |journal=Columbus Dispatch (Ohio) |date=1999-02-12 |volume= |issue= |pages=1H |url=http://store.aetv.com/html/search/index.jhtml?search=The+Plot+to+Overthrow+FDR&itemType=All&x=15&y=10 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*{{cite book|last=Schlesinger Jr.|first=Arthur M.|authorlink=Arthur M. Schlesinger, Jr.|title=The Politics of Upheaval: 1935\u20131936, The Age of Roosevelt, Volume III (The Age of Roosevelt)|publisher=Mariner Books|year=1958|isbn=0-618-34087-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/politicsofupheav0000schl}}\n*{{cite book|last=Schmidt|first=Hans|authorlink=|title=Maverick Marine: General Smedley D. Butler and the Contradictions of American Military History|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|year=1998|isbn=0-8131-0957-4}} \n* {{cite book|last=Seldes|first=George|authorlink=George Seldes|title= 1000 Americans: The Real Rulers of the U.S.A.|publisher=Boni & Gaer|year=1947|id=ASIN: B000ANE968 | quote = pp. 292\u2013298  }}\n* {{cite book|last=Spivak|first=John L.|authorlink=John L. Spivak|title=A Man in His Time|url=https://archive.org/details/maninhistime00spiv|url-access=registration|publisher=Horizon Press|year=1967|id= ASIN: B0007DMOCW}} pp.&nbsp;294\u2013298 .\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource|McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee}}\n* {{cite journal | last = Adams | first = Cecil | title = Oh, Smedley: Was there really a fascist plot to overthrow the United States government? | journal = The Straight Dope | date = 2005-11-18 | volume = | issue = | pages = | url = http://www.straightdope.com/columns/051118.html }}\n* U.S. House of Representatives, Special Committee on Un-American Activities, Public Statement, 73rd Congress, 2nd session, (Washington, D.C.: Government Printing Office, 1934)[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Public Statement on Preliminary findings of HUAC, November 24, 1934]]\n* U.S. House of Representatives, Special Committee on Un-American Activities, Investigation of Nazi Propaganda Activities and Investigation of Certain Other Propaganda Activities, Hearings 73-D.C.-6, Part 1, 73rd Congress, 2nd session, (Washington, D.C.: Government Printing Office, 1935).\n* {{cite journal | last = Spivak | first = John L. | authorlink = John L. Spivak | title = Wall Street's Fascist Conspiracy: Testimony that the Dickstein MacCormack Committee Suppressed; Wall Street's Fascist Conspiracy: Morgan Pulls the Strings | journal = New Masses | date = Jan\u2013Feb 1935 | volume = | issue = | pages = | url = http://coat.ncf.ca/our_magazine/links/53/spivak-NewMasses.pdf }}\n\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1933]]\n[[Category:1933 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Great Depression in the United States]]\n[[Category:Political history of the United States]]\n[[Category:Presidency of Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in the United States]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Fascism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Military coups in the United States]]\n[[Category:1930s coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Political conspiracy in 1933 in the United States}}\nThe '''Business Plot ''' was a [[Conspiracy (political)|political conspiracy]] in 1933 in the United States.  Retired [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]] [[Major General (United States)|Major General]] [[Smedley Butler]] revealed that wealthy businessmen were plotting to create a [[Fascism|fascist]] veterans' organization with Butler as its leader and use it in a [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] to overthrow President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]. In 1934, Butler testified before the [[United States House of Representatives]] [[House Un-American Activities Committee#Special Committee on Un-American Activities (1934-1937)|Special Committee on Un-American Activities]] (the \"[[John William McCormack|McCormack]]\u2013[[Samuel Dickstein (congressman)|Dickstein]] Committee\") on these revelations.<ref name=\"Schlesinger, p. 85\">Schlesinger, p. 85</ref> No one was prosecuted.\n\nAt the time of the incidents, news media dismissed the plot, with a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' editorial characterizing it as a \"gigantic hoax\".<ref name=\"nyt112234\"/>  While historians have not accepted the notion of a plot, they agree that Butler described one.<ref name=burk/><ref name=schmidt226/><ref name=Fox>{{cite book|last1=Fox|title=The Clarks of Cooperstown|publisher=Knopf|year=2007|isbn=978-0-307-26347-6|url=https://archive.org/details/clarksofcooperst00webe}}</ref><ref name=\"schlesinger83\"/>\n\n==Background==\n\n===Butler and the veterans===\n[[Image:evictbonusarmy.jpg|thumb|260px|Shacks, erected by the [[Bonus Army]] on the [[Anacostia]] flats, burning after being set on fire by the US military (1932)]]\n{{Main|Bonus Army}}\n\nOn July 17, 1932, thousands of [[World War I]] veterans converged on [[Washington, D.C.]], set up tent camps, and demanded immediate payment of bonuses due to them according to the [[World War Adjusted Compensation Act]] of 1924 (the original act made the bonuses initially due no earlier than 1925 and no later than 1945). [[Walter W. Waters]], a former Army [[sergeant]], led this \"[[Bonus Army]]\". The Bonus Army was encouraged by an appearance from retired Marine Corps Maj. Gen. [[Smedley Butler]]; as a popular military figure of the time. A few days after Butler's arrival, President [[Herbert Hoover]] ordered the marchers removed and [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] [[cavalry]] troops under the command of Gen. [[Douglas MacArthur]] destroyed their camps.\n\nButler, although a self-described [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], responded by supporting [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] in the [[1932 United States presidential election|1932 US presidential election]].<ref name=\"support\">Schmidt, p. 219 <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\"Declaring himself a \"Hoover-for-Ex-President [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]],\" Smedley used the bonus issue and the army's use of gas in routing the \"Bonus Expeditionary Force\"--recalling infamous gas warfare during the Great War--to disparage Hoover during the [[1932 United States presidential election|1932 general elections]]. He came out for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] \"despite the fact that my family for generations has been Republican,\" and shared the platform when Republican [[United States Senate|Sen.]] [[George W. Norris]] opened a coast-to-coast stump for FDR in Philadelphia....Butler was pleased with the election results that saw Hoover defeated; although he admitted that he had exerted himself in the campaign more \"to get rid of Hoover than to put in Roosevelt,\" and to \"square a debt.\" FDR, his old [[Haiti]] ally, was a \"nice fellow\" and might make a good president, but Smedley did not expect much influence in the new administration.\"</span>\n</ref> By 1933 Butler started denouncing [[capitalism]] and bankers, going on to explain that for 33 years he had been a \"high-class muscle man\" for Wall Street, the bankers and big business, labeling himself as a \"racketeer for Capitalism.\"<ref>Smedley D. Butler, ''[[War is a Racket]]'' (Los Angeles: Feral House, 1935, 2003), 26</ref>\n\n===Reaction to Roosevelt===\nRoosevelt's election was upsetting for many conservative businessmen of the time, as his \"campaign promise that the government would provide jobs for all the unemployed had the perverse effect of creating a new wave of unemployment by businessmen frightened by fears of socialism and reckless government spending.\"<ref name=\"power\">{{cite book|title=The Power of Gold: the history of an obsession|url=https://archive.org/details/powerofgoldhisto00bern|url-access=registration|author=Peter L. Bernstein|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=NY, NY|year=2000|author-link=Peter L. Bernstein}}</ref> Some writers have said concerns over the [[gold standard]] were also involved; Jules Archer, in ''The Plot to Seize the White House'', wrote that with the end of the gold standard, \"conservative financiers were horrified. They viewed a currency not solidly backed by gold as [[inflation]]ary, undermining both private and business fortunes and leading to national bankruptcy. Roosevelt was damned as a socialist or Communist out to destroy private enterprise by sapping the gold backing of wealth in order to subsidize the poor.\"<ref name=\"Jules\"/>\n\n==McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee==\nThe Committee began examining evidence on November 20, 1934. On November 24 the committee released a statement detailing the testimony it had heard about the plot and its preliminary findings. On February 15, 1935, the committee submitted its final report to the House of Representatives.<ref name=\"plotx\" />\n\nDuring the McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee hearings Butler testified that [[Business Plot#1933|Gerald C. MacGuire]] attempted to recruit him to lead a coup, promising him an army of 500,000 men for a march on [[Washington, DC]], and financial backing. Butler testified that the pretext for the coup would be that the president's health was failing.<ref name=\"archerquote\">Archer, p. 155.</ref> Despite Butler's support for Roosevelt in the election<ref name=\"support\" /> and his reputation as a strong critic of capitalism,<ref>Schmidt, p. 231</ref> Butler said the plotters felt his good reputation and popularity were vital in attracting support amongst the general public and saw him as easier to manipulate than others. Given a successful coup, Butler said that the plan was for him to have held near-absolute power in the newly created position of \"Secretary of General Affairs\", while Roosevelt would have assumed a [[figurehead]] role. \n\nThose implicated in the plot by Butler all denied any involvement. MacGuire was the only figure identified by Butler who testified before the committee. Others Butler accused were not called to appear to testify because the \"committee has had no evidence before it that would in the slightest degree warrant calling before it such men ... The committee will not take cognizance of names brought into testimony which constitute mere hearsay.\"<ref name=page1>Public Statement on Preliminary findings of HUAC, November 24, 1934, page 1</ref>\n\nOn the final day of the committee,<ref>Archer, p. 189</ref> January 29, 1935, [[John L. Spivak]] published the first of two articles in the [[Communist Party USA|communist]] magazine ''[[New Masses]]'', revealing portions of the Congressional committee testimony that had been redacted as hearsay. Spivak argued that the plot was part of a plan by [[J.P. Morgan, Jr.|J.P. Morgan]] and other financiers who were coordinating with fascist groups to overthrow President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]].\n\nHans Schmidt concludes that while Spivak made a cogent argument for taking the suppressed testimony seriously, he embellished his article with his \"overblown\" claims regarding Jewish financiers, which Schmidt dismisses as [[guilt by association]] not supported by the evidence of the Butler-MacGuire conversations themselves.<ref name=\"plotx\">Archer, p. x ''(Foreword)''</ref><ref name=Schmidt229>Schmidt, p. 229</ref>\n\nOn March 25, 1935, MacGuire died in a hospital in [[New Haven, Connecticut]], at the age of 37. His attending doctor at the hospital attributed the death to [[pneumonia]] and its complications, but also said that the accusations against MacGuire had led to his weakened condition and collapse which in turn led to the pneumonia.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1935/03/26/archives/gc-mguire-dies-accused-of-plot-was-named-as-leading-wall-st-move-to.html G.C. M'Guire Dies; Accused of 'Plot'], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (March 26, 1935) (subscription).  An image of the article is also accessible down the page [http://imgur.com/gallery/ryG41 here].  Retrieved July 27, 2017.</ref>\n\n===Butler's testimony in detail===\n[[File:Universal Newsreel - Gen. Butler bares \"plot\" by fascists.ogv|thumb|Smedley Butler describes the alleged plot in 1933.]]\n{{synthesis|section|date=March 2009}}\n\n====1933====\nOn July 1, 1933, Butler met with MacGuire and Doyle for the first time. Gerald C. MacGuire was a $100-a-week bond salesman for [[Grayson Murphy|Grayson Murphy & Company]]<ref>Schmidt, p. 224</ref><ref name=\"record\">[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Testimony of Gerald C. Macguire]]</ref> and a member of the Connecticut American Legion.<ref>Archer, p. 6.</ref><ref name=\"contradicts\">This contradicts MacGuire's testimony: \"You are a past department commander in the American Legion?\" \"No, sir; never held an office in the American Legion, I have just been a Legionnaire--oh, I beg your pardon. I did hold one office. I was on the distinguished guest committee of the Legion in 1933, I believe.\" [[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Testimony of Gerald C. Macguire|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, testimony of Gerald C. MacGuire]]</ref> Bill Doyle was commander of the Massachusetts American Legion.<ref>Archer, p. 6</ref> Butler stated that he was asked to run for National Commander of the [[American Legion]].<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 1|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, p. 1]]</ref>\n\nOn July 3 or 4, Butler held a second meeting with MacGuire and Doyle. He stated that they offered to get hundreds of supporters at the American Legion convention to ask for a speech.<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Doyle and MacGuire's second visit|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report]]</ref> MacGuire left a typewritten speech with Butler that they proposed he read at the convention. \"It urged the American Legion convention to adopt a resolution calling for the United States to return to the gold standard, so that when veterans were paid the bonus promised to them, the money they received would not be worthless paper.\"<ref name=\"Jules\">{{cite book |author=Jules Archer|year=1973|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing |title=The Plot to Seize the White House: The Shocking True Story of the Conspiracy to Overthrow FDR}}</ref> The inclusion of this demand further increased Butler's suspicion.\n\nAround August 1, MacGuire visited Butler alone. Butler stated that MacGuire told him Grayson Murphy underwrote the formation of the American Legion in New York and Butler told MacGuire that the American Legion was \"nothing but a [[strikebreaking]] outfit.\"<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Third visit with MacGuire|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report]]</ref> Butler never saw Doyle again.\n\nOn September 24,<ref>Archer, p. 178</ref><ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 20|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, p. 20]]</ref> MacGuire visited Butler's hotel room in [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]].<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Meeting in hotel|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report]]</ref> In late September Butler met with [[Robert Sterling Clark]].<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Meeting with Clark|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report]]</ref> Clark was an art collector and an heir to the [[Singer Corporation]] fortune.<ref>Schmidt, p. 239, 241</ref><ref name=\"Archer, p. 14\">Archer, p. 14</ref> MacGuire had known Robert S. Clark when he was a second lieutenant in [[China]] during the [[Boxer Rebellion]].  Clark had been nicknamed \"the millionaire lieutenant\".<ref name=\"Archer, p. 14\"/>\n\n====1934====\nDuring the first half of 1934, MacGuire traveled to Europe and mailed postcards to Butler.<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 3|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, p. 3]]</ref> On March 6, MacGuire wrote Clark and Clark's attorney a letter describing the [[Croix-de-Feu]].<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 10|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, p. 10]]</ref>\n\nOn August 22, Butler met MacGuire at a hotel, the last time Butler met him.<ref>Archer, p. 153</ref><ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 3|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, p. 3]] and [[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 20|p. 20]]</ref> According to Butler's account, it was on this occasion that MacGuire asked Butler to run a new veterans' organization and lead a coup attempt against the President.\n\nOn September 13, [[Paul Comly French]], a [[investigative journalism|reporter]] who had once been Butler's personal secretary,<ref>Mennonite Church Historical Archives [http://www.mcusa-archives.org/Archives/scannedphotos/Mennonite%20Central%20Committee,%201920-%20(IX)/Civilian%20Public%20Service%20(CPS)%20Photos,%201941-47%20(IX-13-2-2)/General,%20Paul%20C%20French%20(1-2a)/French,%20Paul%20Comly%20-%200D2%20-%201944.pdf Paul French Biographical Information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604000410/http://www.mcusa-archives.org/Archives/scannedphotos/Mennonite%20Central%20Committee%2C%201920-%20%28IX%29/Civilian%20Public%20Service%20%28CPS%29%20Photos%2C%201941-47%20%28IX-13-2-2%29/General%2C%20Paul%20C%20French%20%281-2a%29/French%2C%20Paul%20Comly%20-%200D2%20-%201944.pdf |date=2011-06-04 }}</ref> met MacGuire in his office.<ref>[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Page 5|Wikisource: McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee report, pg. 5]]</ref> In late September, Butler told Van Zandt that co-conspirators would be meeting him at an upcoming [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] convention.\n\nOn November 20 the Committee began examining evidence. Journalist [[Paul Comly French]] broke the story in the ''[[Philadelphia Record]]'' and ''[[New York Post]]'' on November 21.<ref>Archer, p. 139</ref>  On November 22, ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote its first article on the story and described it as a \"gigantic hoax\".<ref name=\"nyt112234\"/><ref name=\"schmidt224\"/>\n\n===Committee reports===\nThe Congressional committee preliminary report said:\n\n<blockquote>This committee has had no evidence before it that would in the slightest degree warrant calling before it such men as [[John W. Davis]], Gen. [[Hugh S. Johnson|Hugh Johnson]], General [[James Harbord|Harbord]], [[Thomas W. Lamont]], Admiral [[William Sims|Sims]], or [[Hanford MacNider]].\n<br>The committee will not take cognizance of names brought into the testimony which constitute mere hearsay.\n<br>This committee is not concerned with premature newspaper accounts especially when given and published prior to the taking of the testimony.\n<br>As the result of information which has been in possession of this committee for some time, it was decided to hear the story of Maj. Gen. Smedley D. Butler and such others as might have knowledge germane to the issue. ...</blockquote>\n\nThe Congressional committee final report said:\n\n<blockquote>In the last few weeks of the committee's official life it received evidence showing that certain persons had made an attempt to establish a fascist organization in this country. No evidence was presented and this committee had none to show a connection between this effort and any fascist activity of any European country. There is no question that these attempts were discussed, were planned, and might have been placed in execution when and if the financial backers deemed it expedient.\n<br>This committee received evidence from Maj. Gen Smedley D. Butler (retired), twice decorated by the Congress of the United States. He testified before the committee as to conversations with one Gerald C. MacGuire in which the latter is alleged to have suggested the formation of a fascist army under the leadership of General Butler.\n<br>MacGuire denied these allegations under oath, but your committee was able to verify all the pertinent statements made by General Butler, with the exception of the direct statement suggesting the creation of the organization. This, however, was corroborated in the correspondence of MacGuire with his principal, Robert Sterling Clark, of New York City, while MacGuire was abroad studying the various forms of veterans organizations of Fascist character.<ref>74th Congress House of Representatives Report, pursuant to House Resolution No. 198, 73d Congress, February 15, 1935. Quoted in: George Seldes, ''1000 Americans'' (1947), pp.&nbsp;290\u2013292. See also Schmidt, p. 245</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Contemporary reaction==\nA ''The New York Times'' editorial dismissed Butler's story as \"a gigantic hoax\" and a \"bald and unconvincing narrative.\"<ref name=\"nyt112234\">{{cite news|title=Credulity Unlimited|date=November 22, 1934|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1934/11/22/archives/credulity-unlimited.html|work=[[The New York Times]]<!--|accessdate=2009-03-03-->}}</ref><ref name=\"schmidt224\">{{cite book|last=Schmidt|authorlink=|title= Maverick Marine|publisher=[[University Press of Kentucky]]|year=1998|edition=reprint, illustrated|pages=224|isbn=0-8131-0957-4|first=Hans}}</ref> Thomas W. Lamont of [[J.P. Morgan & Co.|J.P. Morgan]] called it \"perfect moonshine\".<ref name=\"schmidt224\"/> Gen. Douglas MacArthur, alleged to be the back-up leader of the [[putsch]] if Butler declined, referred to it as \"the best laugh story of the year.\"<ref name=\"schmidt224\"/> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine and other publications also scoffed at the allegations.\n\nWhen the committee released its report, editorials remained skeptical. ''Time'' wrote: \"Also last week the House Committee on Un-American Activities purported to report that a two-month investigation had convinced it that General Butler's story of a Fascist march on Washington was alarmingly true.\" ''The New York Times'' reported that the committee \"alleged that definite proof had been found that the much publicized Fascist march on Washington, which was to have been led by Maj. Gen. Smedley D. Butler, retired, according to testimony at a hearing, was actually contemplated.\"<ref name=time>{{cite magazine|title=Plot Without Plotters|magazine=Time magazine|date=1934-12-03|volume=|issue=|pages=|url= http://www.livejournal.com/users/bailey83221/47109.html}}<br> {{cite journal|title= Gen. Butler Bares 'Fascist Plot' To Seize Government by Force; Says Bond Salesman, as Representative of Wall St. Group, Asked Him to Lead Army of 500,000 in March on Capital \u2013 Those Named Make Angry Denials \u2013 Dickstein Gets Charge.|journal=The New York Times|date=1934-11-21|pages=1|url=}}; <br> Philadelphia Record, November 21 and 22, 1934;''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine, February 25, 1935: <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\"Also last week the House Committee on Un-American Activities purported to report that a two-month investigation had convinced it that General Butler's story of a Fascist march on Washington was alarmingly true.\"</span><br> ''[[The New York Times]]'' February 16, 1935. p. 1, <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\"Asks Laws To Curb Foreign Agitators; Committee In Report To House Attacks Nazis As The Chief Propagandists In Nation. State Department Acts Checks Activities Of An Italian Consul \u2013 Plan For March On Capital Is Held Proved. Asks Laws To Curb Foreign Agitators, \"Plan for \u201cMarch\u201d Recalled. It also alleged that definite proof had been found that the much publicized Fascist march on Washington, which was to have been led by Major. Gen. Smedley D. Butler, retired, according to testimony at a hearing, was actually contemplated. The committee recalled testimony by General Butler, saying he had testified that Gerald C. MacGuire had tried to persuade him to accept the leadership of a Fascist army.\"</span></ref><ref>Archer, p. 173<br>Philadelphia Post, November 22, 1934</ref>\n \nSeparately, Veterans of Foreign Wars commander [[James E. Van Zandt]] stated to the press, \"Less than two months\" after Gen. Butler warned him, \"he had been approached by 'agents of Wall Street' to lead a Fascist dictatorship in the United States under the guise of a 'Veterans Organization'.\"<ref>Schlesinger, p 85; Wolfe, Part IV: <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\"But James E. Van Zandt, national commander of the Veterans of Foreign Wars and subsequently a Republican congressman, corroborated Butler's story and said that he, too, had been approached by \"agents of Wall Street\". \"Zandt had been called immediately after the August 22 meeting with MacGuire by Butler and warned that...he was going to be approached by the coup plotters for his support at an upcoming VFW convention. He said that, just as Butler had warned, he had been approached \"by agents of Wall Street\" who tried to enlist him in their plot.\"</span>{{cite journal|date=1934-11-23 |title=Says Butler Described. Offer. |journal=The New York Times |pages=3 |url=http://bailey83221.livejournal.com/68822.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061020014333/http://bailey83221.livejournal.com/68822.html |archivedate=2006-10-20 }} ''Quoted material from the NYT''<br>Schmidt, p. 224 <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">But James E. Van Zandt, national commander of the Veterans of Foreign Wars and subsequently a Republican congressman, corroborated Butler's story and said that he, too, had been approached by \"agents of Wall Street.\" </span> <br>Archer, p.3, 5, 29, 32, 129, 176.</ref>\n\n==Later reactions==\n\n[[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning historian [[Arthur M. Schlesinger, Jr.]] said in 1958, \"Most people agreed with Mayor [[Fiorello La Guardia|La Guardia]] of New York in dismissing it as a 'cocktail putsch'\" ([[Argument from authority|argumentum ab auctoritate]] via a very likely fabricated [[Argumentum ad populum|argumentum ad populum]]). <ref>Wolfe, Part IV: \"New York's Mayor Fiorello LaGuardia,..&nbsp; a (supporter) of the fascist program of Mussolini, coined the term ''cocktail putsch'' to describe the Butler story: It's a joke of some kind, he told the wire services, \"someone at a party had suggested the idea to the ex-marine as a joke.\"</ref> In Schlesinger's summation of the affair in 1958, \"No doubt, MacGuire did have some wild scheme in mind, though the gap between contemplation and execution was considerable, and it can hardly be supposed that the Republic was in much danger.\"<ref name=schlesinger83>Schlesinger, p. 83</ref>\n\nRobert F. Burk wrote, \"At their core, the accusations probably consisted of a mixture of actual attempts at influence peddling by a small core of financiers with ties to veterans organizations and the self-serving accusations of Butler against the enemies of his pacifist and populist causes.\"<ref name=burk>{{cite book|last=Burk|first=Robert F.|title=The Corporate State and the Broker State: The Du Ponts and American National Politics, 1925\u20131940|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1990|isbn=0-674-17272-8|url=https://archive.org/details/corporatestatet00burk}}</ref>\n\nHans Schmidt wrote, \"Even if Butler was telling the truth, as there seems little reason to doubt, there remains the unfathomable problem of MacGuire's motives and veracity. He may have been working both ends against the middle, as Butler at one point suspected. In any case, MacGuire emerged from the HUAC hearings as an inconsequential trickster whose base dealings could not possibly be taken alone as verifying such a momentous undertaking. If he was acting as an intermediary in a genuine probe, or as agent provocateur sent to fool Butler, his employers were at least clever enough to keep their distance and see to it that he self-destructed on the witness stand.\"<ref name=schmidt226>Schmidt p. 226, 228, 229, 230</ref>\n\n===Prescott Bush===\n<!-- NOTE: THIS SECTION QUICKLY EXPLAINS THE 2007 HARPERS MAGAZINE ARTICLE AND STATES THAT BUSH WAS NOT INVOLVED. SEE TALK PAGE OF PRESCOTT BUSH-->In July 2007, [[Scott Horton (attorney)|Scott Horton]] wrote an article in ''Harper's Magazine'' claiming that [[Prescott Bush]], father of US President [[George H. W. Bush]] and grandfather of US president [[George W. Bush]], was involved in the 1934 Business Plot.<ref>[https://harpers.org/blog/2007/07/1934-the-plot-against-america/ 1934: The Plot Against America], Scott Horton, Harper's Magazine, July 28, 2007</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Roosevelt dictatorship]]\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|title=The McCormack Dickstein Committee | url = https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/McCormack\u2013Dickstein_Committee }}\n* {{cite book|last=Archer|first=Jules|title=The Plot to Seize the White House|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing|origyear=1973|year=2007|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-1-60239-036-2|url=http://www.clubhousewreckards.com/plot/plottoseizethewhitehouse.htm|quote=Book Information and Chapter|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060211190309/http://clubhousewreckards.com/plot/plottoseizethewhitehouse.htm|archivedate=2006-02-11}} [https://www.jstor.org/stable/491493 online review]\n* {{cite book|last=Denton|first=Sally|title=The Plots Against the President: FDR, A Nation in Crisis, and the Rise of the American Right|publisher=Bloomsbury Press|year=2012|isbn=978-1-60819-089-8|url=https://archive.org/details/plotsagainstpres0000dent}}  Interview of the author and an excerpt are available at NPR's \"When The Bankers Plotted To Overthrow FDR\" [https://www.npr.org/2012/02/12/145472726/when-the-bankers-plotted-to-overthrow-fdr.html here] \n* {{cite journal|last=Feran |first=Tim |title=History Channel Looks At Plot to Oust FDR |journal=Columbus Dispatch (Ohio) |date=1999-02-12 |volume= |issue= |pages=1H |url=http://store.aetv.com/html/search/index.jhtml?search=The+Plot+to+Overthrow+FDR&itemType=All&x=15&y=10 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*{{cite book|last=Schlesinger Jr.|first=Arthur M.|authorlink=Arthur M. Schlesinger, Jr.|title=The Politics of Upheaval: 1935\u20131936, The Age of Roosevelt, Volume III (The Age of Roosevelt)|publisher=Mariner Books|year=1958|isbn=0-618-34087-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/politicsofupheav0000schl}}\n*{{cite book|last=Schmidt|first=Hans|authorlink=|title=Maverick Marine: General Smedley D. Butler and the Contradictions of American Military History|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|year=1998|isbn=0-8131-0957-4}} \n* {{cite book|last=Seldes|first=George|authorlink=George Seldes|title= 1000 Americans: The Real Rulers of the U.S.A.|publisher=Boni & Gaer|year=1947|id=ASIN: B000ANE968 | quote = pp. 292\u2013298  }}\n* {{cite book|last=Spivak|first=John L.|authorlink=John L. Spivak|title=A Man in His Time|url=https://archive.org/details/maninhistime00spiv|url-access=registration|publisher=Horizon Press|year=1967|id= ASIN: B0007DMOCW}} pp.&nbsp;294\u2013298 .\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource|McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee}}\n* {{cite journal | last = Adams | first = Cecil | title = Oh, Smedley: Was there really a fascist plot to overthrow the United States government? | journal = The Straight Dope | date = 2005-11-18 | volume = | issue = | pages = | url = http://www.straightdope.com/columns/051118.html }}\n* U.S. House of Representatives, Special Committee on Un-American Activities, Public Statement, 73rd Congress, 2nd session, (Washington, D.C.: Government Printing Office, 1934)[[s:McCormack\u2013Dickstein Committee#Public Statement on Preliminary findings of HUAC, November 24, 1934]]\n* U.S. House of Representatives, Special Committee on Un-American Activities, Investigation of Nazi Propaganda Activities and Investigation of Certain 