{"title_page": "Truth or Dare (2011 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|British psychological thriller film}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Truth or Dare\n| image          = \n| border         = \n| alt            =\n| caption        = \n| director       = Robert Heath\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Richard Johns (producer)|Richard Johns]]\n* Rupert Jermyn\n}}\n| writer         = Matthew McGuchan\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[David Oakes]]\n* [[Liam Boyle (actor)|Liam Boyle]] \n* [[Jack Gordon (actor)|Jack Gordon]]\n* Florence Hall \n* [[Jennie Jacques]]\n* Tom Kane\n* [[Jason Maza]]\n* [[Alexander Vlahos]]\n}}\n| music          = Richard Pryn\n| cinematography = James Friend \n| editing        = Oliver Parker\n| studio = {{plainlist|\n* AV Pictures\n* Met Film Post\n}}\n| distributor    = Corona Pictures  \n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2011|11|3}} {{small|([[American Film Market]])}} {{Film date|df=y|2012|8|27}} {{small|(United Kingdom)}}  {{Film date|df=y|2012|10|9}} {{small|(United States)}} \n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''Truth or Dare'''''<ref name=\"truthordare2\"/> (released in the U.S. as '''''Truth or Die''''') is a 2011 British [[psychological thriller]] film directed by Robert Heath and written by Matthew McGuchan. The film stars [[David Oakes]], Tom Kane, [[Jennie Jacques]], [[Liam Boyle (actor)|Liam Boyle]], [[Jack Gordon (actor)|Jack Gordon]], Florence Hall and [[Alexander Vlahos]].\n\n==Plot==\nThe movie begins with a past reference of house party during a summer camp where folks were enjoying. A guy named Felix enters the party. Another group of friends is to be seen where Chris, a spoilt brat with his girlfriend, Gemma, and Paul with his girlfriend, Eleanor.\n\nIt seemed Felix was deeply in love with Gemma and he was stalking her just like the other day, catching Luke's attention. Luke then convinced him to go and talk to her although knowing of the upcoming consequences. Felix asks her out but she denies. He was hurt. Paul passed out so Eleanor decided to play truth or dare with all the people present.\n\nWhen it was Felix's turn, he chooses truth, and Eleanor asks him to pick anyone he'd like to fulfill his fantasy with. He chooses Gemma. Chris punches him thus he becomes hurt. Gemma dumps Chris and runs to consolidate Felix.\n\nIn the present day, after college lets out, all five of them get an invitation to visit Felix to surprise him on his birthday. They all reach the place and reunite. In front of a big mansion, they try to find a way in but soon are interrupted by a strange old man who tells them the correct address. They walk through the woods to reach a small farmhouse where they're welcomed by a mysterious, handsome man named Justin, the elder brother of Felix.\n\nThey all start settling down for a party when Justin starts the game of truth or dare to accelerate the fun. While playing the game Justin begins asking them questions from that night and reveals to everyone that he lied about Felix's suicide. When they try to stop him he shoots Chris and ties up everyone except Luke whom he convinces to be his partner throughout the night. He tortures them using truth or dare as a means to reveal who hurt his brother including the force feeding of a random choice of similar looking vats of battery acid or water. However, this is soon interrupted by an intruder whom he kills with the help of Luke.\n\nIn the meantime, Gemma escapes and Justin goes out to find her. She reaches the mansion for help but is terrified to see Felix alive but paralyzed. Felix's caretaker attempts to wrestle the gun away from her, where he is fatally wounded. Later on, Justin arrives and kills her in front of his brother. Luke is persuaded by Eleanor and Paul to free them up, but as he denies Eleanor manages to free herself by biting Luke's little finger off and impaling the back of his head on a tool lying on the floor. When Justin comes back with Felix, he is attacked by Eleanor awakes tied to a post by Eleanor. She tells them that actually on that night she made Felix perform oral sex with Paul, who was already passed out. He attempts to die by suicide out of fear of his brother, Justin. She then gives Felix a grenade and escapes with Paul, while the house gets blown up, killing both the brothers.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[David Oakes]] as Justin\n* Tom Kane as Fenix\n* [[Liam Boyle (actor)|Liam Boyle]] as Paul\n* [[Jack Gordon (actor)|Jack Gordon]] as Chris\n* Florence Hall as Gemma\n* [[Jennie Jacques]] as Eleanor\n* [[Alexander Vlahos]] as Luke\n* [[Jason Maza]] as Jonesy\n* [[David Sterne]] as Woodbridge\n\n==Release==\nThe film premiered at the [[American Film Market]] on 3 November 2011.<ref name=\"truthordare2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.28dayslateranalysis.com/2011/10/truth-or-dare-turns-to-pain-and-revenge.html|title=Truth or Dare Turns to Pain and Revenge at the AFM: Preview|last=Allen|first=Michael|date=22 October 2011|work=28 Days Later Analysis|access-date=10 October 2018}}</ref> \n\n===Home media===\n''Truth or Dare'' was released [[straight-to-video]] on 27 August 2012 in the United Kingdom<ref name=\"truthordare1\">{{cite web|url=http://wearemoviegeeks.com/2012/08/truth-or-dare-new-photos-arrives-on-blu-ray-dvd-itunes-august-27-in-uk/|title=TRUTH OR DARE New Photos \u2013 Arrives On Blu-ray, DVD & iTunes August 27 In UK|date=9 August 2012|work=We Are Movie Geeks|access-date=10 October 2018}}</ref> and 9 October in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/horror/news/728862-watch-four-clips-for-the-thriller-truth-or-die-aka-truth-or-dare#kG4yXjRqgQVyOxOV.99|title=Watch Four Clips for the Thriller Truth or Die (aka Truth or Dare)|last=Turek|first=Ryan|date=20 August 2012|work=[[CraveOnline#Owned or associated websites|Coming Soon]]|accessdate=10 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nDave Aldridge of ''[[Radio Times]]'' stated in his negative review: \"''Truth or Dare'' is slickly made and decently acted. It has its bloody horror film moments, but director Robert Heath wisely puts equal emphasis on the psychology of its hostage situation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/film/rn9jr/truth-or-dare/|title=Truth or Dare (2011) \u2013 review|last=Aldridge|first=Dave|work=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1838722}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|truth_or_dare_2011|Truth or Dare}}\n\n[[Category:2011 independent films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:British independent films]]\n[[Category:British psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films about suicide]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British psychological thriller film}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Truth or Dare\n| image          = \n| border         = \n| alt            =\n| caption        = \n| director       = Robert Heath\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Richard Johns (producer)|Richard Johns]]\n* Rupert Jermyn\n}}\n| writer         = Matthew McGuchan\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[David Oakes]]\n* [[Liam Boyle (actor)|Liam Boyle]] \n* [[Jack Gordon (actor)|Jack Gordon]]\n* Florence Hall \n* [[Jennie Jacques]]\n* Tom Kane\n* [[Jason Maza]]\n* [[Alexander Vlahos]]\n}}\n| music          = Richard Pryn\n| cinematography = James Friend \n| editing        = Oliver Parker\n| studio = {{plainlist|\n* AV Pictures\n* Met Film Post\n}}\n| distributor    = Corona Pictures  \n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2011|11|3}} {{small|([[American Film Market]])}} {{Film date|df=y|2012|8|27}} {{small|(United Kingdom)}}  {{Film date|df=y|2012|10|9}} {{small|(United States)}} \n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''Truth or Dare'''''<ref name=\"truthordare2\"/> (released in the U.S. as '''''Truth or Die''''') is a 2011 British [[psychological thriller]] film directed by Robert Heath and written by Matthew McGuchan. The film stars [[David Oakes]], Tom Kane, [[Jennie Jacques]], [[Liam Boyle (actor)|Liam Boyle]], [[Jack Gordon (actor)|Jack Gordon]], Florence Hall and [[Alexander Vlahos]].\n\n==Plot==\nThe movie begins with a past reference of house party during a summer camp where folks were enjoying. A guy named Felix enters the party. Another group of friends is to be seen where Chris, a spoilt brat with his girlfriend, Gemma, and Paul with his girlfriend, Eleanor.\n\nIt seemed Felix was deeply in love with Gemma and he was stalking her just like the other day, catching Luke's attention. Luke then convinced him to go and talk to her although knowing of the upcoming consequences. Felix asks her out but she denies. He was hurt. Paul passed out so Eleanor decided to play truth or dare with all the people present.\n\nWhen it was Felix's turn, he choses truth, and Eleanor asks him to pick anyone he'd like to fulfill his fantasy with. He choses Gemma. Chris punches him thus he becomes hurt. Gemma dumps Chris and runs to consolidate Felix.\n\nIn the present day, after college lets out, all five of them get an invitation to visit Felix to surprise him on his birthday. They all reach the place and reunite. In front of a big mansion, they try to find a way in but soon are interrupted by a strange old man who tells them the correct address. They walk through the woods to reach a small farmhouse where they're welcomed by a mysterious, handsome man named Justin, the elder brother of Felix.\n\nThey all start settling down for a party when Justin starts the game of truth or dare to accelerate the fun. While playing the game Justin begins asking them questions from that night and reveals to everyone that he lied about Felix's suicide. When they try to stop him he shoots Chris and ties up everyone except Luke whom he convinces to be his partner throughout the night. He tortures them using truth or dare as a means to reveal who hurt his brother including the force feeding of a random choice of similar looking vats of battery acid or water. However, this is soon interrupted by an intruder whom he kills with the help of Luke.\n\nIn the mean time, Gemma escapes and Justin goes out to find her. She reaches the mansion for help but is terrified to see Felix alive but paralyzed. Felix's caretaker attempts to wrestle the gun away from her, where he is fatally wounded. Later on, Justin arrives and kills her in front of his brother. Luke is persuaded by Eleanor and Paul to free them up, but as he denies Eleanor manages to free herself by biting Luke's little finger off and impaling the back of his head on a tool lying on the floor. When Justin comes back with Felix, he is attacked by Eleanor awakes tied to a post by Eleanor. She tells them that actually on that night she made Felix perform oral sex with Paul, who was already passed out. He attempts to die by suicide out of fear of his brother, Justin. She then gives Felix a grenade and escapes with Paul, while the house gets blown up, killing both the brothers.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[David Oakes]] as Justin\n* Tom Kane as Fenix\n* [[Liam Boyle (actor)|Liam Boyle]] as Paul\n* [[Jack Gordon (actor)|Jack Gordon]] as Chris\n* Florence Hall as Gemma\n* [[Jennie Jacques]] as Eleanor\n* [[Alexander Vlahos]] as Luke\n* [[Jason Maza]] as Jonesy\n* [[David Sterne]] as Woodbridge\n\n==Release==\nThe film premiered at the [[American Film Market]] on 3 November 2011.<ref name=\"truthordare2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.28dayslateranalysis.com/2011/10/truth-or-dare-turns-to-pain-and-revenge.html|title=Truth or Dare Turns to Pain and Revenge at the AFM: Preview|last=Allen|first=Michael|date=22 October 2011|work=28 Days Later Analysis|access-date=10 October 2018}}</ref> \n\n===Home media===\n''Truth or Dare'' was released [[straight-to-video]] on 27 August 2012 in the United Kingdom<ref name=\"truthordare1\">{{cite web|url=http://wearemoviegeeks.com/2012/08/truth-or-dare-new-photos-arrives-on-blu-ray-dvd-itunes-august-27-in-uk/|title=TRUTH OR DARE New Photos \u2013 Arrives On Blu-ray, DVD & iTunes August 27 In UK|date=9 August 2012|work=We Are Movie Geeks|access-date=10 October 2018}}</ref> and 9 October in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/horror/news/728862-watch-four-clips-for-the-thriller-truth-or-die-aka-truth-or-dare#kG4yXjRqgQVyOxOV.99|title=Watch Four Clips for the Thriller Truth or Die (aka Truth or Dare)|last=Turek|first=Ryan|date=20 August 2012|work=[[CraveOnline#Owned or associated websites|Coming Soon]]|accessdate=10 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nDave Aldridge of ''[[Radio Times]]'' stated in his negative review: \"''Truth or Dare'' is slickly made and decently acted. It has its bloody horror film moments, but director Robert Heath wisely puts equal emphasis on the psychology of its hostage situation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/film/rn9jr/truth-or-dare/|title=Truth or Dare (2011) \u2013 review|last=Aldridge|first=Dave|work=[[Radio Times]]|accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1838722}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|truth_or_dare_2011|Truth or Dare}}\n\n[[Category:2011 independent films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:British independent films]]\n[[Category:British psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films about suicide]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:Typo fixing, replaced: choses \u2192 chooses (2),typo(s) fixed: In the mean time \u2192 In the meantime", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Truth_or_Dare_(2011_film)"}
{"title_page": "Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the performing arts", "text_new": "{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] has had a significant impact on the performing arts, mirroring its [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the arts and cultural heritage|impacts across all arts sectors]]. Due to physical distancing requirements and closure of the physical venues, curtailing not only public performances but also rehearsals, many performing arts institutions attempted to adapt by offering new (or newly expanded) digital services. In particular this resulted in the free [[online streaming]] of previously recorded performances of many companies \u2013 especially [[Orchestral|orchestral performances]] and [[Play (theatre)|plays]] \u2013 lists of which were collated by journalists<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/theatre/best-streaming-theatre-shows-how-to-watch-online|title=The best theatre to watch online right now|website=Time Out Worldwide|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Convery|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/20/livestreaming-schedule-music-art-literature-and-events-from-australia-and-beyond|title=Livestreaming schedule: music, art, literature and events from Australia and beyond|date=2020-03-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Rawson|first2=Sharnee|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/stage-shows-musicals-opera-free-stream-online_51198.html|title=Stage shows, musicals and opera you can watch online now for free {{!}} WhatsOnStage|website=www.whatsonstage.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> as well as bespoke crowdsourcing projects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://streams.culturaldigital.com/|title=Cultural Digital: Streams|last=Unitt|first=Chris|date=|website=streams.culturaldigital.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1JC9gQn8-e_hL6vZGPBENdt_a3QEkcZVmbi3rv4_xNzE/htmlview#gid=0|title=Free Theatre Screenings - Google Drive|website=docs.google.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==Performing arts events==\n===Theatre===\nMany theatre performances have been cancelled or delayed. [[The Broadway League]] announced they would shutdown all [[Broadway theatre]] until June 7.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/04/08/us/broadway-coronavirus-shutdown-extended-trnd/index.html|title=Broadway theaters extend coronavirus shutdown until early June|work=CNN|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> [[West End theatre|West End theatre]] have also closed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51906370|title=Coronavirus: West End shuts down as Boris Johnson's advice sparks anger|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n====Shows====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Shows\n!Location\n!Details\n!Source\n|-\n|''[[Waitress (musical)|Waitress]]''\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Adelphi Theatre]], [[London]], England\n|Close permanently after final performance on 16 March 2020.\n|<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2020/coronavirus-waitress-confirms-it-will-not-reopen-after-theatre-closures |title= Coronavirus: Waitress confirms it will not reopen after theatre closures|publisher=The Stage|last=Snow|first=Georgia|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Beetlejuice (musical)|Beetlejuice]]\n|{{flagicon|United States}} [[Winter Garden Theatre]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S. \n|Close at Winter Garden after final performance on 10 March 2020, may move to another theatre or tour\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/With-Closure-Official-BEETLEJUICE-Considering-Future-Production-Plans-Tour-20200408|title=With Closure Official ''Beetlejuice'' Considering Future Production Plans; Tour|last=Desk|first=BWW News|website=BroadwayWorld.com|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Hangmen (play)|Hangmen]]''\n|{{flagicon|United States}} [[John Golden Theatre]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S. \n|Cancelled after 13 previews\n|<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.playbill.com/article/hangmen-is-the-first-show-to-officially-announce-it-will-not-return-to-broadway|title=''Hangmen'' Is the First Show to Officially Announce It Will Not Return to Broadway|first=Dan|last=Meyer|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020||newspaper=[[Playbill]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?]]''\n|{{flagicon|United States}} [[Booth Theatre]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S. \n|2020 revival cancelled after 9 previews\n|<ref>[https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/WHOS-AFRAID-OF-VIRGINIA-WOOLF-Announces-Broadway-Closing-20200321 \" 'Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf' Announces Broadway Closing\"] broadwayworld.com, March 21, 2020</ref>\n|}\n\n====Events====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Event\n!Location\n!Details\n!Source\n|-\n|[[2020 Laurence Olivier Awards]]\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Royal Albert Hall]], [[London]], [[England]]\n|The awards ceremony in 2020 cancelled, with the awards being issued in an alternate manner.\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.playbill.com/article/olivier-awards-cancel-2020-ceremony |title=Olivier Awards Cancel 2020 Ceremony |last=McPhee |first=Ryan |date=17 March 2020 |publisher=[[Playbill]] |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[74th Tony Awards]]\n|{{flagicon|United States}} [[Radio City Music Hall]], [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|2020 Edition postponed.\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tonyawards.com/news/74th-annual-tony-awards-be-postponed/|title=The 74th Annual Tony Awards to Be Postponed|publisher=[[Tony Award|Tony Awards]]|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Dance===\n\n===Opera===\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n===Theatre===\n\n===Dance===\n\n===Opera===\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Performing arts]]\n[[Category:Theatre]]\n[[Category:Opera]]\n[[Category:Dance]]\n", "text_old": "{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] has had a significant impact on the performing arts, mirroring its [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the arts and cultural heritage|impacts across all arts sectors]]. Due to physical distancing requirements and closure of the physical venues, curtailing not only public performances but also rehearsals, many performing arts institutions attempted to adapt by offering new (or newly expanded) digital services. In particular this resulted in the free [[online streaming]] of previously recorded performances of many companies \u2013 especially [[Orchestral|orchestral performances]] and [[Play (theatre)|plays]] \u2013 lists of which were collated by journalists<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/theatre/best-streaming-theatre-shows-how-to-watch-online|title=The best theatre to watch online right now|website=Time Out Worldwide|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Convery|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/mar/20/livestreaming-schedule-music-art-literature-and-events-from-australia-and-beyond|title=Livestreaming schedule: music, art, literature and events from Australia and beyond|date=2020-03-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Rawson|first2=Sharnee|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/stage-shows-musicals-opera-free-stream-online_51198.html|title=Stage shows, musicals and opera you can watch online now for free {{!}} WhatsOnStage|website=www.whatsonstage.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> as well as bespoke crowdsourcing projects.<ref>{{Cite web|ur