]]\n| music          = Pierre Aviat\n| cinematography = [[Guy Dufaux]]\n| editing        = [[Isabelle Dedieu]]\n| studio         = [[Canal+]]<br />[[Telefilm Canada]]\n| distributor    = Pyramide Distribution {{small|(France)}}<br />[[Alliance Atlantis]] {{small|(Canada)}}<br />[[Miramax Films]] {{small|(US)}}\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2003|05|21|[[2003 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2003|09|24}}\n| runtime        = 99 minutes\n| country        = [[Canada]]<br />[[France]]\n| language       = French<br />English\n| budget         = {{USD}}5 million\n| gross          = {{USD}}26,924,656<ref>{{Mojo title|lesinvasionsbarbares}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Barbarian Invasions''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Les Invasions barbares'''}}) is a 2003 Canadian-French [[sex comedy]]-[[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] written and directed by [[Denys Arcand]] and starring [[R\u00e9my Girard]], [[St\u00e9phane Rousseau]] and [[Marie-Jos\u00e9e Croze]]. The film is a sequel to Arcand's 1986 film ''[[The Decline of the American Empire]]'', continuing the story of the character R\u00e9my, a womanizing history professor now terminally ill with cancer.\n\nThe sequel was a result of Arcand's longtime desire to make a film about a character close to death, also incorporating a response to the [[September 11 attacks]] of 2001. It was produced by companies from both Canada and France, and shot mainly in [[Montreal]], also employing a former hospital and property near [[Lake Memphremagog]].\n\nThe film received a positive response from critics and became one of Arcand's biggest financial successes. It was the first Canadian film to win the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]], at the [[76th Academy Awards]] in 2004. It won awards at the [[2003 Cannes Film Festival]], six [[24th Genie Awards|Genie Awards]], including [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Motion Picture|Best Motion Picture]], and three [[29th C\u00e9sar Awards|C\u00e9sar Awards]], including [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film|Best Film]]. ''The Barbarian Invasions'' was followed by the thematically related ''[[Days of Darkness (2007 Canadian film)|Days of Darkness]]'' in 2007 and ''[[The Fall of the American Empire]]'' in 2018.\n\n==Plot==\nSeventeen years after the events of ''[[The Decline of the American Empire]]'', S\u00e9bastien is enjoying a successful career in quantitative finance in [[London]] when he receives a call from his mother, Louise, that his father and Louise's ex-husband R\u00e9my is terminally ill with cancer. S\u00e9bastien is not enthused about seeing R\u00e9my, whom he blames for breaking up the family with his many [[adultery|adulteries]]. R\u00e9my and his friends of the older generation are still largely [[social democracy|social-democrats]] and proponents of [[Quebec nationalism]], positions seeming somewhat anachronistic long after the [[Quiet Revolution]] of the 1960s. R\u00e9my does not like S\u00e9bastien's career, lack of reading or fondness for video games.\n\nThe father and son travel to the [[U.S. state]] of [[Vermont]] to briefly receive medical care before returning to the overcrowded and disorganized Quebec hospital. S\u00e9bastien attempts to bribe hospital administration for better care, and calls R\u00e9my's old friends about a possible visit. Upon hearing [[heroin]] is \"800%\" more effective than morphine, he tracks some down for R\u00e9my from a drug addict, Nathalie.\n\nMeanwhile, R\u00e9my is reunited with his friends, including Pierre, Dominique, Claude and Diane, Nathalie's mother, and they share a conversation on their old sex drive and the gradual decline of their vitality. Diane is concerned for Nathalie, while R\u00e9my, a history professor, lectures the hospital chaplain Constance on the relative peace of the 20th century compared to past centuries. At the same time, another scholar describes the [[September 11 attacks]] as historically small except as a possible beginning of modern [[Migration Period|barbarian invasions]].  After R\u00e9my and his friends retreat to the countryside, they speak of their devotion to constantly evolving [[-ism]]s. R\u00e9my dies in the company of his friends and S\u00e9bastien, after a heroin injection from Nathalie, whom R\u00e9my calls his guardian angel.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[R\u00e9my Girard]] as R\u00e9my\n* [[St\u00e9phane Rousseau]] as S\u00e9bastien\n* [[Doroth\u00e9e Berryman]] as Louise\n* [[Louise Portal]] as Diane\n* [[Marie-Jos\u00e9e Croze]] as Nathalie\n* [[Marina Hands]] as Ga\u00eblle\n* [[Dominique Michel]] as Dominique\n* [[Pierre Curzi]] as Pierre\n* [[Yves Jacques]] as Claude\n* [[Isabelle Blais]] as Sylvaine\n* Toni Cecchinato as Alessandro\n* [[Sophie Lorain]] as First Lover\n* [[Mitsou|Mitsou G\u00e9linas]] as Ghislaine\n* [[Micheline Lanct\u00f4t]] as Nurse Carole\n* [[Johanne-Marie Tremblay]] as Sister Constance\n* [[Roy Dupuis]] as Narcotics Officer Gilles Levac\n* [[Lise Roy]] as Mme. Joncas-Pelletier{{sfn|Loiselle|2008|p=122}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n[[File:DenysArcand07TIFF.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Director [[Denys Arcand]] developed the idea for ''The Barbarian Invasions'' out of a fascination with death and theories on the [[September 11 attacks]].]]\n[[Denys Arcand]], who wrote and directed the successful French Canadian film ''[[The Decline of the American Empire]]'' (1986), developed the idea of returning to the characters years later due to a fascination with death and an idea of having a character who is expecting to die.{{sfn|Howell|2003|p=29}} Part of his interest in the subject matter related to both of his parents dying of cancer.<ref name=\"Sheffield\">{{cite news |last=Sheffield |first=Skip |date=2 January 2004 |title=Arcand creates refreshing glance at the inevitability of death |newspaper=[[Boca Raton News]] |page=3E}}</ref> He had tried to write screenplays about non-''Decline'' characters going to die for 20 years prior to ''The Barbarian Invasions'', originally pitching the idea to the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] but having difficulty with the subject matter being overly sentimental.{{sfn|Howell|2003|p=29}} He finally decided to try the story with characters from ''The Decline of the American Empire'' because of his fondness for its cast members.{{sfn|Howell|2003|p=29}} There are also characters from Arcand's 1989 film ''[[Jesus of Montreal]]'' in the film.{{sfn|Pike|2012|p=102}}\n\nThe [[September 11 attacks]] of 2001 occurred when Arcand was nearly finished his screenplay,<ref name=\"Associated\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.today.com/id/4417044/ns/today-today_entertainment/t/invasions-takes-foreign-language-oscar/#.V8JWNZgrLIU |title=\u2018Invasions\u2019 takes foreign-language Oscar |last=[[Associated Press]] |date=3 January 2004 |accessdate=27 August 2016 |work=[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009041859/http://www.today.com/id/4417044/ns/today-today_entertainment/t/invasions-takes-foreign-language-oscar/#.V8JWNZgrLIU#.V8JWNZgrLIU |archive-date=9 October 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and gave new impetus to Arcand's ideas of \"the decline of the [[American imperialism|American Empire]].\" Arcand believed the attack represented the first of what would be many foreign attacks on the U.S.{{sfn|Howell|2003|p=30}} Arcand also referred to himself as \"post[[-ism]]s\", and incorporated this discussion into the film.{{sfn|Howell|2003|p=31}}\n\nAnother statement he tried to make with his film was that [[heroin]] could be legalized for terminally ill patients in Canada, claiming it already is in England.<ref name=\"Sheffield\"/> Author Susan C. Boyd wrote that, despite what the film portrays, heroin has been legal in Canadian palliative care since 1984.{{sfn|Boyd|2008|p=109}} To research how his character would find heroin, Arcand contacted the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] and met with them in an interrogation room, resembling the one in the final film. He claimed the RCMP gave him the cellphone number of a Montreal detective, and when he called it, he heard shouting from a police raid on the [[Hells Angels]], which resulted in the arrest of [[Maurice Boucher]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Johnson |first=Brian D. |date=24 November 2003 |title=The Dying Art of Joie De Vivre|magazine=[[Maclean's]] |volume=116 |issue=47 |page=N}}</ref>\n\nThe film was produced by both Canadian and French companies, including [[Telefilm Canada]], [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Radio-Canada]] and [[Canal+]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2003/film/awards/the-barbarian-invasions-3-1200541506/ |title=Review: \u2018The Barbarian Invasions\u2019 |last=Nesselson |first=Lisa |date=21 May 2003 |accessdate=29 August 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911084443/http://variety.com/2003/film/awards/the-barbarian-invasions-3-1200541506/ |archive-date=11 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The budget was $6 million.<ref name=\"Strauss\">{{Cite web |url=http://playbackonline.ca/2003/09/01/cine-20030901/ |title=Dufaux, Arcand reunite on Barbarian Invasions |last=Strauss |first=Marise |date=1 September 2003 |accessdate=28 August 2016 |work=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911024554/http://playbackonline.ca/2003/09/01/cine-20030901/ |archive-date=11 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:St\u00e9phane Rousseau Cannes.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Comedian [[St\u00e9phane Rousseau]] was newly cast as S\u00e9bastien and won the [[24th Genie Awards|Genie Award]] for [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Performance by an Actor in a Supporting Role|Best Supporting Actor]] for the role.]]\nThe cast members from the previous film, including [[Dorothee Berryman]], [[Louise Portal]], [[Dominique Michel]], [[Pierre Curzi]] and [[Yves Jacques]], were easy to secure for the sequel.{{sfn|Howell|2003|p=29}} New to the cast was [[Marie-Jos\u00e9e Croze]], who was selected by Arcand after starring in the Canadian films ''[[Maelstrom (film)|Maelstrom]]'' (2000) and ''[[Ararat (film)|Ararat]]'' (2002). She found Arcand allowed her freedom in how she interpreted her role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fr.canoe.ca/divertissement/cinema/nouvelles/archives/2003/05/20030511-105835.html |title=Qui est Marie-Jos\u00e9e Croze? |last=Conde-Lord |first=Michelle |date=11 May 2003 |accessdate=29 August 2016|work=[[Canoe.ca]]}}</ref> In ''[[The Decline of the American Empire]]'', Croze's character Nathalie is played by [[child actress]] Ariane Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rique.{{sfn|Loiselle|2008|p=67}}\n\n[[St\u00e9phane Rousseau]], better known in Quebec as a stand-up comedian than an actor, was cast as S\u00e9bastien, after Dominique Michel urged Arcand to allow Rousseau to audition.{{sfn|Loiselle|2008|p=106}} Arcand explained he felt Rousseau had the \"authority\" the other actors who auditioned did not, though Rousseau was surprised to get the part as he felt his character was colder and more of an intellectual than he was. Rousseau's mother had died of cancer when he was a child, and he had fought with his father, later incorporating that experience into his performance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/11/16/movies/film-decades-later-a-cast-of-players-faces-the-biggest-chill.html?pagewanted=all |title=Decades Later, a Cast of Players Faces the Biggest Chill |last=Durbin |first=Karen |date=16 November 2003 |accessdate=29 August 2016 |work=[[The New York Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913110558/http://www.nytimes.com/2003/11/16/movies/film-decades-later-a-cast-of-players-faces-the-biggest-chill.html?pagewanted=all |archive-date=13 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nThe film was shot over 50 days, beginning in September 2002 and finishing in November. The bulk of the film was shot in Montreal, with some scenes filmed in London.<ref name=\"Strauss\"/> Footage from the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] attack shot by a Quebec architect and acquired by [[Radio-Canada]] was also used.{{sfn|Howell|2003|p=30}}\n\nFor the hospital scenes, the cast and crew employed Lachine General Hospital,{{sfn|Loiselle|2008|p=107}} an unused former hospital in [[Lachine, Quebec]]. Cinematographer [[Guy Dufaux]] found these scenes difficult to make interesting and realistic at the same time, and decided on more lighting for later scenes when the film's mood brightens, while using fluorescent fixtures and reflecting the former hospital's green painting to shoot the early scenes.<ref name=\"Strauss\"/> As with the first film, scenes were filmed near [[Lake Memphremagog]].{{sfn|Loiselle|2008|p=107}} Most of the film was shot using a [[Steadicam]].<ref name=\"Strauss\"/>\n\n==Release==\nNews that Arcand was working on a sequel to his 1986 film was received with a skeptical and negative response from critics.{{sfn|Pike|2012|p=102}} The film was screened at the [[2003 Cannes Film Festival]] in May, where it received a 22-minute standing ovation, with distribution to 30 countries assured by the time Arcand received his Best Screenplay award.<ref name=\"Odile\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ledevoir.com/culture/cinema/28459/festival-de-cannes-double-pour-les-invasions |title=Festival de Cannes - Doubl\u00e9 pour Les Invasions |last=Tremblay |first=Odile |date=26 May 2003 |accessdate=20 August 2016 |work=[[Le Devoir]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913150649/http://www.ledevoir.com/culture/cinema/28459/festival-de-cannes-double-pour-les-invasions |archive-date=13 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was afterwards selected to open the gala at the [[2003 Toronto International Film Festival]] in September,{{sfn|Howell|2003|p=28}} and also opened the [[Vancouver International Film Festival]] that month.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2003/film/markets-festivals/invasions-invades-vancouver-fest-1117891122/ |title=\u2018Invasions\u2019 invades Vancouver Fest |last=Townson |first=Don |date=19 August 2003 |accessdate=28 August 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911013720/http://variety.com/2003/film/markets-festivals/invasions-invades-vancouver-fest-1117891122/ |archive-date=11 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The film began playing in Quebec theatres in May and ran for months,{{sfn|Howell|2003|p=29}} with its Canadian distributor being [[Alliance Films]].<ref name=\"Telefilm\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.telefilm.ca/en/news/releases/2003/12/18/barbarian-invasions-nominated-golden-globe-nod-best-foreign-language-film |title=News Releases |last= |first= |date=18 December 2003 |accessdate=28 August 2016|work=[[Telefilm Canada]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924053609/https://www.telefilm.ca/en/news/releases/2003/12/18/barbarian-invasions-nominated-golden-globe-nod-best-foreign-language-film |archivedate=24 September 2016}}</ref> It opened across Canada on November 21.<ref name=\"Strauss\"/>\n\nAfter Cannes, rights were sold to [[Miramax]] for distribution of the film in the United States.<ref name=\"Radio\">{{Cite web|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/Index/nouvelles/200305/26/009-croze-arcand-cannes.shtml|title=Marie-Jos\u00e9e Croze couronn\u00e9e pour \"le plus beau r\u00f4le\" de sa vie|date=26 May 2003|accessdate=27 August 2016|work=[[Radio-Canada]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911044204/http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/Index/nouvelles/200305/26/009-croze-arcand-cannes.shtml|archive-date=11 September 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It opened in New York and Los Angeles on November 21.<ref name=\"Lacey\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/arcand-carries-off-the-oscar-for-best-foreign-film/article4087558/ |title=Arcand carries off the Oscar for best foreign film |last=Lacey |first=Liam |date=1 March 2004 |accessdate=29 August 2016 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918133210/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/arcand-carries-off-the-oscar-for-best-foreign-film/article4087558/ |archive-date=18 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In France, the film was available on 450 screens at one time, the most for a [[list of Quebec films|Quebec film]] ever.<ref name=\"Telefilm\"/>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nThe film's box office performance at Quebec theatres between its opening in May 2003 and the fall was considered good.{{sfn|Howell|2003|p=29}} By December, its initial release across Canada made $5.9 million.<ref name=\"Telefilm\"/>\n\nIn France, it grossed the equivalent of US$8 million.<ref name=\"Telefilm\"/> According to ''[[Box Office Mojo]]'', the film finished its run on June 3, 2004 after grossing $8,544,975 in North America and $18,379,681 in other territories, for a worldwide total of $26,924,656.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=barbarianinvasions.htm |title=The Barbarian Invasions |accessdate=28 August 2016 |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304061332/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=barbarianinvasions.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was one of Arcand's biggest box office successes.{{sfn|Pike|2012|p=102}}\n\n===Critical reception===\n[[File:MJCrozeCropped.jpg|thumb|right|[[Marie-Jos\u00e9e Croze]] received positive reviews for her performance, as well as the [[Best Actress Award (Cannes Film Festival)|Cannes Best Actress Award]] and [[24th Genie Awards|Genie Award]] for [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Performance by an Actress in a Supporting Role|Best Supporting Actress]].]]\n''The Barbarian Invasions'' has received positive reviews from numerous critics. In Canada, ''[[Maclean's]]'' critic [[Brian D. Johnson]] called it not only satirical but \"a moving elegy to a generation that defined modern Quebec and has seen its passions rendered obsolete\".<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Johnson |first=Brian D. |date=2 June 2003 |title=Barbarian Diversions|magazine=[[Maclean's]] |volume=116 |issue=2 |page=}}</ref> Liam Lacey wrote in ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' that the film is \"upbeat and wryly positive, or at least as much as you could expect from a film that condemns the Quebec hospital system and features a death by cancer as its central theme\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/slow-and-decidedly-sombre/article25284719/ |title=Slow and decidedly sombre |last=Lacey |first=Liam |date=21 May 2003 |accessdate=27 August 2016 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918103424/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/slow-and-decidedly-sombre/article25284719/ |archive-date=18 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The film drew general attention for its criticism of Quebec's health care system.<ref name=\"Lacey\"/> Peter Howell wrote in ''[[The Toronto Star]]'' that \"It's the depth of emotions Arcand summons for his characters, and the way this superb ensemble cast bring them so vividly to life, that make ''The Barbarian Invasions'' a film not just to see, but to welcome home\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Howell |first=Peter |date=4 September 2003 |title=Arcand goes straight for the heart |newspaper=[[The Toronto Star]] |page=E01}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''Chicago Sun Times'' gave the movie four stars and called it \"a movie with brains, indignation, irony and idealism\".<ref name=\"Ebert Review\">{{cite web |url= http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20031219/REVIEWS/312190301/1023 |title= Movie review: The Barbarian Invasions |author= Rogert Ebert |work= [[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date= 19 December 2003 |access-date= 5 February 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121007060910/http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20031219%2FREVIEWS%2F312190301%2F1023 |archive-date= 7 October 2012 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}</ref> A.O Scott of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote \"what makes ''The Barbarian Invasions'' much more than a facile exercise in generational conflict is that Denys Arcand, who wrote and directed it, has a sense of history that is as acute as it is playful\", adding \"The rapprochement between Remy and Sebastien is beautiful to watch\" and [[Marie-Jos\u00e9e Croze]]'s \"spooky, melancholy intensity darkens the mood of buoyant sentimentality\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F01E6DF143EF934A25753C1A9659C8B63 |title=Film Festival Reviews; Flower Children Grown Up: Somber, Wiser and Still Talking Dirty |last=Scott |first=A.O. |date=17 October 2003 |accessdate=27 August 2016 |work=[[The New York Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311092541/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F01E6DF143EF934A25753C1A9659C8B63 |archive-date=11 March 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'''s Owen Glieberman gave the film a B-, noting R\u00e9my's hedonism.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2003/11/20/barbarian-invasions |title=The Barbarian Invasions |last=Glieberman |first=Owen |date=20 November 2003 |accessdate=27 August 2016 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009053919/http://www.ew.com/article/2003/11/20/barbarian-invasions |archive-date=9 October 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[David Denby]] of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' gave credit to [[St\u00e9phane Rousseau]] for \"a fascinatingly minimal performance\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2003/11/24/close-to-the-end |title=Close to the End |last=Denby |first=David |date=24 November 2003 |accessdate=27 August 2016 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009061128/http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2003/11/24/close-to-the-end |archive-date=9 October 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Jonathan Romney of ''[[The Independent]]'' wrote \"The film has its pros and cons, but you can't fault it for ambition: it not only muses on life and death, but also undertakes fairly comprehensive philosophical soundings of the way the world is today\". Romney added Croze \"has simply the most nuanced presence here: thoughtful, introspective, with a reassuring warmth and lack of cartoonishness\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/the-barbarian-invasions-70643.html |title=The Barbarian Invasions |last=Romney |first=Jonathan |date=21 February 2004 |accessdate=27 August 2016 |work=[[The Independent]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913143938/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/the-barbarian-invasions-70643.html |archive-date=13 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]], writing for ''The Guardian'', disdained the movie, calling it \"grotesquely overpraised\", \"shot through with middlebrow sophistication, boorish cynicism, unfunny satire, a dash of fatuous anti-Americanism and unthinkingly reactionary sexual politics\".<ref name=\"Bradshaw Review\">{{cite web |url= http://film.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/Critic_Review/Guardian_review/0,4267,1151606,00.html |title= The Barbarian Invasions |author= Peter Bradshaw |work= [[The Guardian]] |date= 20 February 2004 |access-date= 10 April 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110622115211/http://film.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/Critic_Review/Guardian_review/0,4267,1151606,00.html |archive-date= 22 June 2011 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}</ref> English Professor Peter Brunette wrote \"its analysis of this state of affairs is all too often annoyingly rhetorical and, finally, altogether too facile\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2004/07/a-farewell-with-facile-analysis-denys-arcands-the-barbarian-invasions-78798/ |title=A Farewell, with Facile Analysis; Denys Arcand\u2019s 'The Barbarian Invasions' |last=Brunette |first=Peter |date=12 July 2014 |accessdate=27 August 2016 |work=[[IndieWire]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105070235/http://www.indiewire.com/2004/07/a-farewell-with-facile-analysis-denys-arcands-the-barbarian-invasions-78798/ |archive-date=5 January 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] ranked the film tenth in the [[Top 10 Canadian Films of All Time]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/top-10-canadian-films-of-all-time|title=Top 10 Canadian Films of All Time|date=2012|accessdate=28 April 2013|work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703002312/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/top-10-canadian-films-of-all-time|archive-date=3 July 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> David Lawrence Pike criticized the use of the World Trade Center footage as exploitative, but said despite \"the crudeness and vulgarity\", the film had a \"particular brilliance\".{{sfn|Pike|2012|p=102}} Review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports an 82% approval rating based on 133 reviews, with an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 7.24/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/barbarian_invasions/|title=The Barbarian Invasions (Les Invasions barbares) - Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=6 December 2019|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211153459/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/barbarian_invasions/|archive-date=11 February 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] reports that the film has an average score of 70 out of 100, based on 34 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/barbarianinvasions|title=The Barbarian Invasions Reviews|accessdate=26 January 2010|website=[[Metacritic]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214144830/http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/barbarianinvasions/|archive-date=14 February 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n''The Barbarian Invasions'' is considered historically significant as the first Canadian film to win the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]].{{sfn|Thompson|2014|p=5}} Canadian historian [[George Melnyk]] interpreted it as a sign that \"[[Cinema of Canada|Canadian cinema]] has come of global age\", also pointing to ''[[Atanarjuat: The Fast Runner]]'' (2001) winning the [[Camera d'Or]] at Cannes.{{sfn|Melnyk|2007|p=xi}}\n\nMarie-Jos\u00e9e Croze's honour for [[Best Actress Award (Cannes Film Festival)|Best Actress]] at the [[2003 Cannes Film Festival]] was considered unlikely.<ref name=\"Radio\"/> She was not present to accept the award.<ref name=\"Odile\"/> The film's victory at France's national [[C\u00e9sar Awards]] was also considered a surprise, since it is mainly a Quebec film.<ref name=\"Fouche\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/feb/23/awardsandprizes.news1 |title=Barbarian Invasions overwhelms C\u00e9sars |last=Fouch\u00e9 |first=Gwladys |date=24 February 2004 |accessdate=27 August 2016 |work=[[The Guardian]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922224401/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/feb/23/awardsandprizes.news1 |archive-date=22 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It received the most nominations at the [[24th Genie Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/the-barbarian-invasions-tops-genie-list/article20428964/ |title=The Barbarian Invasions tops Genie list |last=Yourk |first=Darren |date=16 March 2004 |accessdate=27 August 2016 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918100047/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/the-barbarian-invasions-tops-genie-list/article20428964/ |archive-date=18 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n{|