laude Gagn\u00e9  \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Make-Up\n| [[Evelyne Byot]] and [[Diane Simard]] \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Special Jutra \n| rowspan=\"2\" | Denys Arcand\n| {{won}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Lumi\u00e8res Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"1\" | [[9th Lumi\u00e8res Awards|17 February 2004]]\n| [[Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best French-Language Film|Best French-Language Film]] \n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" | <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2004/film/awards/lumiere-awards-puts-spotlight-on-triplets-1117900261/ |title=Lumiere Awards puts spotlight on \u2018Triplets\u2019 |last=James |first=Alison |date=17 February 2004 |accessdate=27 August 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911005439/http://variety.com/2004/film/awards/lumiere-awards-puts-spotlight-on-triplets-1117900261/ |archive-date=11 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=2| [[National Board of Review]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | December 2003\n| [[National Board of Review Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''The Barbarian Invasions''\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telefilm.ca/en/news/releases/2003/12/05/barbarian-invasions-and-statement-take-home-national-board-review-honours |title=News Releases |date=5 December 2003 |accessdate=27 August 2016|publisher=[[Telefilm Canada]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924050747/https://www.telefilm.ca/en/news/releases/2003/12/05/barbarian-invasions-and-statement-take-home-national-board-review-honours |archivedate=24 September 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n| Top Foreign Films\n| {{won}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Toronto Film Critics Association]]\n| rowspan=\"1\" | [[Toronto Film Critics Association Awards 2003|17 December 2003]]\n| [[Toronto Film Critics Association Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]] \n| rowspan=\"2\" | Denys Arcand\n| {{won}}{{efn|Shared with [[Sofia Coppola]] for ''[[Lost in Translation (film)|Lost in Translation]]''}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" | <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://torontofilmcritics.com/past-award-winners/|title=Past Award Winners|accessdate=27 August 2016|publisher=[[Toronto Film Critics Association]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715181549/http://torontofilmcritics.com/past-award-winners/|archive-date=15 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Toronto International Film Festival]]\n| rowspan=\"1\" | [[2003 Toronto International Film Festival|4\u201313 September 2003]]\n| [[Toronto International Film Festival Award for Best Canadian Film|Best Canadian Feature Film]] \n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" | <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/barbarian-invasions-is-canadas-entry-for-oscar/article1166357/ |title=Barbarian Invasions is Canada's entry for Oscar |last=[[Canadian Press]] |date=18 September 2003 |accessdate=27 August 2016 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918102454/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/barbarian-invasions-is-canadas-entry-for-oscar/article1166357/ |archive-date=18 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=5| [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle]]\n| rowspan=\"5\" | [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle Awards 2003|2 February 2004]]\n| [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Canadian Film|Best Canadian Feature Film]] \n| ''The Barbarian Invasions''\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"5\" | <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://vancouverfilmcritics.com/2004/02/02/4th-annual-award-winners/ |title=4th Annual Award Winners |date=2 February 2004 |accessdate=28 August 2016 |publisher=[[Vancouver Film Critics Circle]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913060757/https://vancouverfilmcritics.com/2004/02/02/4th-annual-award-winners/ |archive-date=13 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Director of a Canadian Film|Best Canadian Director]]\n| Denys Arcand\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actor in a Canadian Film|Best Actor in a Canadian Film]]\n| R\u00e9my Girard\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actress in a Canadian Film|Best Actress in a Canadian Film]]\n| Marie-Jos\u00e9e Croze\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Supporting Actor in a Canadian Film|Best Supporting Actor in a Canadian Film]]\n| St\u00e9phane Rousseau\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2007, Arcand's film ''[[Days of Darkness (2007 Canadian film)|Days of Darkness]]'' was released. While considered part of a loose trilogy following ''[[The Decline of the American Empire]]'' and ''The Barbarian Invasions'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2008/03/21/days_of_darkness_arcand_triumph.html |title='Days of Darkness': Arcand triumph |last=Howell |first=Peter |date=21 March 2008 |accessdate=30 December 2016 |work=[[The Toronto Star]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202003347/https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2008/03/21/days_of_darkness_arcand_triumph.html |archive-date=2 February 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"HaysCBC\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/tiff/features/tiffarcand.html |title=Dark shadows |last=Hays |first=Matthew |date=14 September 2007 |accessdate=30 December 2016 |work=[[CBC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231171635/http://www.cbc.ca/arts/tiff/features/tiffarcand.html |archive-date=31 December 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Coulombe\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.lactualite.com/culture/quest-ce-qui-cloche-avec-denys-arcand/ |title=Qu\u2019est-ce qui cloche avec Denys Arcand ? |last=Coulombe |first=Michel |date=8 November 2007 |accessdate=30 December 2016 |work=[[L'actualit\u00e9]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231061947/http://www.lactualite.com/culture/quest-ce-qui-cloche-avec-denys-arcand/ |archive-date=31 December 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Arcand acknowledged in a 2007 interview ''Days of Darkness'' had more similarities to his less successful 2000 film ''[[Stardom]]''.<ref name=\"Coulombe\"/> [[Johanne-Marie Tremblay]] reprised her role as Constance from ''Jesus of Montreal'' and ''The Barbarian Invasions''.{{sfn|Pike|2012|p=105}} In 2018, Arcand's ''[[The Fall of the American Empire]]'' followed similar themes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://voir.ca/nouvelles/actualite-cinematographique/2018/03/08/denys-arcand-devoile-une-premiere-bande-annonce-de-la-chute-de-lempire-americain/ |title=Denys Arcand D\u00e9voile Une Premi\u00e8re Bande-Annonce De La Chute De L'empire Am\u00e9ricain |last=Lods |first=Jeanne |date=25 July 2017 |accessdate=9 April 2018 |work=[[Voir]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410134910/https://voir.ca/nouvelles/actualite-cinematographique/2018/03/08/denys-arcand-devoile-une-premiere-bande-annonce-de-la-chute-de-lempire-americain/ |archive-date=10 April 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 76th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Canadian submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book |last=Boyd|first=Susan C. |title=Hooked: Drug War Films in Britain, Canada, and the U.S. |publisher=Routledge|date=2008 |isbn=0203930738 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite magazine |last=Howell|first=Peter |date=September\u2013December 2003 |title=A Director in His Prime: Denys Arcand's Les Invasions barbares|magazine=[[Take One (Canadian magazine)|Take One]] |location= |publisher= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Loiselle|first=Andr\u00e9 |title=Denys Arcand's Le D\u00e9clin de L'empire Am\u00e9ricain and Les Invasions Barbares |location=Toronto, Buffalo and London |publisher=University of Toronto Press |date=2008 |isbn=0802099335 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Melnyk|first=George |title=Great Canadian Film Directors |url=https://archive.org/details/greatcanadianfil00meln|url-access=registration|publisher=The University of Alberta Press|date=2007|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Pike|first=David Lawrence |title=Canadian Cinema Since the 1980s: At the Heart of the World |location=Toronto, Buffalo and London |publisher=University of Toronto Press|date=2012 |isbn=1442698322 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Thompson|first=Wayne C. |title=Canada 2014 |publisher=Rowman and Littlefield|date=2014 |edition=30 |isbn=147581240X |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.miramax.com/movie/barbarian-invasions}}\n* {{IMDb title|0338135}}\n* {{Allmovie title|285687}}\n* {{mojo title|barbarianinvasions}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|barbarian_invasions}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-barbarian-invasions}}\n\n{{Denys Arcand}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for ''The Barbarian Invasions''\n|list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestForeignLanguageFilm 2001\u20132020}}\n{{ACCT Best Picture}}\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Foreign Language Film}}\n{{Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best French-Language Film}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Foreign Language Film}}\n{{Prix Iris for Best Film}}\n{{TIFF Best Canadian Film}}\n{{VFCC Award for Best Canadian Film}}\n}}\n{{Canadian submission for Academy Awards}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barbarian Invasions}}\n[[Category:2003 films]]\n[[Category:2000s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:French comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about cancer]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian aviation films]]\n[[Category:Canadian comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Canadian sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Denys Arcand]]\n[[Category:Best Film C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:European Film Awards winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Best Foreign Language Film Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Films set in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Best Picture Genie and Canadian Screen Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best French-Language Film Lumi\u00e8res Award winners]]\n[[Category:Films set in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n", "name_user": "Diopic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:addCategory:Films whose director won the Best Director C\u00e9sar Award", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Barbarian_Invasions"}
{"title_page": "Dipropyltryptamine", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{drugbox | Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 444963386\n| IUPAC_name = ''N''-[2-(1''H''-indol-3-yl)]ethyl-''N''-propylpropan-1-amine\n| image = DPT.svg\n| width = 150px\n| image2 = DPT-3d-sticks.png\n| width2 = 150px\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| pregnancy_AU =\n| pregnancy_US =\n| pregnancy_category =\n| legal_AU =\n| legal_CA =\n| legal_DE = NpSG\n| legal_UK = Class A\n| legal_US =\n| legal_status =\n| routes_of_administration = [[Ingestion]], [[inhalation]], [[intravenous therapy|intravenous]] or [[intramuscular injection|intramuscular]] [[Injection (medicine)|injection]]\n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability =\n| protein_bound =\n| metabolism =\n| elimination_half-life =\n| excretion =\n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| CAS_number = 61-52-9\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = S7272VWU50\n| ATC_prefix = none\n| ATC_suffix =\n| PubChem = 6091\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 5866\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=16 | H=24 | N=2\n| molecular_weight = 244.38 g/mol\n| smiles = CCCN(CCC)CCC1=CNC2=C1C=CC=C2\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C16H24N2/c1-3-10-18(11-4-2)12-9-14-13-17-16-8-6-5-7-15(14)16/h5-8,13,17H,3-4,9-12H2,1-2H3\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = BOOQTIHIKDDPRW-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| melting_point = 174.5\n| melting_high = 178\n}}\n\n'''''N,N''-Dipropyltryptamine''' ('''DPT''', also known as \"The Light\") is a [[Psychedelics, Dissociatives and Deliriants|psychedelic]] [[entheogen]] belonging to the [[tryptamine]] family, first reported in 1973.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Grof S, Soskin RA, Richards WA, Kurland AA | title = DPT as an adjunct in psychotherapy of alcoholics. | journal = International Pharmacopsychiatry | date = 1973 | volume = 8 | issue = 1 | pages = 104\u201315 | doi = 10.1159/000467979 | pmid = 4150711 }} </ref>  It is found either as a [[crystalline]] [[hydrochloride]] [[Salt (chemistry)|salt]] or as an oily or crystalline [[base (chemistry)|base]]. It has not been found to occur endogenously. It is a close structural [[Homology (chemistry)|homologue]] of [[dimethyltryptamine]] and [[diethyltryptamine]].\n\nFrequent physical effects are [[nausea]], [[paresthesia|numbness]] of the [[tongue]] or [[throat]], and [[mydriasis|pupil dilation]].\n\n== Pharmacology ==\n\nStudies on rodents have found that the effectiveness with which a selective [[5-HT2A receptor|5-HT<sub>2A</sub> receptor]] [[Receptor antagonist|antagonist]] blocks the behavioral actions of this compound strongly suggest that the 5-HT<sub>2A</sub> receptor is an important site of action for DPT, but the modulatory actions of a [[5-HT1A receptor|5-HT<sub>1A</sub> receptor]] antagonist also imply a 5-HT<sub>1A</sub>-mediated component to the actions of DPT.<ref name=\"pmid17905422\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fantegrossi WE, Reissig CJ, Katz EB, Yarosh HL, Rice KC, Winter JC | title = Hallucinogen-like effects of N,N-dipropyltryptamine (DPT): possible mediation by serotonin 5-HT1A and 5-HT2A receptors in rodents | journal = Pharmacology, Biochemistry, and Behavior | volume = 88 | issue = 3 | pages = 358\u201365 | date = January 2008 | pmid = 17905422 | pmc = 2322878 | doi = 10.1016/j.pbb.2007.09.007 }}</ref>\n\n== Chemistry ==\n\nDPT changes [[Ehrlich's reagent]] violet and causes the marquis reagent to turn yellow.<ref name='microgram2005'>{{cite journal | title = Analytical Profiles for Five \"Designer\" Tryptamines\n | journal = Microgram Journal | date = 2004 | first = Trinette | last = Spratley | name-list-format = vanc | volume = 3 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 55| id = | url = http://www.erowid.org/library/periodicals/microgram/microgram_journal_2005-1.pdf#page=54 | format = PDF | accessdate = 2013-10-09}}</ref>\n\n== Psychedelic properties ==\n\nWhile dipropyltryptamine is chemically similar to [[dimethyltryptamine]] (DMT), its psychoactive effects are markedly different.<ref>{{cite book |last = Pinchbeck |first = Daniel | name-list-format = vanc |authorlink = Daniel Pinchbeck |title = Breaking Open The Head |publisher = Broadway Books |year = 2003 |isbn = 0-7679-0743-4}}</ref>\n\nWhile experiences of apparent entity contact may occasionally occur under the influence of DPT, the perspective is more as an observer or watcher, as contrasted to the more personal and realistic experience reported with DMT.<ref>{{cite book |last = Metzger |first = Richard | name-list-format = vanc |authorlink = Richard Metzger |title = Book of Lies - The Disinformation Guide to Magic and the Occult |publisher = The Disinformation Company Ltd. |year = 2003 |isbn = 0-9713942-7-X}}</ref>\n\n== Side effects ==\nNegative side effects of human consumption of this drug can include increased heart rate, dizziness, anxiety, confusion, paranoia, seizure and nausea. The use of dipropyltryptamine has caused at least two deaths, both involving seizures.<ref>{{cite web | first = Beatrice | last = Dupuy | name-list-format = vanc | work = Star Tribune | date = 1 October 2015  | title = Carver County teen's death puts spotlight on ease of purchasing synthetic drugs online | url = http://www.startribune.com/carver-county-teen-s-death-puts-spotlight-on-ease-of-purchasing-synthetic-drugs-online/330344661/ }}</ref>\n\n== Religious use ==\n\nDPT is used as a [[religious]] [[sacrament]] by the [[Temple of the True Inner Light]], a [[New York City]] offshoot of the [[Native American Church]]. The Temple believes DPT and other [[entheogen]]s are physical manifestations of [[God]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://psychede.tripod.com/ | title = Temple of the True Inner Light | work = tripod.com }}</ref>\n\n== Legal status ==\n\n===United Kingdom===\nDPT is a Class A drug in the United Kingdom, making it illegal to possess or distribute\n.\n\n===United States===\nDPT is not scheduled at the federal level in the United States,<ref name=\"PART 1308 \u2014 SCHEDULES OF CONTROLLED SUBSTANCES - 1308.11 Schedule I\">{{cite web | url = http://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/21cfr/cfr/1308/1308_11.htm | work = CFR | title = SCHEDULES OF CONTROLLED SUBSTANCES \u00a71308.11 Schedule I. }}</ref> but it could be considered an analog of [[5-MeO-DiPT]], [[dimethyltryptamine|DMT]], or [[diethyltryptamine|DET]], in which case purchase, sale, or possession could be prosecuted under the [[Federal Analogue Act]].\n\n====Florida====\n\"DPT (N,N-Dipropyltryptamine)\" is a Schedule I [[controlled substance]] in the state of [[Florida]] making it illegal to buy, sell, or possess in Florida.<ref name=\"Florida Statutes - Chapter 893 - DRUG ABUSE PREVENTION AND CONTROL\">[http://leg.state.fl.us/statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&URL=0800-0899/0893/0893.html Florida Statutes - Chapter 893 - DRUG ABUSE PREVENTION AND CONTROL]</ref>\n\n====Maine====\nDPT is a Schedule I [[controlled substance]] in the state of [[Maine]] making it illegal to buy, sell, or possess in Maine.\n\n===Sweden===\nDPT is illegal in Sweden as of 26 January 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2015/november/31-nya-amnen-kan-klassas-som-narkotika-eller-halsofarlig-vara/ | title=31 nya \u00e4mnen kan klassas som narkotika eller h\u00e4lsofarlig vara | publisher=Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten | language=Swedish | date=November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<!--See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes for an explanation of how to generate footnotes or references using the <ref(erences/)> tags-->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.erowid.org/library/books_online/tihkal/tihkal09.shtml TiHKAL entry]\n* [http://isomerdesign.com/PiHKAL/explore.php?domain=tk&id=5009 DPT entry in TiHKAL \u2022 info]\n* [https://www.erowid.org/chemicals/dpt/dpt_primer.shtml A DPT Primer by Toad]\n* [https://www.erowid.org/experiences/subs/exp_DPT.shtml Erowid Experience Vault]\n\n{{TiHKAL}}\n{{Hallucinogens}}\n{{Serotonin receptor modulators}}\n{{Sigma receptor modulators}}\n{{Tryptamines}}\n\n[[Category:Entheogens]]\n[[Category:Psychedelic tryptamines]]\n[[Category:Designer drugs]]\n[[Category:Serotonin receptor agonists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{drugbox | Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 444963386\n| IUPAC_name = ''N''-[2-(1''H''-indol-3-yl)]ethyl-''N''-propylpropan-1-amine\n| image = DPT.svg\n| width = 150px\n| image2 = DPT-3d-sticks.png\n| width2 = 150px\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| pregnancy_AU =\n| pregnancy_US =\n| pregnancy_category =\n| legal_AU =\n| legal_CA =\n| legal_DE = NpSG\n| legal_UK = Class A\n| legal_US =\n| legal_status =\n| routes_of_administration = [[Ingestion]], [[inhalation]], [[intravenous therapy|intravenous]] or [[intramuscular injection|intramuscular]] [[Injection (medicine)|injection]]\n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability =\n| protein_bound =\n| metabolism =\n| elimination_half-life =\n| excretion =\n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| CAS_number = 61-52-9\n| ATC_prefix = none\n| ATC_suffix =\n| PubChem = 6091\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 5866\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=16 | H=24 | N=2\n| molecular_weight = 244.38 g/mol\n| smiles = CCCN(CCC)CCC1=CNC2=C1C=CC=C2\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C16H24N2/c1-3-10-18(11-4-2)12-9-14-13-17-16-8-6-5-7-15(14)16/h5-8,13,17H,3-4,9-12H2,1-2H3\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = BOOQTIHIKDDPRW-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| melting_point = 174.5\n| melting_high = 178\n}}\n\n'''''N,N''-Dipropyltryptamine''' ('''DPT''', also known as \"The Light\") is a [[Psychedelics, Dissociatives and Deliriants|psychedelic]] [[entheogen]] belonging to the [[tryptamine]] family, first reported in 1973.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Grof S, Soskin RA, Richards WA, Kurland AA | title = DPT as an adjunct in psychotherapy of alcoholics. | journal = International Pharmacopsychiatry | date = 1973 | volume = 8 | issue = 1 | pages = 104\u201315 | doi = 10.1159/000467979 | pmid = 4150711 }} </ref>  It is found either as a [[crystalline]] [[hydrochloride]] [[Salt (chemistry)|salt]] or as an oily or crystalline [[base (chemistry)|base]]. It has not been found to occur endogenously. It is a close structural [[Homology (chemistry)|homologue]] of [[dimethyltryptamine]] and [[diethyltryptamine]].\n\nFrequent physical effects are [[nausea]], [[paresthesia|numbness]] of the [[tongue]] or [[throat]], and [[mydriasis|pupil dilation]].\n\n== Pharmacology ==\n\nStudies on rodents have found that the effectiveness with which a selective [[5-HT2A receptor|5-HT<sub>2A</sub> receptor]] [[Receptor antagonist|antagonist]] blocks the behavioral actions of this compound strongly suggest that the 5-HT<sub>2A</sub> receptor is an important site of action for DPT, but the modulatory actions of a [[5-HT1A receptor|5-HT<sub>1A</sub> receptor]] antagonist also imply a 5-HT<sub>1A</sub>-mediated component to the actions of DPT.<ref name=\"pmid17905422\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Fantegrossi WE, Reissig CJ, Katz EB, Yarosh HL, Rice KC, Winter JC | title = Hallucinogen-like effects of N,N-dipropyltryptamine (DPT): possible mediation by serotonin 5-HT1A and 5-HT2A receptors in rodents | journal = Pharmacology, Biochemistry, and Behavior | volume = 88 | issue = 3 | pages = 358\u201365 | date = January 2008 | pmid = 17905422 | pmc = 2322878 | doi = 10.1016/j.pbb.2007.09.007 }}</ref>\n\n== Chemistry ==\n\nDPT changes [[Ehrlich's reagent]] violet and causes the marquis reagent to turn yellow.<ref name='microgram2005'>{{cite journal | title = Analytical Profiles for Five \"Designer\" Tryptamines\n | journal = Microgram Journal | date = 2004 | first = Trinette | last = Spratley | name-list-format = vanc | volume = 3 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 55| id = | url = http://www.erowid.org/library/periodicals/microgram/microgram_journal_2005-1.pdf#page=54 | format = PDF | accessdate = 2013-10-09}}</ref>\n\n== Psychedelic properties ==\n\nWhile dipropyltryptamine is chemically similar to [[dimethyltryptamine]] (DMT), its psychoactive effects are markedly different.<ref>{{cite book |last = Pinchbeck |first = Daniel | name-list-format = vanc |authorlink = Daniel Pinchbeck |title = Breaking Open The Head |publisher = Broadway Books |year = 2003 |isbn = 0-7679-0743-4}}</ref>\n\nWhile experiences of apparent entity contact may occasionally occur under the influence of DPT, the perspective is more as an observer or watcher, as contrasted to the more personal and realistic experience reported with DMT.<ref>{{cite book |last = Metzger |first = Richard | name-list-format = vanc |authorlink = Richard Metzger |title = Book of Lies - The Disinformation Guide to Magic and the Occult |publisher = The Disinformation Company Ltd. |year = 2003 |isbn = 0-9713942-7-X}}</ref>\n\n== Side effects ==\nNegative side effects of human consumption of this drug can include increased heart rate, dizziness, anxiety, confusion, paranoia, seizure and nausea. The use of dipropyltryptamine has caused at least two deaths, both involving seizures.<ref>{{cite web | first = Beatrice | last = Dupuy | name-list-format = vanc | work = Star Tribune | date = 1 October 2015  | title = Carver County teen's death puts spotlight on ease of purchasing synthetic drugs online | url = http://www.startribune.com/carver-county-teen-s-death-puts-spotlight-on-ease-of-purchasing-synthetic-drugs-online/330344661/ }}</ref>\n\n== Religious use ==\n\nDPT is used as a [[religious]] [[sacrament]] by the [[Temple of the True Inner Light]], a [[New York City]] offshoot of the [[Native American Church]]. The Temple believes DPT and other [[entheogen]]s are physical manifestations of [[God]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://psychede.tripod.com/ | title = Temple of the True Inner Light | work = tripod.com }}</ref>\n\n== Legal status ==\n\n===United Kingdom===\nDPT is a Class A drug in the United Kingdom, making it illegal to possess or distribute\n.\n\n===United States===\nDPT is not scheduled at the federal level in the United States,<ref name=\"PART 1308 \u2014 SCHEDULES OF CONTROLLED SUBSTANCES - 1308.11 Schedule I\">{{cite web | url = http://www.deadiversion.usdoj.gov/21cfr/cfr/1308/1308_11.htm | work = CFR | title = SCHEDULES OF CONTROLLED SUBSTANCES \u00a71308.11 Schedule I. }}</ref> but it could be considered an analog of [[5-MeO-DiPT]], [[dimethyltryptamine|DMT]], or [[diethyltryptamine|DET]], in which case purchase, sale, or possession could be prosecuted under the [[Federal Analogue Act]].\n\n====Florida====\n\"DPT (N,N-Dipropyltryptamine)\" is a Schedule I [[controlled substance]] in the state of [[Florida]] making it illegal to buy, sell, or possess in Florida.<ref name=\"Florida Statutes - Chapter 893 - DRUG ABUSE PREVENTION AND CONTROL\">[http://leg.state.fl.us/statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&URL=0800-0899/0893/0893.html Florida Statutes - Chapter 893 - DRUG ABUSE PREVENTION AND CONTROL]</ref>\n\n====Maine====\nDPT is a Schedule I [[controlled substance]] in the state of [[Maine]] making it illegal to buy, sell, or possess in Maine.\n\n===Sweden===\nDPT is illegal in Sweden as of 26 January 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2015/november/31-nya-amnen-kan-klassas-som-narkotika-eller-halsofarlig-vara/ | title=31 nya \u00e4mnen kan klassas som narkotika eller h\u00e4lsofarlig vara | publisher=Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten | language=Swedish | date=November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<!--See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes for an explanation of how to generate footnotes or references using the <ref(erences/)> tags-->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.erowid.org/library/books_online/tihkal/tihkal09.shtml TiHKAL entry]\n* [http://isomerdesign.com/PiHKAL/explore.php?domain=tk&id=5009 DPT entry in TiHKAL \u2022 info]\n* [https://www.erowid.org/chemicals/dpt/dpt_primer.shtml A DPT Primer by Toad]\n* [https://www.erowid.org/experiences/subs/exp_DPT.shtml Erowid Experience Vault]\n\n{{TiHKAL}}\n{{Hallucinogens}}\n{{Serotonin receptor modulators}}\n{{Sigma receptor modulators}}\n{{Tryptamines}}\n\n[[Category:Entheogens]]\n[[Category:Psychedelic tryptamines]]\n[[Category:Designer drugs]]\n[[Category:Serotonin receptor agonists]]\n", "name_user": "Fswitzer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "added FDA UNII to drug box", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dipropyltryptamine"}
{"title_page": "Karl Elmendorff", "text_new": "<!-- please do not add an infobox, per [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Classical music/Style guidelines#Biographical infoboxes]]-->\n[[Image:karlelmendorff.jpg|210px|thumb]] \n'''Karl Eduard Maria Elmendorff''' (October 25, 1891 \u2013 October 21, 1962) was a German [[opera]] [[conducting|conductor]].\n\t\nBorn in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]], Elmendorff studied music at the [[Cologne College of Music]] and [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik K\u00f6ln]] from 1913 to 1916 under [[Fritz Steinbach]] and [[Hermann Abendroth]]. \n\n==Career==\nEarly in his career, Elmendorff was a regular guest conductor in various European cities, including at [[La Scala]]:\n\n* 1916 to 1920 in D\u00fcsseldorf\n* 1920 to 1923 in [[Mainz]]\n* 1923 to 1924 in Hagen\n* 1925 at the [[Munich State Opera]]\n\n===Bayreuth===\nWhen [[Fritz Busch]] refused to return to Bayreuth after the 1924 Festival and with [[Michael Balling]] dead the following year, [[Siegfried Wagner]] invited Elmendorff and [[Franz von Hoesslin]] to Bayreuth.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Spotts |first1=Frederic |title=Bayreuth: A History of the Wagner Festival |date=1996 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |isbn=0-300-06665-1 |page=169}}</ref> Although [[Richard Wagner]], in his 1869 tract ''On Conducting'' had no intention of imposing a system on conducting practice,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wagner |first1=Richard |title=Three Wagner Essays |date=1979 |publisher=Ernst Eulenburg Ltd |location=London |page=49 |language=English Tr. Robert L. Jacobs |chapter=On Conducting}}</ref> and post-Wagner Bayreuth conductors Levi, Mottl, Richard Strauss and Siegfried Wagner were able to develop their own conducting idiosyncrasies, nevertheless, a Bayreuth style that tended toward slower tempi had gradually developed that not only reflected Cosima's ideology but could be practically justified as the style demanded by the Festspielhaus's unique acoustics.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Breckbill |first1=David |editor1-last=Millington |editor1-first=Barry |title=The Wagner Compendium: A Guide to Wagner's Life and Work |date=1992 |publisher=Thames and Hudson |location=London |page=369 |chapter=Section 17: Wagner in Performance:  Conducting}}</ref> By the 1920's the Bayreuth style of conducting was exemplified in the work of [[Karl Muck]], and it was into this undulating sound world of flowing symphonic texture that both men 'who fully met Bayreuth's conservative criteria',<ref>{{cite book |last1=Spotts |first1=Frederic |title=Bayreuth: A History of the Wagner Festival |date=1996 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |isbn=0-300-06665-1 |page=148}}</ref> entered and were taken up by. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Breckbill |first1=David |editor1-last=Millington |editor1-first=Barry |title=The Wagner Compendium: A Guide to Wagner's Life and Work |date=1992 |publisher=Thames and Hudson |location=London |pages=369-370 |chapter=Section 17: Wagner in Performance:  Conducting}}</ref>\n\nIn 1928 Winifred was approached by [[Elsa Bruckmann]] to help enlist Muck into the ranks of the [[Militant League for German Culture]] (the KfdK). Winifred agreed to help and, in a letter to Bruckmann dated 15th October 1928, outlined her plan to use Elemendorff ('he's very keen on anything like this' as the easiest and most natural way of achieving their aim.<ref>{{cite book |last1=quoted in Hamann |first1=Brigitte |title=Winifred Wagner: A Life At The Heart of Hitler's Bayreuth |date=2005 |publisher=Harcourt Books |location=Orlando | pages=129-30n.40}}</ref> In the end, neither Winifred, nor Elmendorff's enthusiasm could persuade Muck to join.\n\nFollowing Siegfried Wagner's death in August 1930, a memorial concert was held in the [[Bayreuth Festspielhaus|Festspielhaus]]. The concert programme was framed by two pieces by [[Richard Wagner]] that commemorated Siegfried's birth and death; the opening piece, the [[Siegfried Idyll]], conducted by [[Arturo Toscanini]], and to close,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hamann |first1=Brigitte |title=Winifred Wagner: A Life At The Heart of Hitler's Bayreuth |date=2005 |publisher=Harcourt Books |location=Orlando | page=145}}</ref> Siegfried's Funeral March' from [[G\u00f6tterd\u00e4mmerung]], conducted by Muck. The centrepiece of the concert was conducted by Elmendorff, and commemorated Siegfried's own 'modest genius'<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wagner |first1=Nike |title=The Wagners: The Dramas of A Musical Dynasty |date=2000 |publisher=Phoenix |location=London |isbn=0-75381-280-0 |page=211 |language=English tr. Osers, E and Downes, M |chapter=15}}</ref> with excerpts from his operas including the overture to ''Angel of Peace'' and 'Faith' from ''Heathen King''.\n\nDuring the 1931 Festival a memorial concert was planned to take place on 4th August, the first anniversary of Siegfried's death. During the rehearsals a row broke out that led to Toscanini storming out of Bayreuth. Initially Furtw\u00e4ngler wanted to be the sole conductor of an all-Beethoven concert but Winifred insisted that all three of that year's Festival conductors Elmendorff, [[Wilhelm Furtw\u00e4ngler]] and Toscanini, should take part in a programme of music by Liszt, Richard and Siegfried Wagner. Furtw\u00e4ngler prolonged the argument by declaring that he had no intention of conducting \"dynastic programme\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lieselotte Schmidt, letter to her parents 23.7.1931 quoted in Hamann |first1=Brigitte |title=Winifred Wagner: A Life At The Heart of Hitler's Bayreuth |date=2005 |publisher=Harcourt Books |location=Orlando | page=129n.51}}</ref> The time taken up by the argument started to intrude on Toscanini's general rehearsal time, a situation exacerbated when an incompetent assistant lost Toscanini's score. Enraged, Toscanini snapped his baton and immediately left Bayreuth. From a safe distance in the USA, he declared that he would never return and although he did return to conduct his remaining performances that year, he never again conducted at Bayreuth.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hamann |first1=Brigitte |title=Winifred Wagner: A Life At The Heart of Hitler's Bayreuth |date=2005 |publisher=Harcourt Books |location=Orlando | pages=129-130}}</ref>\n\nIt wasn't until after Furtw\u00e4ngler acrimoniously departed following the 1936 Festival that Elmendorff was officially appointed as an assistant to the principal conductor, Heinz Tietjen.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Spotts |first1=Frederic |title=Bayreuth: A History of the Wagner Festival |date=1996 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |isbn=0-300-06665-1 |page=178}}</ref> It was at this time, in 1937, that Elmendorff joined the [[Nazi Party]].<ref>[[Fred K. Prieberg]]: Handbuch Deutsche Musiker 1933\u20131945, CD-Rom-Lexikon, Kiel 2004, {{p.|1392\u20131393}}.</ref>\n\n====Bayreuth Festival statistics====\nElemendorff conducted five Ring cycles and eight performances, in total, of three different operas during his fifteen years at Bayreuth.<ref>{{cite web |title=Statistics: The Bayreuth Festival in Figures |url=https://www.bayreuther-festspiele.de/en/the-festival/statistics/ |publisher=Bayreuther Festspiele |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> His conducting at the Festival ended when Furtw\u00e4ngler returned to Bayreuth in 1943.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| 1927 || ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'' (Tr)\n|-\n| 1928 || Tr (see Discography)\n|-\n| 1930 || ''[[Der Ring des Nibelungen]]'' (R)\n|-\n| 1930 || ''[[Tannh\u00e4user]]'' * Toscanini conducted the public performances but for contractual reasons Elemendorff conducted the recording (see Discography)\n|-\n| 1931 || R\n|-\n| 1933 || R\n|-\n| 1933 || ''[[Die Meistersinger von N\u00fcrnberg]]'' (M)\n|-\n| 1934 || R\n|-\n| 1934 || M\n|-\n| 1938 || Tr\n|-\n| 1939 || ''[[Der fliegende Hollander]]'' (H)\n|-\n| 1940 || H\n|-\n| 1941 || H\n|-\n| 1942 || R\n|-\n|}\n\n==Critical Reception==\n[[Jonathan Carr]] describes Elmendorff's 1928 recording of ''Tristan und Isolde'' as 'orchestrally exemplary' whilst also noting that although it was Toscanini was responsible for fully preparing Bayreuth Festival orchestra to achieve great things in the 1930 production of [[Tannh\u00e4user]], it was Elmendorff who (for contractual reasons) conducted the Bayreuth recording.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Carr |first1=Jonathan |title=The Wagner Clan |date=2007 |publisher=Faber and Faber |location=London |page=118}}</ref>\n\n[[Ernest Newman]] regarded Elmendorff's performance in the 1930 ''Ring'' as 'efficient rather than dazzling' - an opinion, noted by Frederic Spotts, as not uncommon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Spotts |first1=Frederic |title=Bayreuth: A History of the Wagner Festival |date=1996 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |isbn=0-300-06665-1 |page=169}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1933 [[Walter Legge]] attended the Bayreuth Festival in his role as the music critic of the [[Manchester Guardian]] newspaper. As well as observing that the Wagner Festival had been transformed into a Hitler festival, with ''[[Mein Kampf]]'' displacing ''[[Mein Leben (Wagner)|Mein Leben]]'', Legge heaped scorn on the quality of the conducting which he considers a consequence of German musical protectionism. Lamenting the absence of Toscanini, Legge's review critically slated both [[Richard Strauss]], whose 'conducting days are over' and  Elemendorff who Legge damns as 'an artist of but average talent'.\n\n<blockquote>If Elmendorff is the best Wagnerian conductor Germany can produce, we can only sympathise with the intelligent music-lovers who have to live in a land where only German conductors are allowed to appear. It looks as if \"German music performed by German artists\" were fit only for the German home.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schwarzkopf |first1=Elisabeth |title=On and Off The Record |date=1982 |publisher=Faber and Faber |location=London |isbn=0-571-11928 X |page=24}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Discography ==\n* ''[[G\u00f6tterd\u00e4mmerung]]'' - Live 1942 Bayreuth, Label: Music & Arts Program, 2000 (recorded 1942)\n* ''[[Tannh\u00e4user (opera)|Tannh\u00e4user]]'', Label: [[Naxos Records]], 2001 (recorded 1930)\n* ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'', Label: Naxos, 2003 (recorded 1928)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite news | author= | title=Bayreuth's Blight | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,789365,00.html | work=Time  | date=19 June 1933 | accessdate=2007-09-21}}\n\n{{Dresden Staatskapelle conductors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elmendorff, Karl}}\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:German conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:German male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:People from D\u00fcsseldorf]]\n[[Category:Cologne University of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:20th-century German musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male musicians]]\n\n\n{{germany-conductor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "<!-- please do not add an infobox, per [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Classical music/Style guidelines#Biographical infoboxes]]-->\n[[Image:karlelmendorff.jpg|210px|thumb]] \n'''Karl Eduard Maria Elmendorff''' (October 25, 1891 \u2013 October 21, 1962) was a German [[opera]] [[conducting|conductor]].\n\t\nBorn in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]], Elmendorff studied music at the [[Cologne College of Music]] and [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik K\u00f6ln]] from 1913 to 1916 under [[Fritz Steinbach]] and [[Hermann Abendroth]]. \n\n==Career==\nEarly in his career, Elmendorff was a regular guest conductor in various European cities, including at [[La Scala]]:\n\n* 1916 to 1920 in D\u00fcsseldorf\n* 1920 to 1923 in [[Mainz]]\n* 1923 to 1924 in Hagen\n* 1925 at the [[Munich State Opera]]\n\n===Bayreuth===\nWhen [[Fritz Busch]] refused to return to Bayreuth after the 1924 Festival and with [[Michael Balling]] dead the following year, [[Siegfried Wagner]] invited Elmendorff and Franz von Hoe\u1e9elin to Bayreuth.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Spotts |first1=Frederic |title=Bayreuth: A History of the Wagner Festival |date=1996 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |isbn=0-300-06665-1 |page=169}}</ref> Although [[Richard Wagner]], in his 1869 tract ''On Conducting'' had no intention of imposing a system on conducting practice,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wagner |first1=Richard |title=Three Wagner Essays |date=1979 |publisher=Ernst Eulenburg Ltd |location=London |page=49 |language=English Tr. Robert L. Jacobs |chapter=On Conducting}}</ref> and post-Wagner Bayreuth conductors Levi, Mottl, Richard Strauss and Siegfried Wagner were able to develop their own conducting idiosyncrasies, nevertheless, with deference to Cosima, a Bayreuth style that tended toward slower tempi gradually developed. This not only reflected Cosima's ideology but could be practically justified as the style demanded by the Festspielhaus's unique acoustics.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Breckbill |first1=David |editor1-last=Millington |editor1-first=Barry |title=The Wagner Compendium: A Guide to Wagner's Life and Work |date=1992 |publisher=Thames and Hudson |location=London |page=369 |chapter=Section 17: Wagner in Performance:  Conducting}}</ref> By the 1920's the Bayreuth style of conducting was exemplified in the work of Karl Muck, and it was into this undulating sound world of flowing symphonic texture that both men 'who fully met Bayreuth's conservative criteria',<ref>{{cite book |last1=Spotts |first1=Frederic |title=Bayreuth: A History of the Wagner Festival |date=1996 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |isbn=0-300-06665-1 |page=148}}</ref> entered and were taken up by. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Breckbill |first1=David |editor1-last=Millington |editor1-first=Barry |title=The Wagner Compendium: A Guide to Wagner's Life and Work |date=1992 |publisher=Thames and Hudson |location=London |pages=369-370 |chapter=Section 17: Wagner in Performance:  Conducting}}</ref>\n\nIn 1928 Winifred was approached by [[Elsa Bruckmann]] to help enlist [[Karl Muck]] into the ranks of the [[Militant League for German Culture]] (the KfdK). Winifred agreed to help, in a letter to Bruckmann dated 15th October 1928, outlined her plan to use Elemendorff ('he's very keen on anything like this' as the easiest and most natural way of achieving their aim.<ref>{{cite book |last1=quoted in Hamann |first1=Brigitte |title=Winifred Wagner: A Life At The Heart of Hitler's Bayreuth |date=2005 |publisher=Harcourt Books |location=Orlando | pages=129-30n.40}}</ref> In the end, neither Winifred, nor Elmendorff's enthusiasm could persuade Muck to join.\n\nFollowing Siegfried Wagner's death in August 1930, a memorial concert was held in the [[Bayreuth Festspielhaus|Festspielhaus]]. The concert programme was framed by two pieces by [[Richard Wagner]] that commemorated Siegfried's birth and death; the opening piece, the [[Siegfried Idyll]], conducted by [[Arturo Toscanini]], and to close,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hamann |first1=Brigitte |title=Winifred Wagner: A Life At The Heart of Hitler's Bayreuth |date=2005 |publisher=Harcourt Books |location=Orlando | page=145}}</ref> Siegfried's Funeral March' from [[G\u00f6tterd\u00e4mmerung]], conducted by Karl Muck. The centrepiece of the concert was conducted by Elmendorff, and commemorated Siegfried's own 'modest genius'<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wagner |first1=Nike |title=The Wagners: The Dramas of A Musical Dynasty |date=2000 |publisher=Phoenix |location=London |isbn=0-75381-280-0 |page=211 |language=English tr. Osers, E and Downes, M |chapter=15}}</ref> with excerpts from his operas including the overture to ''Angel of Peace'' and 'Faith' from ''Heathen King''.\n\nDuring the 1931 Festival a memorial concert was planned to take place on 4th August, the first anniversary of Siegfried's death. During the rehearsals a row broke out that led to Toscanini storming out of Bayreuth. Initially Furtw\u00e4ngler wanted to be the sole conductor of an all-Beethoven concert but Winifred insisted that all three of that year's Festival conductors Elmendorff, Furtw\u00e4ngler and Toscanini, should take part in a programme of music by Liszt, Richard and Siegfried Wagner. Furtw\u00e4ngler prolonged the argument by declaring that he had no intention of conducting \"dynastic programme\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lieselotte Schmidt, letter to her parents 23.7.1931 quoted in Hamann |first1=Brigitte |title=Winifred Wagner: A Life At The Heart of Hitler's Bayreuth |date=2005 |publisher=Harcourt Books |location=Orlando | page=129n.51}}</ref> The time taken up by the argument started to intrude on Toscanini's general rehearsal time, a situation exacerbated when an incompetent assistant lost Toscanini's score. Enraged, Toscanini snapped his baton and immediately left Bayreuth. From a safe distance in the USA, he declared that he would never return and although he did return to conduct his remaining performances that year, he never again conducted at Bayreuth.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hamann |first1=Brigitte |title=Winifred Wagner: A Life At The Heart of Hitler's Bayreuth |date=2005 |publisher=Harcourt Books |location=Orlando | pages=129-130}}</ref>\n\nIt wasn't until after Furtw\u00e4ngler acrimoniously departed following the 1936 Festival that Elmendorff was officially appointed as an assistant to the principal conductor, Heinz Tietjen.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Spotts |first1=Frederic |title=Bayreuth: A History of the Wagner Festival |date=1996 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |isbn=0-300-06665-1 |page=178}}</ref> It was at this time, in 1937, that he joined the [[Nazi Party]].<ref>[[Fred K. Prieberg]]: Handbuch Deutsche Musiker 1933\u20131945, CD-Rom-Lexikon, Kiel 2004, {{p.|1392\u20131393}}.</ref>\n====Bayreuth Festival statistics====\nElemendorff conducted five Ring cycles and eight performances, in total, of three different operas during his fifteen years at Bayreuth.<ref>{{cite web |title=Statistics: The Bayreuth Festival in Figures |url=https://www.bayreuther-festspiele.de/en/the-festival/statistics/ |publisher=Bayreuther Festspiele |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> His conducting at the Festival ended when Furtw\u00e4ngler returned to Bayreuth in 1943.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| 1927 || ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'' (Tr)\n|-\n| 1928 || Tr (see Discography)\n|-\n| 1930 || ''[[Der Ring des Nibelungen]]'' (R)\n|-\n| 1930 || ''[[Tannh\u00e4user]]'' * Toscanini conducted the public performances but for contractual reasons Elemendorff conducted the recording (see Discography)\n|-\n| 1931 || R\n|-\n| 1933 || R\n|-\n| 1933 || ''[[Die Meistersinger von N\u00fcrnberg]]'' (M)\n|-\n| 1934 || R\n|-\n| 1934 || M\n|-\n| 1938 || Tr\n|-\n| 1939 || ''[[Der fliegende Hollander]]'' (H)\n|-\n| 1940 || H\n|-\n| 1941 || H\n|-\n| 1942 || R\n|-\n|}\n\n==Critical Reception==\n[[Jonathan Carr]] describes Elmendorff's 1928 recording of ''Tristan und Isolde'' as 'orchestrally exemplary' whilst also noting that although it was Toscanini was responsible for fully preparing Bayreuth Festival orchestra to achieve great things in the 1930 production of [[Tannh\u00e4user]], it was Elmendorff who (for contractual reasons) conducted the Bayreuth recording.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Carr |first1=Jonathan |title=The Wagner Clan |date=2007 |publisher=Faber and Faber |location=London |page=118}}</ref>\n\n[[Ernest Newman]] regarded Elmendorff's performance in the 1930 ''Ring'' as 'efficient rather than dazzling' - an opinion, noted by Frederic Spotts, as not uncommon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Spotts |first1=Frederic |title=Bayreuth: A History of the Wagner Festival |date=1996 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |isbn=0-300-06665-1 |page=169}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1933 [[Walter Legge]] attended the Bayreuth Festival in his role as the music critic of the [[Manchester Guardian]] newspaper. As well as observing that the Wagner Festival had been transformed into a Hitler festival, with ''[[Mein Kampf]]'' displacing ''[[Mein Leben (Wagner)|Mein Leben]]'', Legge heaped scorn on the quality of the conducting which he considers a consequence of German musical protectionism. Lamenting the absence of Toscanini, Legge's review critically slated both [[Richard Strauss]], whose 'conducting days are over' and  Elemendorff who Legge damns as 'an artist of but average talent'.\n\n<blockquote>If Elmendorff is the best Wagnerian conductor Germany can produce, we can only sympathise with the intelligent music-lovers who have to live in a land where only German conductors are allowed to appear. It looks as if \"German music performed by German artists\" were fit only for the German home.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schwarzkopf |first1=Elisabeth |title=On and Off The Record |date=1982 |publisher=Faber and Faber |location=London |isbn=0-571-11928 X |page=24}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Discography ==\n* ''[[G\u00f6tterd\u00e4mmerung]]'' - Live 1942 Bayreuth, Label: Music & Arts Program, 2000 (recorded 1942)\n* ''[[Tannh\u00e4user (opera)|Tannh\u00e4user]]'', Label: [[Naxos Records]], 2001 (recorded 1930)\n* ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'', Label: Naxos, 2003 (recorded 1928)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite news | author= | title=Bayreuth's Blight | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,789365,00.html | work=Time  | date=19 June 1933 | accessdate=2007-09-21}}\n\n{{Dresden Staatskapelle conductors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elmendorff, Karl}}\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:German conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:German male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:People from D\u00fcsseldorf]]\n[[Category:Cologne University of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:20th-century German musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male musicians]]\n\n\n{{germany-conductor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Flourbomb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBayreuth:tidying up links and polishing syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Elmendorff"}
{"title_page": "Chinese Land Reform", "text_new": "{{Infobox Chinese\n|pic=A man reads the Land Reform Law of PRC.jpg\n|piccap=The land reform staff publicizing the Land Reform Law to peasants in 1950.\n|picsize=300px\n|altname=Formal name\n|s=\u571f\u5730\u6539\u9769\u8fd0\u52a8\n|t=\u571f\u5730\u6539\u9769\u904b\u52d5\n|l=Land Reform Movement\n|order=st\n|p=T\u01d4d\u00ec g\u01ceig\u00e9 y\u00f9nd\u00f2ng\n|w=Tu<sup>3</sup> ti<sup>4</sup> kai<sup>3</sup> ko<sup>2</sup> yun<sup>4</sup> tong<sup>4</sup>\n|bpmf=\u310a\u3128\u02c7 \u3109\u3127\u02cb \u310d\u311e\u02c7 \u310d\u311c\u02ca \u3129\u3123\u02cb \u3109\u3128\u3125\u02cb \n|myr=Tu<sup>3</sup>di<sup>4</sup> gai<sup>3</sup>ge<sup>2</sup> yun<sup>4</sup>dung<sup>4</sup>\n|y=t\u00f3u deih g\u00f3i gaak wahn duhng\n|j=tou<sup>2</sup> dei<sup>6</sup> goi<sup>2</sup> gaak<sup>3</sup> wan<sup>6</sup> dung<sup>6</sup>\n}}\n\nThe '''Chinese Land Reform Movement''', also known by the Chinese abbreviation '''T\u01d4g\u01cei''' (\u571f\u6539), was a campaign by the Communist Party leader [[Mao Zedong]] during the late phase of the [[Chinese Civil War]] and the early [[People's Republic of China]].<ref name=Short>{{cite book|last=Short|first=Philip|title=Mao: A Life|publisher=Owl Books|year=2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HQwoTtJ43_AC&pg=PA436|isbn=0-8050-6638-1|pages=436\u20137}}</ref> The campaign involved mass killings of [[landlords]] by tenants and land redistribution to the [[peasantry]].<ref name=Scheidel226/> The estimated death count of the movement ranges from hundreds of thousands to millions.<ref name=\"Roberts\">{{cite book |last= Roberts|first=J. A. G.|date=2006|title=A History of China (Palgrave Essential Histories Series)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oJhMDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA257|location= |publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]]|page=257 |isbn=978-1403992758|author-link=J. A. G. Roberts|quote=\"Estimates of the number of landlords and rural power-holders who died range from 200,000 to two million.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"Teiwes\"/><ref name=Rummel223>{{cite book|last=Rummel|first=Rudolph J.|title=China's bloody century: genocide and mass murder since 1900|publisher=Transaction Publishers|year=2007|page=223|url=http://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/NOTE2.HTM|isbn=978-1-4128-0670-1|access-date=2016-11-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109091539/https://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/NOTE2.HTM|archive-date=2016-11-09|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThose who were killed were targeted on the basis of their [[social class]] rather than on the basis of their [[Ethnic group|ethnicity]]; the neologism \"[[classicide]]\" is used to describe the killings.<ref name=Wu> {{encyclopedia|last= Wu |first = Harry| chapter= Classicide in Communist China|editor-last = Arrigo, Bruce and Heather Bersot  |year = 2013 |title = The Routledge Handbook of International Crime and Justice Studies | |publisher = Routledge| location = |url= |isbn = 9781136868504|ref = none}}, [https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=8WptAAAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PR25&dq=classicide&ots=uq4DuOFT_q&sig=oCVuLPriVw4ZjVSSIA6MSjYAonM#v=onepage&q=classicide&f=false xxv-xxvi] </ref> Class-motivated [[Mass murder|mass killings]] continued almost throughout the 30 years of social and economic transformation in [[Maoist China]], and by the end of reforms, the landlord class had been largely eliminated from Mainland China or had fled to [[Taiwan]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=BHaRAAAAIAAJ]\"Wealthy farmers\" and rural landlords fleeing the communist land redistribution program (mostly during 1951 to 1954)</ref> By 1953, land reform in most parts of mainland China was completed except in [[Xinjiang]], [[Tibet]], [[Qinghai]], and [[Sichuan]]. From 1953 onwards, the Communist Party of China began to implement collective ownership of expropriated land through the creation of \"Agricultural Production Cooperatives\" transferring property rights from the former landlord class to the Chinese state.\n\n== Origins ==\n{{History of the People's Republic of China}}\nIn the mid-19th century, the [[Taiping Rebellion]] had a short-lived program of [[Taiping Heavenly Kingdom#Policies|land confiscation and redistribution]] and after\nthe [[Xinhai Revolution]] in 1911, the founder of the [[Kuomintang|Nationalist Party]], [[Sun Yat-sen]], advocated a \"[[Land reform|land to the tiller]]\" program of [[Socialist ideology of the Kuomintang#History|equal distribution of land]] which was partly implemented by the Nationalist Government under [[Chiang Kai-shek]].\n\nAs early as 1927, [[Mao Zedong]] believed that the countryside would be the basis of revolution. Land reform was key for the [[Communist Party of China]] both to carry out its program of social equality and to extend its control to the countryside. Unlike in Russia before the revolution, peasants in imperial China were not in feudal bondage to large estates; they either owned their land or rented it. They marketed their crops for cash in village markets, but [[Chinese gentry|local elites]] used their connections with officialdom to dominate local society. When the central government began to lose control in the late 19th century and then disintegrated after 1911, the local gentry and clan organizations became even more powerful. {{sfnb|M\u00fchlhahn|2019|p=402}} Mao's 1927 ''[[Report on an Investigation of the Peasant Movement in Hunan]]'' advocated a then heretical strategy of mobilizing poor peasants to carry out \"struggle\" (''douzheng'' ). Mao from that point on rejected the idea of peaceful land reform, arguing that peasants could not achieve true liberation unless they participated in the violent overthrow of the landlords.{{sfnb|DeMare|2019|p = 10, 104-105}}\n\nOver the following decades, the Party went back and forth on strategy. Leaders fought over such questions as the level of violence which was to be used; whether to woo or target middle peasants, who farmed most of the land; or to redistribute all of the land to poor peasants.{{sfnb|DeMare|2019|pp= 6-17}} During the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]] and the [[Second United Front]], the Party emphasized Sun Yat-sen's moderate \"[[land to the tiller]]\" program, which limited rent to 37 1/2% of the crop, rather than land redistribution. At the outbreak of the [[Chinese Civil War]] in 1946, however, Mao began to push for a return to radical policies to mobilize the village against the Landlord class, but protected the rights of middle peasants and specified that rich peasants were not landlords.  {{sfnb|DeMare|2019|p=10-11}} The July 7 Directive of 1946 set off eighteen months of fierce conflict in which all rich peasant and landlord property of all types was to be confiscated and redistributed to poor peasants. Party work teams went quickly from village to village and divided the population into landlords, rich, middle,  poor, and landless peasants. Because the work teams did not involve villagers in the process, however, rich and middle peasants quickly returned to power. {{sfnb|Tanner|2015| pp = 134-135}} \n\nThe Outline Land Law of October 1947 increased the pressure. <ref>Saich ''The Rise to Power of the Chinese Communist Party'' [https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Rise_to_Power_of_the_Chinese_Communi/w48YDQAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=%22Outline+Land+Law%22+-wikipedia&printsec=frontcover Outline Land Law of 1947] </ref> Party central sent the work teams back to the villages to put poor and landless peasants in charge, mandating the elimination of land rent, which it termed \"feudal exploitation\", and the elimination of landlord status. The work teams mobilized poor and landless peasants to take direct and violent action against the leading clans and families of neighboring villages to ensure that family loyalties not interfere with the campaign. <ref>{{cite book |last = Tanner |first =Harold Miles   |year = 2015 |title = Where Chiang Kai-Shek Lost China: The Liao-Shen Campaign, 1948 | |publisher = Indiana University Press| location = Bloomington|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=no4bCgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |isbn = 9780253016928 |ref = harv}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=no4bCgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=land%20reform&f=false p.135-137]</ref> In one village in southern Hebei, a foreign observer recorded that four people were stoned to death, {{sfnb|CrookCrook|1979|p = 151}} and [[William H. Hinton|William Hinton]] reported that at least a dozen people were beaten to death in the village he called Longbow. {{sfnb|Hinton|1966| p = xi}}\n\nThe \"Land Reform Law of the People's Republic of China\" of June 1950 coincided with campaigns against Nationalist troops and local resistance. Implementation began in the fall, usually preceded by campaigns of rent reduction.{{sfnb|DeMare|2019|p= 167-168}}\n\n== Mass killings of landlords ==\n{{see also|Struggle session|Laogai}}\n=== Initial campaign (1947\u20131951) ===\nShortly after the founding of the PRC in 1949, land reform, according to Mao biographer [[Philip Short]], \"lurched violently to the left\" with Mao Zedong laying down new guidelines for \"not correcting excesses prematurely.\"<ref name=Short/> Beatings, while not officially promoted by the party, were not prohibited either. While landlords had no protection, those who were branded \"rich peasants\" received moderate protections from violence and those on the lower end were fully protected.<ref name=Scheidel225>{{cite book | last =Scheidel | first =Walter | author-link =Walter Scheidel | title =The Great Leveler: Violence and the History of Inequality from the Stone Age to the Twenty-First Century | publisher =[[Princeton University Press]] | location = | year =2017 | isbn =978-0-691-16502-8 | url =http://press.princeton.edu/titles/10921.html | page =225 | access-date =2017-09-03 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20170904231557/http://press.princeton.edu/titles/10921.html | archive-date =2017-09-04 | url-status =live }}</ref>\n[[File:Choubapi.jpg|thumb|left|300px|A farmer confronting a landlord, 1946.]]\nIn this vein Mao insisted that the people themselves, not the [[secret police|security organs]], should become involved in enacting the Land Reform Law and killing the [[landlords]] who had oppressed them, which was quite different from [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] practice.<ref name=Short/> Mao thought that peasants who killed landlords would become permanently linked to the revolutionary process in a way that passive spectators could not be.<ref name=Short/> Some condemned as landlords were buried alive, dismembered, strangled and shot.<ref name=Scheidel225/> \n\nEstimates for the number of deaths range from a lower range of 200,000 to 800,000,<ref name=\"Roberts\"/><ref name=\"Teiwes\">{{encyclopedia |last=Teiwes |first=Frederic |chapter=Establishment of the New Regime |editor1-last=Twitchett |editor1-first=Denis |editor2=John K. Fairbank |editor3=Roderick MacFarquhar |title=The Cambridge history of China |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=0-521-24336-X |page=87 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ioppEjkCkeEC&pg=PA87&dq=at+least+one+landlord,+and+usually+several,+in+virtually+every+village+for+public+execution&ei=wP14R6muKIi0iQHR4ezAAQ&ie=ISO-8859-1&sig=9REVjFOEIx_4TIMFixd7fhgC9FY |accessdate=2008-08-23 |quote=\"For a careful review of the evidence and a cautious estimate of 200,000 two 800,000 executions, see Benedict Stavis, ''The Politics of Agricultural Mechanization in China'' (Ithaca, NY: Cornell University Press, 1978), 25-30. |date= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220225306/https://books.google.com/books?id=ioppEjkCkeEC&pg=PA87&dq=at+least+one+landlord,+and+usually+several,+in+virtually+every+village+for+public+execution&ei=wP14R6muKIi0iQHR4ezAAQ&ie=ISO-8859-1&sig=9REVjFOEIx_4TIMFixd7fhgC9FY |archivedate=2019-02-20 |url-status=live }}</ref> and higher estimates of 2,000,000<ref name=\"Roberts\"/><ref name=\"Teiwes\"/><ref name=\"Mao 1999\">[[Maurice Meisner]]. ''Mao's China and After: A History of the People's Republic, Third Edition.'' Free Press, 1999. {{ISBN|0-684-85635-2}} p. 72: \"...&nbsp;the estimate of many relatively impartial observers that there were {{formatnum:2000000}} people executed during the first three years of the People's Republic is probably as accurate a guess as one can make on the basis of scanty information.\"</ref> to 5 million<ref>Steven W. Mosher. ''China Misperceived: American Illusions and Chinese Reality.'' [[Basic Books]], 1992. {{ISBN|0-465-09813-4}} pg 74: \"...a figure that [[John K. Fairbank|Fairbank]] has cited as the upper range of \"sober\" estimates.\"</ref><ref name=feig>Lee Feigon. ''Mao: A Reinterpretation.'' Ivan R. Dee, 2002. {{ISBN|1-56663-522-5}} p. 96: \"By 1952 they had extended land reform throughout the countryside, but in the process somewhere between two and five million landlords had been killed.\"</ref> executions for the years 1949\u20131953, along with 1.5 million people,<ref name=\"Philip Short\">{{cite book |last=Short |first=Philip |title=Mao: A Life |publisher=Owl Books |year=2001 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HQwoTtJ43_AC&pg=PA436&dq=%27%27At+least+a+million-and-a-half+more+disappeared+into+the+newly+established+%27reform+through+labour%27+camps,+purpose-built+to+accommodate+them&ei=L_54R6eOFYq-igG72-2XCA&ie=ISO-8859-1&sig=lJa-WxMPEygPOSBdsIoT13cmSHY |isbn=0-8050-6638-1 |pages=436 |access-date=2019-09-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220225307/https://books.google.com/books?id=HQwoTtJ43_AC&pg=PA436&dq=%27%27At+least+a+million-and-a-half+more+disappeared+into+the+newly+established+%27reform+through+labour%27+camps,+purpose-built+to+accommodate+them&ei=L_54R6eOFYq-igG72-2XCA&ie=ISO-8859-1&sig=lJa-WxMPEygPOSBdsIoT13cmSHY |archive-date=2019-02-20 |url-status=live }}</ref> to 6 million,<ref name=\"Valentino\">Benjamin A. Valentino. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=LQfeXVU_EvgC&pg=PA121&dq=four+million+to+six+million+forced+labor#v=onepage&q=four%20million%20to%20six%20million%20forced%20labor&f=false Final Solutions: Mass Killing and Genocide in the Twentieth Century] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220225307/https://books.google.com/books?id=LQfeXVU_EvgC&pg=PA121&dq=four+million+to+six+million+forced+labor#v=onepage&q=four%20million%20to%20six%20million%20forced%20labor&f=false |date=2019-02-20 }}'' [[Cornell University Press]], 2004. pp. 121-122. {{ISBN|0-8014-3965-5}}</ref> being sent to [[laogai|\"reform through labour\"]] camps where many perished.<ref name=\"Valentino\"/> There were policies in certain regions of China not necessarily obeyed{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} which required the selection of \"at least one landlord, and usually several, in virtually every village for public execution\".<ref name=\"Teiwes\"/> [[Philip Short]] noted that such estimates exclude the hundreds of thousands driven to suicide during [[Struggle Session|\"struggle sessions\"]] of the [[three-anti/five-anti campaigns]], which also occurred around the same time.<ref>{{cite book |last=Short |first=Philip |title=Mao: A Life |publisher=Owl Books |year=2001 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4y6mACbLWGsC&pg=PA437&dq=mao+while+the+worst+among+them+should+be+shot&ei=ipaVSYquJpLmyQTiieWsDw |isbn=0-8050-6638-1 |pages=437 |access-date=2019-09-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220225305/https://books.google.com/books?id=4y6mACbLWGsC&pg=PA437&dq=mao+while+the+worst+among+them+should+be+shot&ei=ipaVSYquJpLmyQTiieWsDw |archive-date=2019-02-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Retaliation by landlords ===\nDuring the [[Chinese Civil War]], the [[Kuomintang]] helped establish the \"Huanxiang Tuan\" ({{zh|s=\u9084\u9109\u5718|p=Hu\u00e1n xi\u0101ng tu\u00e1n}}), or Homecoming Legion, which was composed of landlords who sought the return of their redistributed land and property from peasants and CCP guerrillas, as well as forcibly conscripted peasants and communist POWs.<ref name=\"Liu\">{{cite book | last =  Zaiyu | first = Liu | title = \u7b2c\u4e8c\u6b21\u570b\u5171\u6230\u722d\u6642\u671f\u7684\u9084\u9109\u5718 | publisher = Twenty First Century Bimonthly| location = Hong Kong| year = 2002  |url=http://www.cuhk.edu.hk/ics/21c/media/articles/c071-200104044.pdf}}</ref> The Homecoming legion conducted its guerrilla warfare campaign against CCP forces and purported collaborators up until the end of the civil war in 1949.<ref name=\"Liu\"/>\n\n==Land redistribution==\nLand seized from Landlords was brought under [[collective ownership]] resulting in the creation of \"Agricultural production cooperatives\".<ref>{{cite web |title=\u5728\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u515a\u7b2c\u4e03\u5c4a\u4e2d\u592e\u59d4\u5458\u4f1a\u7b2c\u516d\u6b21\u5168\u4f53\u4f1a\u8bae\u4e0a |url=http://www.gov.cn/test/2008-06/03/content_1003737.htm |website=Central People's Government of the People's Republic of China |accessdate=27 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191027012546/http://www.gov.cn/test/2008-06/03/content_1003737.htm |archive-date=27 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the mid-1950s, a second land reform during the [[Great Leap Forward]] compelled individual farmers to join collectives, which, in turn, were grouped into [[People's communes]] with centrally controlled [[property rights]] and an egalitarian principle of distribution. This policy was generally a failure in terms of production.{{sfnb|ChenDavis|1998}} The PRC reversed this policy in 1962 through the proclamation of the Sixty Articles. As a result, the ownership of the basic means of production was divided into three levels with collective land ownership vested in the production team.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|+Ownership of cultivable land before reform in mainland China<ref name=\"\u5efa\u56fd\u4e09\u5341\u5e74\u5168\u56fd\u519c\u4e1a\u7edf\u8ba1\u8d44\u6599\">\u56fd\u5bb6\u7edf\u8ba1\u5c40\u7f16\uff1a\u300a\u5efa\u56fd\u4e09\u5341\u5e74\u5168\u56fd\u519c\u4e1a\u7edf\u8ba1\u8d44\u6599\uff081949\uff0d1979\uff09\u300b\uff0c1980\u5e743\u6708\u5370\u5236\u3002</ref>{{efn|1=The number of households, population, and total arable land are based on the 1950 agricultural production annual report. The figures for each class are calculated based on the proportion of each class before the land reform in each region.}}\n!Classification!! Number of households<br>(10,000)!! Proportion of households<br>(%) !! Population<br>(Millions) !! Population ratio<br>(%) !! Farmland<br >(10,000 mu)!! The proportion of cultivated land<br>(%) !! The average cultivated land <br>(mu)!! Per capita cultivated land<br>(mu)\n|-\n!Poor Farmer\n| 6062 || 57.44 || 24123 || 52.37 || 21503 || 14.28 || 3.55 || 0.89\n|-\n!Middle Peasants\n| 3081 || 29.20 || 15260 || 33.13 || 46577 || 30.94 || 15.12 || 3.05\n|-\n!Rich Farmer\n| 325 || 3.08 || 2144 || 4.66 || 20566 || 13.66 || 63.24 || 9.59\n|-\n!Landlord \n| 400 || 3.79 || 2188 || 4.75 || 57588 || 38.26 || 144.11 || 26.32\n|-\n!Other\n| 686 || 6.49 || 2344 || 5.09 || 4300 || 2.86 || 6.27 || 1.83\n|-\n!Total  \n| 10554 || 100.00 || 46059 || 100.00 || 150534 || 100.00 || 14.26 || 3.27\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|+Ownership of cultivable land after reform in mainland China<ref name=\"\u5efa\u56fd\u4e09\u5341\u5e74\u5168\u56fd\u519c\u4e1a\u7edf\u8ba1\u8d44\u6599\"/>{{efn|1=The number of households was calculated based on the survey data of 9900 households in 21 provinces and autonomous regions. Others are calculated based on the survey data of more than 15,000 rural households in 23 provinces and autonomous regions in 1954.}}\n!Classification!! Number of households<br>(%) !! Population<br>(%) !! Cultivated land<br>(%) !! Per capita cultivated land<br>(mu)!! Large livestock<br>( Head/100 households)\n|-\n!Poor Farmer\n| 54.5|| 52.2|| 47.1|| 12.5|| 46.73\n|-\n!Middle Peasants\n| 39.3|| 39.9|| 44.3|| 19.0|| 90.93\n|-\n!Rich Farmer\n| 3.1|| 5.3|| 6.4|| 25.1|| 114.86\n|-\n!Landlord\n| 2.4|| 2.6|| 2.2|| 12.2|| 23.19\n|-\n!Other\n| 0.7|| --|| --|| --|| --\n|-\n!Total\n| 100.00|| 100.00|| 100.00|| 15.3|| 64.01\n|}\n\n==== Economic effects ====\n[[file:Visit to the People's Commune named Chinese-Hungarian Friendship-3.jpg|thumb|right|An example of a people's commune collective farm.]]\nHistorian [[Walter Scheidel]] writes that the violence of the land reform campaign had a significant impact on [[economic inequality]]. He gives as an example the village of Zhangzhuangcun, made famous by [[William H. Hinton|William Hinton]]'s book ''[[Fanshen]]'': {{quote|In Zhangzhuangcun, in the more thoroughly reformed north of the country, most \"landlords\" and \"rich peasants\" had lost all their land and often their lives or had fled. All formerly landless workers had received land, which eliminated this category altogether. As a result, \"middling peasants,\" who now accounted for 90 percent of the village population, owned 90.8 percent of the land, as close to perfect equality as one could possibly hope for.<ref name=Scheidel226>{{cite book | last =Scheidel | first =Walter | author-link =Walter Scheidel | title =The Great Leveler: Violence and the History of Inequality from the Stone Age to the Twenty-First Century | publisher =[[Princeton University Press]] | location = | year =2017 | isbn =978-0-691-16502-8 | url =http://press.princeton.edu/titles/10921.html | page =226 | access-date =2017-09-03 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20170904231557/http://press.princeton.edu/titles/10921.html | archive-date =2017-09-04 | url-status =live }}</ref>}}\n\nBy 1958 private ownership was entirely abolished and households all over China were forced into state-operated communes. Chinese leadership insisted that the communes must produce more grain for the cities and earn foreign exchange from exports. These reforms were generally unpopular with the peasants and usually implemented by summoning them to meetings and making them stay there for days and sometimes weeks until they \"voluntarily\" agreed to join the collective.\n\n==== Great Leap Forward ====\n\nDuring the [[Great Leap Forward]], the state introduced a system of compulsory state purchases of grain at fixed prices to build up stockpiles for famine-relief and meet the terms of its trade agreements with the [[Soviet Union]]. Together, taxation and compulsory purchases accounted for 30% of the harvest by 1957, leaving very little surplus.<ref>Mirsky, Jonathan. \"[http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2009/feb/26/the-china-we-dont-know/ The China We Don't Know] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016120725/http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2009/feb/26/the-china-we-dont-know/ |date=2015-10-16 }}.\" New York Review of Books Volume 56, Number 3. February 26, 2009.</ref> Rationing was also introduced in the cities to curb 'wasteful consumption' and encourage savings (which were deposited in state-owned banks and thus became available for investment), and although food could be purchased from state-owned retailers the market price was higher than that for which it had been purchased. This too was done in the name of discouraging excessive consumption.\n\nDuring 1958\u20131960 China continued to be a substantial net exporter of grain, despite the widespread famine experienced in the countryside, as Mao sought to maintain face and convince the outside world of the success of his plans. Foreign aid was refused. When the Japanese foreign minister told his Chinese counterpart Chen Yi of an offer of 100,000 tonnes of wheat to be shipped out of public view, he was rebuffed. [[John F. Kennedy]] was also aware that the Chinese were exporting food to Africa and Cuba during the famine and said \"we've had no indication from the Chinese Communists that they would welcome any offer of food.\"<ref>{{cite|last= Dik\u00f6tter|first = Frank|title =Mao's Great Famine: The History of China's Most Devastating Catastrophe, 1958-62|place = London| publisher = Bloomsbury| year =2010 |ref= harv}}, p. = [https://books.google.com/books?id=nuKoQeYTGRMC&pg=PA115&lpg=PA115&dq=japanese+foreign+minister+told+his+Chinese+counterpart+Chen+Yi+of+an+offer+of+100,000+tonnes+of+wheat&source=bl&ots=BGb-UJXDLq&sig=ACfU3U0icQ09IwgUFMxCzlsYCPMxFAMwSQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjx2d-QgdrlAhUHPq0KHcenA4QQ6AEwC3oECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=japanese%20foreign%20minister%20told%20his%20Chinese%20counterpart%20Chen%20Yi%20of%20an%20offer%20of%20100%2C000%20tonnes%20of%20wheat&f=false 114\u2013115].</ref> With dramatically reduced yields, even urban areas suffered much reduced rations; however, mass starvation was largely confined to the countryside, where, as a result of drastically inflated production statistics, very little grain was left for the peasants to eat.\n\n==Land reform in Taiwan==\n{{main|Land Reform in Taiwan}}\nAfter its retreat to Taiwan, the Nationalist government carried out a program of land reform under the [[Joint Commission on Rural Reconstruction]].<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=MacFaquhar|editor1-first=Roderick|editor2-last=Fairbank|editor2-first=John K.|title=The People's Republic.|date=1991|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge [Cambridgeshire]|isbn=9780521243377 |author-last=Clough |author-first=Ralph |chapter=Chapter 12: Taiwan under Nationalist Rule, 1949-1982 |page=837 |ref=none}}</ref> The [[land reform]] law removed the landlord class, and created a higher number of peasants who, with the help of the [[sovereign state|state]], dramatically increased Taiwan's agricultural output.<ref name=\"historycooperative.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://historycooperative.org/journal/the-labour-movement-in-taiwan/|title=The Labour Movement in Taiwan|date=September 21, 2004|access-date=November 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021063230/https://historycooperative.org/journal/the-labour-movement-in-taiwan/|archive-date=October 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Land reform also succeeded because the [[Kuomintang]]'s members were mostly from [[mainland China]] and as a result, they had few ties with the remaining indigenous Taiwanese landowners.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.landreform.org.tw/html/01.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725231354/http://www.landreform.org.tw/html/01.htm |archivedate=2011-07-25 |trans-title=Land Reform Museum |script-title=zh:\u571f\u5730\u6539\u9769\u7d00\u5ff5\u9928 |language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Collectivization in the Soviet Union]]\n* [[Dekulakization]]\n* [[Land reform by country]]\n* [[Land reform in Vietnam]]\n* [[Mass killings under communist regimes]]\n* [[Socialist ideology of the Kuomintang]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography and further reading==\n{{Library resources box}}\n\n* {{cite journal| url =http://www.fao.org/3/x1372t/x1372t10.htm |title = Land reform in rural China since the mid-1980s| author1-first = Fu |author1-last = Chen|author2-first = John |author2-last = Davis|publisher = Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations| year = 1998|journal = Land Reform|ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1 = Crook|first1 = Isabel|first2 = David|last2 = Crook|year = 1979|title = Ten Mile Inn: Mass Movement in a Chinese Village|7 = |publisher = Pantheon Books|location = New York|isbn = 0394411781|ref = harv|url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/tenmileinnmassmo0000croo}}\n*{{cite book |last = DeMare |first=Brian James  |year = 2019 |title = Land Wars: The Story of China's Agrarian Revolution |publisher = Stanford University Press| location = Palo Alto, CA |isbn = 9781503609525|ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book |last = Hinton|first = William  |year = 1966 |title = Fanshen: A Documentary of Revolution in a Chinese Village | |publisher = Monthly Review Press| location = New York |isbn = |ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book |last = Li |first = Huaiyin |year = 2011 |title = Village China under Socialism and Reform : A Micro History, 1948-2008 | |publisher = Stanford University Press| location = Stanford, Calif.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Re4YLsESWjoC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&printsec=frontcover#v= |isbn = 0804776571|ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book |last = Moise  |first = Edwin E. |year = 1983 |title = Land Reform in China and North Vietnam : Consolidating the Revolution at the Village Level | |publisher = University of North Carolina Press| location = Chapel Hill |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Land_Reform_in_China_and_North_Vietnam/lAg1DgAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=moise+land+reform&printsec= |isbn = |ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book |last = M\u00fchlhahn  |first =  Klaus|year = 2019 |title = Making China Modern: From the Great Qing to Xi Jinping |publisher = Harvard University Press| location = Cambridge, Massachusetts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uxN-DwAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v= |isbn = |ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book |last = Shue |first=Vivienne |year = 1980 |title = Peasant China in Transition: The Dynamics of Development toward Socialism, 1949-1956  |publisher = University of California Press| location = Berkeley, CA|url=https://archive.org/details/peasantchinaintr0000shue |url-access = registration |isbn = 9780520037342|ref = none}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://chineseposters.net/themes/land-reform.php Land Reform and Collectivization (1950-1953)] Posters from the Stephan Landsberger collection. There are other posters on the topic in other sections of the site.\n\n[[Category:Political repression in China]]\n[[Category:Campaigns of the Communist Party of China]]\n[[Category:Communist repression]]\n[[Category:Political and cultural purges]]\n[[Category:Massacres in China]]\n[[Category:Human rights abuses]]\n[[Category:Class discrimination]]\n[[Category:Cold War history of China]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1947]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1948]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1949]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1950]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1951]]\n[[Category:1950s murders in China]]\n[[Category:1940s murders in China]]\n[[Category:Chinese landlords]]\n[[Category:Mao Zedong]]\n[[Category:Land reform]]\n[[Category:Man-made disasters in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Chinese\n|pic=A man reads the Land Reform Law of PRC.jpg\n|piccap=The land reform staff publicizing the Land Reform Law to peasants in 1950.\n|picsize=300px\n|altname=Formal name\n|s=\u571f\u5730\u6539\u9769\u8fd0\u52a8\n|t=\u571f\u5730\u6539\u9769\u904b\u52d5\n|l=Land Reform Movement\n|order=st\n|p=T\u01d4d\u00ec g\u01ceig\u00e9 y\u00f9nd\u00f2ng\n|w=Tu<sup>3</sup> ti<sup>4</sup> kai<sup>3</sup> ko<sup>2</sup> yun<sup>4</sup> tong<sup>4</sup>\n|bpmf=\u310a\u3128\u02c7 \u3109\u3127\u02cb \u310d\u311e\u02c7 \u310d\u311c\u02ca \u3129\u3123\u02cb \u3109\u3128\u3125\u02cb \n|myr=Tu<sup>3</sup>di<sup>4</sup> gai<sup>3</sup>ge<sup>2</sup> yun<sup>4</sup>dung<sup>4</sup>\n|y=t\u00f3u deih g\u00f3i gaak wahn duhng\n|j=tou<sup>2</sup> dei<sup>6</sup> goi<sup>2</sup> gaak<sup>3</sup> wan<sup>6</sup> dung<sup>6</sup>\n}}\n\nThe '''Chinese Land Reform Movement''', also known by the Chinese abbreviation '''T\u01d4g\u01cei''' (\u571f\u6539), was a campaign by the Communist Party leader [[Mao Zedong]] during the late phase of the [[Chinese Civil War]] and the early [[People's Republic of China]].<ref name=Short>{{cite book|last=Short|first=Philip|title=Mao: A Life|publisher=Owl Books|year=2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HQwoTtJ43_AC&pg=PA436|isbn=0-8050-6638-1|pages=436\u20137}}</ref> The campaign involved mass killings of [[landlords]] by tenants and land redistribution to the [[peasantry]].<ref name=Scheidel226/> The estimated death count of the movement ranges from hundreds of thousands to millions.<ref name=\"Roberts\">{{cite book |last= Roberts|first=J. A. G.|date=2006|title=A History of China (Palgrave Essential Histories Series)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oJhMDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA257|location= |publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]]|page=257 |isbn=978-1403992758|author-link=J. A. G. Roberts|quote=\"Estimates of the number of landlords and rural power-holders who died range from 200,000 to two million.\"}}</ref><ref name=\"Teiwes\"/><ref name=Rummel223>{{cite book|last=Rummel|first=Rudolph J.|title=China's bloody century: genocide and mass murder since 1900|publisher=Transaction Publishers|year=2007|page=223|url=http://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/NOTE2.HTM|isbn=978-1-4128-0670-1|access-date=2016-11-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109091539/https://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/NOTE2.HTM|archive-date=2016-11-09|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThose who were killed were targeted on the basis of their [[social class]] rather than on the basis of their [[Ethnic group|ethnicity]]; the neologism \"[[classicide]]\" is used to describe the killings.<ref name=Wu> {{encyclopedia|last= Wu |first = Harry| chapter= Classicide in Communist China|editor-last = Arrigo, Bruce and Heather Bersot  |year = 2013 |title = The Routledge Handbook of International Crime and Justice Studies | |publisher = Routledge| location = |url= |isbn = 9781136868504|ref = none}}, [https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=8WptAAAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PR25&dq=classicide&ots=uq4DuOFT_q&sig=oCVuLPriVw4ZjVSSIA6MSjYAonM#v=onepage&q=classicide&f=false xxv-xxvi] </ref> Class-motivated [[Mass murder|mass killings]] continued almost throughout the 30 years of social and economic transformation in [[Maoist China]], and by the end of reforms, the landlord class had been largely eliminated from Mainland China or had fled to [[Taiwan]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=BHaRAAAAIAAJ]\"Wealthy farmers\" and rural landlords fleeing the communist land redistribution program (mostly during 1951 to 1954)</ref> By 1953, land reform in most parts of mainland China was completed except in [[Xinjiang]], [[Tibet]], [[Qinghai]], and [[Sichuan]]. From 1953 onwards, the Communist Party of China began to implement collective ownership of expropriated land through the creation of \"Agricultural Production Cooperatives\" transferring property rights from the former landlord class to the Chinese state.\n\n== Origins ==\n{{History of the People's Republic of China}}\nIn the mid-19th century, the [[Taiping Rebellion]] had a short-lived program of [[Taiping Heavenly Kingdom#Policies|land confiscation and redistribution]] and after\nthe [[Xinhai Revolution]] in 1911, the founder of the [[Kuomintang|Nationalist Party]], [[Sun Yat-sen]], advocated a \"[[Land reform|land to the tiller]]\" program of [[Socialist ideology of the Kuomintang#History|equal distribution of land]] which was partly implemented by the Nationalist Government under [[Chiang Kai-shek]].\n\nAs early as 1927, [[Mao Zedong]] believed that the countryside would be the basis of revolution. Land reform was key for the [[Communist Party of China]] both to carry out its program of social equality and to extend its control to the countryside. Unlike in Russia before the revolution, peasants in imperial China were not in feudal bondage to large estates; they either owned their land or rented it. They marketed their crops for cash in village markets, but [[Chinese gentry|local elites]] used their connections with officialdom to dominate local society. When the central government began to lose control in the late 19th century and then disintegrated after 1911, the local gentry and clan organizations became even more powerful. {{sfnb|M\u00fchlhahn|2019|p=402}} Mao's 1927 ''[[Report on an Investigation of the Peasant Movement in Hunan]]'' advocated a then heretical strategy of mobilizing poor peasants to carry out \"struggle\" (''douzheng'' ). Mao from that point on rejected the idea of peaceful land reform, arguing that peasants could not achieve true liberation unless they participated in the violent overthrow of the landlords.{{sfnb|DeMare|2019|p = 10, 104-105}}\n\nOver the following decades, the Party went back and forth on strategy. Leaders fought over such questions as the level of violence which was to be used; whether to woo or target middle peasants, who farmed most of the land; or to redistribute all of the land to poor peasants.{{sfnb|DeMare|2019|pp= 6-17}} During the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]] and the [[Second United Front]], the Party emphasized Sun Yat-sen's moderate \"[[land to the tiller]]\" program, which limited rent to 37 1/2% of the crop, rather than land redistribution. At the outbreak of the [[Chinese Civil War]] in 1946, however, Mao began to push for a return to radical policies to mobilize the village against the Landlord class, but protected the rights of middle peasants and specified that rich peasants were not landlords.  {{sfnb|DeMare|2019|p=10-11}} The July 7 Directive of 1946 set off eighteen months of fierce conflict in which all rich peasant and landlord property of all types was to be confiscated and redistributed to poor peasants. Party work teams went quickly from village to village and divided the population into landlords, rich, middle,  poor, and landless peasants. Because the work teams did not involve villagers in the process, however, rich and middle peasants quickly returned to power. {{sfnb|Tanner|2015| pp = 134-135}} \n\nThe Outline Land Law of October 1947 increased the pressure. <ref>Saich ''The Rise to Power of the Chinese Communist Party'' [https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Rise_to_Power_of_the_Chinese_Communi/w48YDQAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=%22Outline+Land+Law%22+-wikipedia&printsec=frontcover Outline Land Law of 1947] </ref> Party central sent the work teams back to the villages to put poor and landless peasants in charge, mandating the elimination of land rent, which it termed \"feudal exploitation\", and the elimination of landlord status. The work teams mobilized poor and landless peasants to take direct and violent action against the leading clans and families of neighboring villages to ensure that family loyalties not interfere with the campaign. <ref>{{cite book |last = Tanner |first =Harold Miles   |year = 2015 |title = Where Chiang Kai-Shek Lost China: The Liao-Shen Campaign, 1948 | |publisher = Indiana University Press| location = Bloomington|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=no4bCgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |isbn = 9780253016928 |ref = harv}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=no4bCgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=land%20reform&f=false p.135-137]</ref> In one village in southern Hebei, a foreign observer recorded that four people were stoned to death, {{sfnb|CrookCrook|1979|p = 151}} and [[William H. Hinton|William Hinton]] reported that at least a dozen people were beaten to death in the village he called Longbow. {{sfnb|Hinton|1966| p = xi}}\n\nThe \"Land Reform Law of the People's Repulic of China\" of June 1950 coincided with campaigns against Nationalist troops and local resistance. Implementation began in the fall, usually preceded by campaigns of rent reduction.{{sfnb|DeMare|2019|p= 167-168}}\n\n== Mass killings of landlords ==\n{{see also|Struggle session|Laogai}}\n=== Initial campaign (1947\u20131951) ===\nShortly after the founding of the PRC in 1949, land reform, according to Mao biographer [[Philip Short]], \"lurched violently to the left\" with Mao Zedong laying down new guidelines for \"not correcting excesses prematurely.\"<ref name=Short/> Beatings, while not officially promoted by the party, were not prohibited either. While landlords had no protection, those who were branded \"rich peasants\" received moderate protections from violence and those on the lower end were fully protected.<ref name=Scheidel225>{{cite book | last =Scheidel | first =Walter | author-link =Walter Scheidel | title =The Great Leveler: Violence and the History of Inequality from the Stone Age to the Twenty-First Century | publisher =[[Princeton University Press]] | location = | year =2017 | isbn =978-0-691-16502-8 | url =http://press.princeton.edu/titles/10921.html | page =225 | access-date =2017-09-03 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20170904231557/http://press.princeton.edu/titles/10921.html | archive-date =2017-09-04 | url-status =live }}</ref>\n[[File:Choubapi.jpg|thumb|left|300px|A farmer confronting a landlord, 1946.]]\nIn this vein Mao insisted that the people themselves, not the [[secret police|security organs]], should become involved in enacting the Land Reform Law and killing the [[landlords]] who had oppressed them, which was quite different from [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] practice.<ref name=Short/> Mao thought that peasants who killed landlords would become permanently linked to the revolutionary process in a way that passive spectators could not be.<ref name=Short/> Some condemned as landlords were buried alive, dismembered, strangled and shot.<ref name=Scheidel225/> \n\nEstimates for the number of deaths range from a lower range of 200,000 to 800,000,<ref name=\"Roberts\"/><ref name=\"Teiwes\">{{encyclopedia |last=Teiwes |first=Frederic |chapter=Establishment of the New Regime |editor1-last=Twitchett |editor1-first=Denis |editor2=John K. Fairbank |editor3=Roderick MacFarquhar |title=The Cambridge history of China |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=0-521-24336-X |page=87 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ioppEjkCkeEC&pg=PA87&dq=at+least+one+landlord,+and+usually+several,+in+virtually+every+village+for+public+execution&ei=wP14R6muKIi0iQHR4ezAAQ&ie=ISO-8859-1&sig=9REVjFOEIx_4TIMFixd7fhgC9FY |accessdate=2008-08-23 |quote=\"For a careful review of the evidence and a cautious estimate of 200,000 two 800,000 executions, see Benedict Stavis, ''The Politics of Agricultural Mechanization in China'' (Ithaca, NY: Cornell University Press, 1978), 25-30. |date= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220225306/https://books.google.com/books?id=ioppEjkCkeEC&pg=PA87&dq=at+least+one+landlord,+and+usually+several,+in+virtually+every+village+for+public+execution&ei=wP14R6muKIi0iQHR4ezAAQ&ie=ISO-8859-1&sig=9REVjFOEIx_4TIMFixd7fhgC9FY |archivedate=2019-02-20 |url-status=live }}</ref> and higher estimates of 2,000,000<ref name=\"Roberts\"/><ref name=\"Teiwes\"/><ref name=\"Mao 1999\">[[Maurice Meisner]]. ''Mao's China and After: A History of the People's Republic, Third Edition.'' Free Press, 1999. {{ISBN|0-684-85635-2}} p. 72: \"...&nbsp;the estimate of many relatively impartial observers that there were {{formatnum:2000000}} people executed during the first three years of the People's Republic is probably as accurate a guess as one can make on the basis of scanty information.\"</ref> to 5 million<ref>Steven W. Mosher. ''China Misperceived: American Illusions and Chinese Reality.'' [[Basic Books]], 1992. {{ISBN|0-465-09813-4}} pg 74: \"...a figure that [[John K. Fairbank|Fairbank]] has cited as the upper range of \"sober\" estimates.\"</ref><ref name=feig>Lee Feigon. ''Mao: A Reinterpretation.'' Ivan R. Dee, 2002. {{ISBN|1-56663-522-5}} p. 96: \"By 1952 they had extended land reform throughout the countryside, but in the process somewhere between two and five million landlords had been killed.\"</ref> executions for the years 1949\u20131953, along with 1.5 million people,<ref name=\"Philip Short\">{{cite book |last=Short |first=Philip |title=Mao: A Life |publisher=Owl Books |year=2001 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HQwoTtJ43_AC&pg=PA436&dq=%27%27At+least+a+million-and-a-half+more+disappeared+into+the+newly+established+%27reform+through+labour%27+camps,+purpose-built+to+accommodate+them&ei=L_54R6eOFYq-igG72-2XCA&ie=ISO-8859-1&sig=lJa-WxMPEygPOSBdsIoT13cmSHY |isbn=0-8050-6638-1 |pages=436 |access-date=2019-09-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220225307/https://books.google.com/books?id=HQwoTtJ43_AC&pg=PA436&dq=%27%27At+least+a+million-and-a-half+more+disappeared+into+the+newly+established+%27reform+through+labour%27+camps,+purpose-built+to+accommodate+them&ei=L_54R6eOFYq-igG72-2XCA&ie=ISO-8859-1&sig=lJa-WxMPEygPOSBdsIoT13cmSHY |archive-date=2019-02-20 |url-status=live }}</ref> to 6 million,<ref name=\"Valentino\">Benjamin A. Valentino. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=LQfeXVU_EvgC&pg=PA121&dq=four+million+to+six+million+forced+labor#v=onepage&q=four%20million%20to%20six%20million%20forced%20labor&f=false Final Solutions: Mass Killing and Genocide in the Twentieth Century] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220225307/https://books.google.com/books?id=LQfeXVU_EvgC&pg=PA121&dq=four+million+to+six+million+forced+labor#v=onepage&q=four%20million%20to%20six%20million%20forced%20labor&f=false |date=2019-02-20 }}'' [[Cornell University Press]], 2004. pp. 121-122. {{ISBN|0-8014-3965-5}}</ref> being sent to [[laogai|\"reform through labour\"]] camps where many perished.<ref name=\"Valentino\"/> There were policies in certain regions of China not necessarily obeyed{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} which required the selection of \"at least one landlord, and usually several, in virtually every village for public execution\".<ref name=\"Teiwes\"/> [[Philip Short]] noted that such estimates exclude the hundreds of thousands driven to suicide during [[Struggle Session|\"struggle sessions\"]] of the [[three-anti/five-anti campaigns]], which also occurred around the same time.<ref>{{cite book |last=Short |first=Philip |title=Mao: A Life |publisher=Owl Books |year=2001 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4y6mACbLWGsC&pg=PA437&dq=mao+while+the+worst+among+them+should+be+shot&ei=ipaVSYquJpLmyQTiieWsDw |isbn=0-8050-6638-1 |pages=437 |access-date=2019-09-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220225305/https://books.google.com/books?id=4y6mACbLWGsC&pg=PA437&dq=mao+while+the+worst+among+them+should+be+shot&ei=ipaVSYquJpLmyQTiieWsDw |archive-date=2019-02-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Retaliation by landlords ===\nDuring the [[Chinese Civil War]], the [[Kuomintang]] helped establish the \"Huanxiang Tuan\" ({{zh|s=\u9084\u9109\u5718|p=Hu\u00e1n xi\u0101ng tu\u00e1n}}), or Homecoming Legion, which was composed of landlords who sought the return of their redistributed land and property from peasants and CCP guerrillas, as well as forcibly conscripted peasants and communist POWs.<ref name=\"Liu\">{{cite book | last =  Zaiyu | first = Liu | title = \u7b2c\u4e8c\u6b21\u570b\u5171\u6230\u722d\u6642\u671f\u7684\u9084\u9109\u5718 | publisher = Twenty First Century Bimonthly| location = Hong Kong| year = 2002  |url=http://www.cuhk.edu.hk/ics/21c/media/articles/c071-200104044.pdf}}</ref> The Homecoming legion conducted its guerrilla warfare campaign against CCP forces and purported collaborators up until the end of the civil war in 1949.<ref name=\"Liu\"/>\n\n==Land redistribution==\nLand seized from Landlords was brought under [[collective ownership]] resulting in the creation of \"Agricultural production cooperatives\".<ref>{{cite web |title=\u5728\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u515a\u7b2c\u4e03\u5c4a\u4e2d\u592e\u59d4\u5458\u4f1a\u7b2c\u516d\u6b21\u5168\u4f53\u4f1a\u8bae\u4e0a |url=http://www.gov.cn/test/2008-06/03/content_1003737.htm |website=Central People's Government of the People's Republic of China |accessdate=27 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191027012546/http://www.gov.cn/test/2008-06/03/content_1003737.htm |archive-date=27 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the mid-1950s, a second land reform during the [[Great Leap Forward]] compelled individual farmers to join collectives, which, in turn, were grouped into [[People's communes]] with centrally controlled [[property rights]] and an egalitarian principle of distribution. This policy was generally a failure in terms of production.{{sfnb|ChenDavis|1998}} The PRC reversed this policy in 1962 through the proclamation of the Sixty Articles. As a result, the ownership of the basic means of production was divided into three levels with collective land ownership vested in the production team.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|+Ownership of cultivable land before reform in mainland China<ref name=\"\u5efa\u56fd\u4e09\u5341\u5e74\u5168\u56fd\u519c\u4e1a\u7edf\u8ba1\u8d44\u6599\">\u56fd\u5bb6\u7edf\u8ba1\u5c40\u7f16\uff1a\u300a\u5efa\u56fd\u4e09\u5341\u5e74\u5168\u56fd\u519c\u4e1a\u7edf\u8ba1\u8d44\u6599\uff081949\uff0d1979\uff09\u300b\uff0c1980\u5e743\u6708\u5370\u5236\u3002</ref>{{efn|1=The number of households, population, and total arable land are based on the 1950 agricultural production annual report. The figures for each class are calculated based on the proportion of each class before the land reform in each region.}}\n!Classification!! Number of households<br>(10,000)!! Proportion of households<br>(%) !! Population<br>(Millions) !! Population ratio<br>(%) !! Farmland<br >(10,000 mu)!! The proportion of cultivated land<br>(%) !! The average cultivated land <br>(mu)!! Per capita cultivated land<br>(mu)\n|-\n!Poor Farmer\n| 6062 || 57.44 || 24123 || 52.37 || 21503 || 14.28 || 3.55 || 0.89\n|-\n!Middle Peasants\n| 3081 || 29.20 || 15260 || 33.13 || 46577 || 30.94 || 15.12 || 3.05\n|-\n!Rich Farmer\n| 325 || 3.08 || 2144 || 4.66 || 20566 || 13.66 || 63.24 || 9.59\n|-\n!Landlord \n| 400 || 3.79 || 2188 || 4.75 || 57588 || 38.26 || 144.11 || 26.32\n|-\n!Other\n| 686 || 6.49 || 2344 || 5.09 || 4300 || 2.86 || 6.27 || 1.83\n|-\n!Total  \n| 10554 || 100.00 || 46059 || 100.00 || 150534 || 100.00 || 14.26 || 3.27\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|+Ownership of cultivable land after reform in mainland China<ref name=\"\u5efa\u56fd\u4e09\u5341\u5e74\u5168\u56fd\u519c\u4e1a\u7edf\u8ba1\u8d44\u6599\"/>{{efn|1=The number of households was calculated based on the survey data of 9900 households in 21 provinces and autonomous regions. Others are calculated based on the survey data of more than 15,000 rural households in 23 provinces and autonomous regions in 1954.}}\n!Classification!! Number of households<br>(%) !! Population<br>(%) !! Cultivated land<br>(%) !! Per capita cultivated land<br>(mu)!! Large livestock<br>( Head/100 households)\n|-\n!Poor Farmer\n| 54.5|| 52.2|| 47.1|| 12.5|| 46.73\n|-\n!Middle Peasants\n| 39.3|| 39.9|| 44.3|| 19.0|| 90.93\n|-\n!Rich Farmer\n| 3.1|| 5.3|| 6.4|| 25.1|| 114.86\n|-\n!Landlord\n| 2.4|| 2.6|| 2.2|| 12.2|| 23.19\n|-\n!Other\n| 0.7|| --|| --|| --|| --\n|-\n!Total\n| 100.00|| 100.00|| 100.00|| 15.3|| 64.01\n|}\n\n==== Economic effects ====\n[[file:Visit to the People's Commune named Chinese-Hungarian Friendship-3.jpg|thumb|right|An example of a people's commune collective farm.]]\nHistorian [[Walter Scheidel]] writes that the violence of the land reform campaign had a significant impact on [[economic inequality]]. He gives as an example the village of Zhangzhuangcun, made famous by [[William H. Hinton|William Hinton]]'s book ''[[Fanshen]]'': {{quote|In Zhangzhuangcun, in the more thoroughly reformed north of the country, most \"landlords\" and \"rich peasants\" had lost all their land and often their lives or had fled. All formerly landless workers had received land, which eliminated this category altogether. As a result, \"middling peasants,\" who now accounted for 90 percent of the village population, owned 90.8 percent of the land, as close to perfect equality as one could possibly hope for.<ref name=Scheidel226>{{cite book | last =Scheidel | first =Walter | author-link =Walter Scheidel | title =The Great Leveler: Violence and the History of Inequality from the Stone Age to the Twenty-First Century | publisher =[[Princeton University Press]] | location = | year =2017 | isbn =978-0-691-16502-8 | url =http://press.princeton.edu/titles/10921.html | page =226 | access-date =2017-09-03 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20170904231557/http://press.princeton.edu/titles/10921.html | archive-date =2017-09-04 | url-status =live }}</ref>}}\n\nBy 1958 private ownership was entirely abolished and households all over China were forced into state-operated communes. Chinese leadership insisted that the communes must produce more grain for the cities and earn foreign exchange from exports. These reforms were generally unpopular with the peasants and usually implemented by summoning them to meetings and making them stay there for days and sometimes weeks until they \"voluntarily\" agreed to join the collective.\n\n==== Great Leap Forward ====\n\nDuring the [[Great Leap Forward]], the state introduced a system of compulsory state purchases of grain at fixed prices to build up stockpiles for famine-relief and meet the terms of its trade agreements with the [[Soviet Union]]. Together, taxation and compulsory purchases accounted for 30% of the harvest by 1957, leaving very little surplus.<ref>Mirsky, Jonathan. \"[http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2009/feb/26/the-china-we-dont-know/ The China We Don't Know] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016120725/http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2009/feb/26/the-china-we-dont-know/ |date=2015-10-16 }}.\" New York Review of Books Volume 56, Number 3. February 26, 2009.</ref> Rationing was also introduced in the cities to curb 'wasteful consumption' and encourage savings (which were deposited in state-owned banks and thus became available for investment), and although food could be purchased from state-owned retailers the market price was higher than that for which it had been purchased. This too was done in the name of discouraging excessive consumption.\n\nDuring 1958\u20131960 China continued to be a substantial net exporter of grain, despite the widespread famine experienced in the countryside, as Mao sought to maintain face and convince the outside world of the success of his plans. Foreign aid was refused. When the Japanese foreign minister told his Chinese counterpart Chen Yi of an offer of 100,000 tonnes of wheat to be shipped out of public view, he was rebuffed. [[John F. Kennedy]] was also aware that the Chinese were exporting food to Africa and Cuba during the famine and said \"we've had no indication from the Chinese Communists that they would welcome any offer of food.\"<ref>{{cite|last= Dik\u00f6tter|first = Frank|title =Mao's Great Famine: The History of China's Most Devastating Catastrophe, 1958-62|place = London| publisher = Bloomsbury| year =2010 |ref= harv}}, p. = [https://books.google.com/books?id=nuKoQeYTGRMC&pg=PA115&lpg=PA115&dq=japanese+foreign+minister+told+his+Chinese+counterpart+Chen+Yi+of+an+offer+of+100,000+tonnes+of+wheat&source=bl&ots=BGb-UJXDLq&sig=ACfU3U0icQ09IwgUFMxCzlsYCPMxFAMwSQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjx2d-QgdrlAhUHPq0KHcenA4QQ6AEwC3oECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=japanese%20foreign%20minister%20told%20his%20Chinese%20counterpart%20Chen%20Yi%20of%20an%20offer%20of%20100%2C000%20tonnes%20of%20wheat&f=false 114\u2013115].</ref> With dramatically reduced yields, even urban areas suffered much reduced rations; however, mass starvation was largely confined to the countryside, where, as a result of drastically inflated production statistics, very little grain was left for the peasants to eat.\n\n==Land reform in Taiwan==\n{{main|Land Reform in Taiwan}}\nAfter its retreat to Taiwan, the Nationalist government carried out a program of land reform under the [[Joint Commission on Rural Reconstruction]].<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=MacFaquhar|editor1-first=Roderick|editor2-last=Fairbank|editor2-first=John K.|title=The People's Republic.|date=1991|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge [Cambridgeshire]|isbn=9780521243377 |author-last=Clough |author-first=Ralph |chapter=Chapter 12: Taiwan under Nationalist Rule, 1949-1982 |page=837 |ref=none}}</ref> The [[land reform]] law removed the landlord class, and created a higher number of peasants who, with the help of the [[sovereign state|state]], dramatically increased Taiwan's agricultural output.<ref name=\"historycooperative.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://historycooperative.org/journal/the-labour-movement-in-taiwan/|title=The Labour Movement in Taiwan|date=September 21, 2004|access-date=November 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021063230/https://historycooperative.org/journal/the-labour-movement-in-taiwan/|archive-date=October 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Land reform also succeeded because the [[Kuomintang]]'s members were mostly from [[mainland China]] and as a result, they had few ties with the remaining indigenous Taiwanese landowners.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.landreform.org.tw/html/01.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725231354/http://www.landreform.org.tw/html/01.htm |archivedate=2011-07-25 |trans-title=Land Reform Museum |script-title=zh:\u571f\u5730\u6539\u9769\u7d00\u5ff5\u9928 |language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Collectivization in the Soviet Union]]\n* [[Dekulakization]]\n* [[Land reform by country]]\n* [[Land reform in Vietnam]]\n* [[Mass killings under communist regimes]]\n* [[Socialist ideology of the Kuomintang]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography and further reading==\n{{Library resources box}}\n\n* {{cite journal| url =http://www.fao.org/3/x1372t/x1372t10.htm |title = Land reform in rural China since the mid-1980s| author1-first = Fu |author1-last = Chen|author2-first = John |author2-last = Davis|publisher = Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations| year = 1998|journal = Land Reform|ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1 = Crook|first1 = Isabel|first2 = David|last2 = Crook|year = 1979|title = Ten Mile Inn: Mass Movement in a Chinese Village|7 = |publisher = Pantheon Books|location = New York|isbn = 0394411781|ref = harv|url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/tenmileinnmassmo0000croo}}\n*{{cite book |last = DeMare |first=Brian James  |year = 2019 |title = Land Wars: The Story of China's Agrarian Revolution |publisher = Stanford University Press| location = Palo Alto, CA |isbn = 9781503609525|ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book |last = Hinton|first = William  |year = 1966 |title = Fanshen: A Documentary of Revolution in a Chinese Village | |publisher = Monthly Review Press| location = New York |isbn = |ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book |last = Li |first = Huaiyin |year = 2011 |title = Village China under Socialism and Reform : A Micro History, 1948-2008 | |publisher = Stanford University Press| location = Stanford, Calif.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Re4YLsESWjoC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&printsec=frontcover#v= |isbn = 0804776571|ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book |last = Moise  |first = Edwin E. |year = 1983 |title = Land Reform in China and North Vietnam : Consolidating the Revolution at the Village Level | |publisher = University of North Carolina Press| location = Chapel Hill |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Land_Reform_in_China_and_North_Vietnam/lAg1DgAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=moise+land+reform&printsec= |isbn = |ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book |last = M\u00fchlhahn  |first =  Klaus|year = 2019 |title = Making China Modern: From the Great Qing to Xi Jinping |publisher = Harvard University Press| location = Cambridge, Massachusetts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uxN-DwAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v= |isbn = |ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book |last = Shue |first=Vivienne |year = 1980 |title = Peasant China in Transition: The Dynamics of Development toward Socialism, 1949-1956  |publisher = University of California Press| location = Berkeley, CA|url=https://archive.org/details/peasantchinaintr0000shue |url-access = registration |isbn = 9780520037342|ref = none}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://chineseposters.net/themes/land-reform.php Land Reform and Collectivization (1950-1953)] Posters from the Stephan Landsberger collection. There are other posters on the topic in other sections of the site.\n\n[[Category:Political repression in China]]\n[[Category:Campaigns of the Communist Party of China]]\n[[Category:Communist repression]]\n[[Category:Political and cultural purges]]\n[[Category:Massacres in China]]\n[[Category:Human rights abuses]]\n[[Category:Class discrimination]]\n[[Category:Cold War history of China]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1947]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1948]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1949]]\